<HEADLINE>
`THE RIVER OF GOLD': OVERHETED PASSION, BETRAYAL AND DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 .1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mixing the mystical and the literal as it relates its
tale of guilt, lust and betrayal, the Portuguese film ``The River
of Gold'' ends by hurling itself over the rapids of reason into an
overheated, quasi-operatic frenzy of blood and union in death.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion, as one character repeatedly daubs herself in the
blood of her murdered husband and another swims underwater toward
her dead lover, is more suggestive of uncertain control than of a
firmly conceived resolution of the film's portents and passions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Paulo Rocha's seething melodrama is characterized by
sharply etched characters, fine performances and peaceful riverside
settings that lend the film a dreamy quality in sharp contrast with
its relentless atmosphere of impending violence.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, voices are heard singing of a horrible crime,
and the young women who wash their clothes at the bank of the river
sing of passion, murder, blood and cuckoldry.
</P>
<P>
   The principal characters are Antonio (Lima Duarte), the
past-his-prime dredger who takes Carolina (Isabel Ruth), a
middle-aged railroad crossing guard, as his wife at the outset of
the film. Carolina comes with plenty of baggage: a wandering eye,
guilt about a deadly act of vengeance, and her young niece, Melita
(Joana Barcia), whom Antonio saves from drowning. Melita could be
described as nubile, except that she is pregnant by Joao (Filipe
Cochofel), a womanizer who already has a wife.
</P>
<P>
   And when Carolina takes Melita on a train trip to Oporto to see
a doctor, they encounter a Gypsy who calls himself Ze of Gold (Jose
Mario Branco), who is so troubled by what he senses about Melita
that he flees their compartment, though not without leaving behind
a gold necklace from his case of wares.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Ze will arrive to conduct some sinister business in
the town where the other major characters live, to reveal secrets
and to bed women, and the stage will be set for rage and jealousy
and fate to write an overheated end to ``The River of Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   The film will be shown at 3 p.m. Saturday at Alice Tully Hall as
part of the 36th New York Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE RIVER OF GOLD'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Paulo Rocha; written (in Portuguese, with English
subtitles) by Rocha and Claudia Tomaz, based on an idea by Rocha;
director of photography, Elso Roque; edited by Jose Edgar Feldman;
music by Jose Mario Branco; production designers, Alberto Pessimo
and Jorge Goncalves; produced by Rocha and Bruno Stroppiana. Shown
with a three-minute short, Ondrej Rudavsky's ``Shaman,'' Saturday
at 3 p.m. at Alice Tully Hall as part of the 36th New York Film
Festival. Running time: 103 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Isabel Ruth (Carolina), Lima Duarte (Antonio), Joana
Barcia (Melita), Antonio Capelo (Joaquim), Filipe Cochofel (Joao)
and Jose Mario Branco (Ze).
</P>
</TEXT>
