<HEADLINE>
GM RUNS THE SHOW TO SPREAD ITS MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mich.)   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ People used to go to auto shows to see new car
models from all companies and then to a particular dealer to
test-drive the one they liked. Now General Motors, eager to regain
market share, is trying a new way to sell cars; it is putting on
its own one-company auto shows, where visitors can take test
drives, to raise the chance that when the customer goes to a
dealer, it will belong to GM.
</P>
<P>
   When the world's largest industrial corporation gets its act
together and takes it on the road, it is a giant road show _ 150
cars and trucks, including 50 different GM brands; a 60,000
square-foot air-conditioned tent; six half-mile test tracks, and
150 people to run the show, with a catering crew that serves a
choice of four free entrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the world's biggest, most aggressive, in-your-face test
program,'' said Phil Guarascio, a GM vice president and general
manager for marketing and advertising. But it was only a road test,
and none of the cars were for sale. There were no dealers here,
only a data base to match shoppers with dealers in their
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The company first tried the idea, which it calls Auto Show in
Motion, in July at Denver's old airport, Stapleton. Then came here,
to the huge parking lots of the USAir Arena on the Beltway east of
Washington for four days in September; the next stop was Tustin,
Calif., near Los Angeles, for four days ending Sunday. If the
multimillion dollar experiment works, it could be repeated in 50
cities across the country, company executives say.
</P>
<P>
   The company had an 18-stop tour laid out before last summer's
strike; now it plans to re-evaluate after Los Angeles and decide
whether to do more.
</P>
<P>
   A key measure of success will come in November when it resurveys
the people who came to the Denver event. Among a sample interviewed
before the show by GM, 35 percent said they were likely to buy a
General Motors car; after, 85 percent said they were likely to,
according to company officials. The next survey will find out how
many actually did.
</P>
<P>
   And GM, working with Visual Services, a marketing company in
Livonia, Mich., and other marketing consultants, plans to resurvey
them six months after the event and a year after.
</P>
<P>
   The sales targets are what GM calls ``conquest owners,'' people
who own a Ford Taurus, Toyota Camry or other non-General Motors
vehicle that is ripe for replacement. Part of the strategy was to
let people drive GM vehicles and the competitors' vehicles of the
same class, so the company hauled in a Taurus and a Camry, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea was simply to make people excited about GM, so the
company invited tens of thousands of people, through a direct-mail
campaign and displayed everything from the modestly priced compact
Chevrolet Prizm to the full-size sport utility Suburban. There were
even two copies of the EV-1, the electric car, which the company
markets only in Arizona and California.
</P>
<P>
   People lined up to drive the electrics and all other kinds of
cars, but the longest lines were for Corvette sports cars and Trans
Ams, Pontiac's power version of the Firebird. There were many more
Corvette drivers than potential Corvette buyers, but that was fine
with GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been to a dealer lately, you really appreciate this.
Dealers make you give them your first-born child before they let
you take out a Trans Am,'' said Fred McGrath Jr. of Fort
Washington, Md., who runs a family real estate company and was
visiting the show with his wife and his father.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath said he really was in the market for a Trans Am; he
already owns five. The show personnel were more knowledgeable than
the staff at dealerships, he said, where ``80 or 90 percent of
salespeople don't want to sit down and talk to you.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McGrath's wife, Cindy Costenbader, was also impressed. ``If you
had fun, you'd think about GM,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other shoppers got to try maneuvers they said would turn a
dealer livid. Barbara Gershberg, a real estate agent from Potomac,
Md., tried out an Oldsmobile Intrigue GL on a track that featured a
curve, marked by orange plastic cones, that was covered with sand.
The idea was to hit the brakes in the middle of the gritty turn and
see how well the anti-lock system performed.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Gershberg, who acknowledged that this was her first
time on a test track, kept hitting the brakes too early, 30 feet
before the sand, to avoid the hazard entirely. So her husband told
her to drive the course a second time, and once again she hit the
brakes too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Mrs. Gershberg said, ``it's kind of neat.''
</P>
<P>
   She left with a computer printout comparing the Olds to a Toyota
Camry LE; the Camry itself was available for a comparison drive
around the same course.
</P>
<P>
   That is part of GM's strategy, said Michael Wright, marketing
services manager at Oldsmobile. ``They're very impressed we have
the guts to put ours against theirs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another man shopping at the show, Thomas Schultz of Alexandria,
Va., said he liked the atmosphere and that it gave him a more
favorable impression of GM ``You go to a dealership, and all they
see is dollar signs in your eyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Diane saw a shorter-term strategy for the company.
``It's an ingenious way to get rid of the 98's,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
