<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK, IN THE ROLE OF THE STARTER . . . FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The New York Jets prepared Friday for life
without running back Curtis Martin, whose thigh injury will
probably sideline him for Sunday's game against the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's absence would be critical because quarterback Glenn
Foley is coming back from a rib-cartilage injury after missing two
games. A strong running game, which a healthy Martin could help
deliver, would ease the pressure on any quarterback _ especially
one who has not played in almost a month. Martin has been averaging
almost 130 yards a game in total offense, including consecutive
100-yard rushing performances as the Jets won their last two games
with Vinny Testaverde at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells has said that if Martin is unavailable and
he still needs a featured back, Richie Anderson will fill that
role. Anderson was the Jets' fullback in 1996, running 47 times for
150 yards and catching 44 passes for 385 yards. But he became a
backup last season. This year his situation is even more tenuous,
and he was not even in uniform the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said he was not asking, and no one told him, whether he
would start in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get caught up in asking if I'm playing or not,'' he
said. ``If you don't get the answer you want, then you get caught
up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Anderson's recent inactivity have anything to do with his
missing a tackle in Week 2, when the Ravens' Jermaine Lewis
returned a punt for a touchdown? ``It may,'' Anderson said. ``What
do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   That was as much of an opinion as he was willing to offer. The
thoughtful former Penn State star said he approaches each week the
same, whether or not he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year you're a starter, and when you're in a backup role
this year, you've got to be a pro,'' said Anderson, who is Penn
State's fourth-leading career scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in preseason this year, when Martin was sidelined with a
hamstring injury, Anderson produced runs of 66 and 83 yards. Over
all, he picked up 149 yards in 25 carries over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells ran practice by committee this week. Anderson saw
action along with the versatile Leon Johnson. But Parcells has said
he wants to limit Johnson to about 35 plays a game _ half of them
on offense _ even though Johnson has produced the longest running
and receiving plays for the Jets this year. He will remain a
stalwart on special teams, returning punts and kickoffs as well as
covering kicks.
</P>
<P>
   If Parcells partly saved Johnson for special teams and if Martin
were unavailable, Anderson would be the Jets' big back Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to know the game as much as possible,'' Anderson said.
``I try to be a student.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he feel, though, when he is the backup and in an
uncertain role? ``I don't make anything out of not starting,'' he
said. ``It starts messing with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is thinking about another game after Sunday's, though.
He wonders, is it better for Martin to take a week off? ``If this
Sunday is the last week of the season, he plays,'' the coach said.
``But I don't want to set anyone back.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially, he did not have to add, with the Patriots as the
Jets' next opponent. Parcells and Martin reached the Super Bowl
with New England two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   While some of the Rams' players, and even some coaches, were
complaining about his long summertime practices and meetings, coach
DICK VERMEIL called BILL PARCELLS to ask how he did things. ``I
talked to him off and on last year and in the off season and
everything else,'' Vermeil said. ``So that was not out of the
ordinary communication. You sort of need a couple of guys'
shoulders to cry on in the business once in a while.'' Parcells
said their discussions centered on the length of practices and how
often players worked out in full pads. ``I told him his practices
weren't that much different from mine or some other coaches,''
Parcells said. So what Vermeil was doing was no big deal? ``When
you don't win, it's always an issue,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   _ TERRY DAY, the defensive lineman who had knee surgery after an
off-season basketball injury, will began practice next week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Jets have not played a regular-season game in St. Louis
since 1971, when the Cardinals were there. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
