<HEADLINE>
CORNERBACK IS A CONCERN FOR GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Entering the season, Jason Sehorn and
Phillippi Sparks figured to make cornerback a position of strength
for the New York Giants. It is now a position in flux.
</P>
<P>
   Sehorn is out for the season, having had knee surgery, and the
Giants said Friday that it was not likely Sparks, who has an
injured shoulder, would play in Sunday night's nationally televised
game against the Atlanta Falcons at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, who has not practiced all week, was to have a magnetic
resonance imaging test Friday afternoon on his right shoulder. The
injury, which occurred when Sparks made a tackle during the Giants'
loss to Tampa Bay last Sunday, was originally considered a bruise.
The Giants do not have any serious, long-term concerns about
Sparks' condition, but since he has not improved as rapidly as the
team expected, more tests were ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how serious it is,'' Sparks said. ``It hurts. I
know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Gray, who started 58 National Football League games when
he was with the Seattle Seahawks and the Indianapolis Colts, will
start if Sparks cannot play. Conrad Hamilton has been starting in
Sehorn's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Gray immediately assumed a role in the nickel defenses. He had
an interception in the Giants' victory over San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before Phillippi got hurt, I viewed myself as a
starter,'' Gray, 27, said Friday. ``I look at it as us having three
starters, four if you count Jeremy Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, another cornerback the Giants signed as a free agent
over the winter, is a former starter for the Chicago Bears. If
Sparks is out Sunday, Lincoln will see time in the nickel packages.
Lincoln has been used sparingly by the Giants, who said they were
disappointed by his performances in the preseason. Lincoln would be
pressed into service in the nickel defense because the rookie
safety Shaun Williams has a hamstring injury and is not expected to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Also, defensive tackle Robert Harris, who has a strained chest
muscle, is listed as doubtful for the game. And safety Sam Garnes,
who has a foot injury, is still limping; he is listed as
questionable. Guard Ron Stone, who has a bruised tailbone, is also
questionable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not all the injury news for the Giants on Friday was bad. The
nickel linebacker Scott Galyon, who missed the last two games
because of a sore Achilles' heel, practiced all week and should
return Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With Galyon back, the Giants can rest Jessie Armstead more often
if Armstead's sprained right ankle bothers him. But Armstead also
had a full week of practice and said his ankle feels better than it
had since he sustained the injury in the season-opening game Sept.
6 against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Armstead and a number of Giants said they were viewing Sunday
night's game as a chance to redeem themselves. ``The last time we
were on national TV, we looked pretty bad,'' said Armstead,
referring to the Giants' 31-7 loss to Dallas in a Monday night game
Sept. 21. ``You want to look good when everybody's watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel said he was concerned his team may have been
distracted by the national television exposure in the game against
the Cowboys. Thirty-two players on the Giants active roster had
never played on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to tell them before this game that we're still
playing, but they've canceled the national television broadcast,''
Fassel said. ``A lot of these guys hadn't played on national
television before, and we didn't play too well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to be motivated to redeem ourselves for the last
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel did say he hopes the national spotlight will put a charge
in the Giants Stadium crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our fans know that when they get loud, we get a little
juiced up,'' Fassel said. ``And right now, coming off a loss, we
need to get a little juiced up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
