<HEADLINE>
DEVILS STILL TRYING TO PLUG GAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Jersey Devils begin the future Saturday night by
immediately confronting the past. They will be in Chicago to open
the 1998-99 season against the Chicago Blackhawks, who hope to get
a big year out of Doug Gilmour, a key player for the Devils until
he switched sides in the off-season after getting an $18 million
offer from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour's departure has left the Devils with something of a void
at center. The Devils have also been searching for an adequate
replacement for Scott Niedermayer, their most creative and skillful
defenseman, who is an unsigned restricted free agent. Niedermayer's
absence will be more evident because Lyle Odelein will also be
missing on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Odelein was given permission by the team to remain in Cincinnati
with his 5-month-old daughter, Paulina, who underwent surgery this
week to alleviate a breathing problem caused by extra cartilage in
her epiglottis, a flap that folds back over the opening of the
windpipe during swallowing, thus preventing food from entering the
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martin Brodeur practiced Friday after missing work a
day earlier because of a groin problem, it is uncertain whether he
will play. Randy McKay and Vadim Sarifijanov are also nursing groin
problems and are out. Sarifijanov joined Jason Arnott (broken
finger) on injured reserve Friday, when the Devils brought their
opening-day roster to 23 by assigning forward John Madden to
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   One highlight of Saturday night's game will come at the opening
faceoff, when the Chicago Cubs' Sammy Sosa drops the first puck.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, who finished second to Mark McGwire in baseball's home run
race this season, will be presented with a Blackhawks jersey before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackhawks' game comes at the beginning of what figures to
be a busy off-season for Sosa. Earlier this week he was invited to
speak in front of the Chicago City Council and appeared on ``The
Tonight Show with Jay Leno.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
