<SLUG> BC-AUTO-WINSTON-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD TITLE NOT A CINCH FOR GORDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ To win his second straight Winston Cup
championship and his third in six years, Jeff Gordon doesn't need
to win a race, he just needs to finish fifth or better in each of
the season's final five races.
</P>
<P>
   But considering the time of year, that could be tough for
Gordon, who leads Mark Martin by 174 points in the title chase.
Gordon has never won a race in October or November, averaging a
15th-place finish in those months.
</P>
<P>
   For Martin to pass Gordon, he needs to win a race in which
Gordon has a wreck or a poor finish. Martin needs a race like
Sunday's Winston 500 at Talladega, where avoiding the big accident
is the only strategy.
</P>
<P>
   This year's stretch run figures to be exciting. Gordon, in a
Chevrolet, qualified sixth (194.153 miles per hour) Friday and
Martin, in a Ford, was eighth (194.058).
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader won the pole, driving his Chevy around the
2.66-mile oval at 196.153 mph. Bobby Labonte, in a Pontiac, was
second (195.985) and Dale Jarrett, in a Ford, was third (195.031).
</P>
<P>
   Five drivers _ Gordon, Jeff Burton, Dale Jarrett, Dale Earnhardt
and Jeremy Mayfield _ will be going for the Winston $1 million
bonus on Sunday. In four chances, Gordon has won the bonus twice
(Indianapolis and Darlington). ``We're excited about it,'' Gordon
said. ``If we're up there, we're going for the million dollars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
