<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FORMER WINNERS TO COMPETE IN NYC MARATHON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first Swiss runner and the first South African
runner to win the New York City Marathon will both be competing in
the event again Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Franziska Rochat-Moser of Switzerland will defend the women's
title she earned last year with a time of 2 hours 28 minutes 43
seconds. The 32-year-old Rochat-Moser, a lawyer and restaurant
owner who has won 15 marathons, finished ahead of Colleen de Rueck
by 28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Giacomo Leone, the women's winner two years ago, will not be
back.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Mtolo of South Africa, who won the men's race in 1992 by
overtaking Andres Espinosa of Mexico near the finish, also will
return. Mtolo has not raced much since he ran 44th in the 1994
marathon.
</P>
<P>
   His victory in 1992 marked the first year that Mtolo ran outside
South Africa, whose athletes were banned internationally for many
years when the country followed a policy of enforced racial
separation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
