<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SIMPSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOKE SIMPSON, 83, FORMER DEAN OF BUSINESS SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hoke Simpson, a former associate dean at the Graduate
School of Business at Columbia University, died on Sept. 26 at
United Hospital in Port Chester. Simpson, a resident of Rye, was
83.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was lung disease, said his daughter, Drayton
Jenkins Gerety.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson joined the business school as the director of executive
programs in 1954 and was promoted to associate dean for executive
education in 1967. The executive education program, which is part
of the business school, is a series of one- to four-week non-degree
courses for executives, including those in management, finance,
leadership and marketing. Courses are sometimes custom-designed for
private companies.
</P>
<P>
   When Simpson joined the business school, its executive education
division was just starting. He helped develop a wide range of
business courses, and during his tenure the school had programs in
New York, France, Spain and South America. He retired in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   After he graduated from the Georgia Institute of Technology in
1935 with a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering and
industrial management, Simpson went to work as a salesman for
General Foods Corp. During a 16-year career at General Foods,
except for a six-year stint with the Naval Reserve, Simpson worked
in the marketing, personnel and labor-relations divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Columbia University, Simpson worked for Vick
Chemical Co. as director of personnel and public relations.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson is survived by his wife, Suzanne, of Rye; his daughter,
of Mamaroneck; two sons, Hoke Jr., of San Diego, and Willis, of
Asheville, N.C.; seven grandchildren, and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
