<HEADER>
A9805 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-ASSIGNMENT-SHARES-     10-10 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-ASSIGNMENT-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY CEO, ANALYSTS STILL UPBEAT ABOUT COMPANY'S OUTLOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It's been a rough couple of weeks for On
Assignment Inc. Shares in the temporary staffing firm have fallen
37.8 percent since Sept. 30., slipping from $37 to $23 at the close
of trading Friday. So why is Chief Executive Officer Tom Buelter
happy? Likely because his competitors have suffered even more, in
some cases losing twice as much of their market capitalization as
Los Angeles-based On Assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find me in the greatest mood -- absolutely no worries,''
Buelter said Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are bullish on the company, too. Five rate it a ``buy''
and four recommend holding onto its stock. None has come out with a
``sell'' call on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great company and will, I think, do really well,'' A.G.
Edwards analyst Laura Browder said. Said another analyst, ``They
came out better than most.''
</P>
<P>
   What On Assignment has going for it over a ManPower, Administaff
or Remedy Temp is focus, analysts say. Through three divisions --
Lab Support, Healthcare Financial Staffing and Envirostaff -- the
company places temporary professional workers into jobs in the
sciences, medical, and food and beverage industries.
</P>
<P>
   While other firms place a spectrum of staffers, from
administrative to executive, into any company that comes calling,
On Assignment draws commissions almost entirely from professionals
who, happily, tend to pull far heftier paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   What has hurt On Assignment -- and virtually all other publicly
traded staffing companies -- is concern that despite the best
attempts of Alan Greenspan, the U.S. economy is recession-bound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thinking is that while things are first slowing down and
you're going into a recession, it'll be the temporary people who
are laid off first,'' Browder said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing such concern, Little Rock-based Stephens Inc. downgraded
the entire staffing industry Oct. 1, in part explaining the
sell-off in On Assignment stock.
</P>
<P>
   But Buelter said that in the long run, his firm and others in
the sector see increased business in an economic downturn, as
companies reluctant to make permanent hires rely increasingly on
temporary staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncertainty is an advantage in our business,'' Buelter said.
</P>
<P>
   With steady annual growth of 20 to 25 percent in revenues and 35
to 40 percent in earnings (the company made $12.38 million last
year on sales of $107.84 million), Buelter said On Assignment will
overcome the latest depression in its stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is one American investor or one stock
today that is better off than in July,'' he said. ``But we have no
debt; we've got $35 million cash in the bank ... I'm not really
worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
