<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS, COLON HUMBLE YANKEES, 6-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The New York Yankees' 114 victories this season will
mean nothing if baseball's best team does not advance to the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   That became a distinct possibility last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians _ Central Division champions and overwhelming
underdogs in the American League Championship Series _ moved within
two victories of their third World Series berth since 1995 with
last night's 6-1 triumph at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians lead the best-of-seven series two games to one, and
that bodes well for manager Mike Hargrove's ballclub. History
reveals that the winner of Game 3 advanced to the World Series nine
of 12 times after opponents split games 1 and 2 of the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this team believes in itself,'' said Indians first
baseman Jim Thome, who drove in three runs on the strength of his
second- and fifth-inning home runs. ``We knew coming into this
series that the Yankees were the team to beat and really have been
the team to beat all year with what they did during the regular
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Bartolo Colon, who surrendered only four hits and
four walks for the victory, threw the first complete game in ALCS
play since former White Sox left-hander Wilson Alvarez during their
1993 series against the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   This evening, though, belonged to the Indians' sleeping giant.
</P>
<P>
   Thome, whose second-inning, solo home run gave the Indians' a
1-0 lead, ensured the victory with his two-run, fifth-inning homer
off left-hander Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   The affable, left-handed power hitter struggled throughout
September and this postseason since his return from the 15-day
disabled list. Thome suffered a fracture to his right hand Aug. 7
after being hit by a pitch thrown by Alvarez, now with the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   Thome returned Sept. 16, but the first baseman hit .195
(8-for-41) with 15 strikeouts and only one home and three runs
batted in during the remainder of the season. The postseason
continued to be unkind to Thome, who entered last night's game
hitting .130 (3-for-23) with nine strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a palm reader yesterday, and she told me ... No, Jimmy
is a good hitter,'' Hargrove said. ``You look at his career stats
and you see what he's done year in and year out, and he's normally
a very good, consistent hitter throughout the season. I feel the
broken hand caused him to be a little inconsistent the last two
weeks of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome's second home run gave the Indians a 5-1 lead and
highlighted their four-run fifth inning in which right fielder
Manny Ramirez and left fielder Mark Whiten also hit solo home runs
with Pettitte on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Whiten's 416-foot blast signaled the end for Pettitte, who fell
prey to the big inning once again this season. Opponents victimized
Pettitte for four or more runs in a single inning a league-high 10
times during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of leaving too many pitches out over the
plate,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``I thought he had it
straightened out after the second inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Yankees' offense _ which this season led the
major leagues in runs scored _ continues to be kept in check. The
Yankees have scored only 18 runs through their six postseason
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we just got kicked tonight, and there's frustration in
that,'' Torre said. ``We're not scoring any runs. I think everybody
is a little frustrated with that fact alone.''
</P>
<P>
   That frustration will run much deeper without a World Series
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Indians appear confident, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We protect against overconfidence,'' Hargrove said, ``because
you don't give us any credit for being here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
