</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-THOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOME'S SLUMP ENDS WITH A COUPLE OF BLASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Several hours before the American League
Championship Series began on Tuesday, all the Cleveland Indians
were corralled in their clubhouse before batting practice. All but
one. Jim Thome kept pacing the corridor beneath Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``How cold is it out there, Cleveland-like cold?'' he asked a
few hallway loiterers.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to pace while whirling a bat in his hand until it
was the Indians' turn at batting practice. As Thome stood on the
field, with the red-white-and-blue bunting in the background, he
looked around and displayed a smile as big as a half moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it is all about,'' Thome said. ``You cannot beat
this.''
</P>
<P>
   His enthusiasm was pure as he began this series, and it never
wavered, no matter how disappointing his at-bats. Even after he
struck out once in Game 1 and three times in Game 2, he refused to
get frustrated or uptight and kept on swinging freely until
something connected in Game 3 against the Yankees Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thome wheeled his sturdy frame and made contact with two Andy
Pettitte fastballs, both of which ended up over the wall and into a
roaring crowd in right field at Jacobs Field. Thome's two home runs
_ one a solo shot estimated at 421 feet in the second inning, the
other a two-run rainbow estimated at 369 feet in the fifth inning _
put the Indians firmly in control to win Game 3, 6-1, and they
helped provide Cleveland with a 2-1 lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I've been having a hard time with left-handed
pitching lately,'' said Thome, whose right hand was fractured by a
pitch on Aug. 7, causing him to miss a month of playing time.
``They've been trying to establish the fastball inside. I was
fortunate tonight to get ahead in the count and get a good pitch to
hit. I've been having such a hard time lately that it wasn't on my
mind to hit two home runs. I was just trying to put it in play.''
</P>
<P>
   This is as good as Thome has looked since returning to the
lineup on Sept. 16. He finished the last 12 games of the season
hitting .195 with one home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a palm reader, so I knew,'' manager Mike Hargrove joked
when asked if he knew Thome was ready to break out. ``No, Jimmy is
a good hitter. Look over his career and see what he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome has always had a knack for the home run. In the fifth
inning, his second homer barely crept over the wall in right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Paul O'Neill was going back, I didn't know if it was
going,'' Thome said of the Yankee right fielder. ``I was trying to
blow it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome was one of three Indians to hit homers off Pettitte in the
fifth inning, which put the Indians ahead, 6-1. Manny Ramirez and
Mark Whiten joined Thome in their show of power. And it was a show,
all right, as Thome thrashed his way out of a 1-for-8 slump through
Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get good pitching like we have lately, it's
contagious,'' Thome said. ``The offense just relaxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome looked at ease despite his recent struggles as he tried to
get adjusted to swinging the bat with a pad on his healing hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, the pad wasn't really the problem,'' he said.
``It just felt like spring training all over again, especially
against left-hand pitching. The first week back, I was just trying
to get a feel for everything again. Hitting is about momentum and
getting good pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   After Cleveland's disastrous loss in Game 1 and its fluke-aided
victory in Game 2, no one could argue the merits of the Indians
victory in Game 3. Obviously, they are not daunted by the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the Yankees have been the team to beat,'' Thome said.
``For us, going in you have to bring your game to another level.
We've won because our pitching has put us in a situation where we
could win. After the first inning, you could see the momentum shift
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Thome sent up his first home run of the
night. It was a release of the nervous energy that he had been
building for hours before the series even began.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
