<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SHARON (JERUSALEM) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
appointed Ariel Sharon, a hawkish former defense minister, to be
foreign minister in a bid to placate the far right wing as he moves
closer to turning over more West Bank land to the Palestinians. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-AID (MOSCOW) _ Rocked by a poor harvest and a plummeting
ruble, Russia appealed for humanitarian aid from the West. By
Michael R. Gordon. (with graphic)
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-AID-GROUPS (KABUL, Afghanistan) _ Nearly three months
have passed since 23 international aid groups left this country
rather than obey a command to move their non-Afghan employees into
decrepit and abandoned dormitories at the capital's edge. The
international agencies had been supplying clean water and fresh
bread and medical necessities _ services that benefited 400,000
people, a third of the city's population. There is no one to take
their place. By Barry Bearak. (with map)
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-PRODI (ROME) _ By only one vote, the center-left prime
minister of Italy, Romano Prodi, lost a confidence vote in
parliament and was toppled from power. The collapse of his
government after two and a half years, making it the second-longest
to hold office since World War II, suggested that the chronic
political instability that marked Italy for decades has sprung back
to life. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (BELGRADE, Yugoslavia) _ U.S. envoy Richard
Holbrooke met with Yugoslav President Milosevic in a ``last-ditch''
effort to resolve the crisis in the ethnic-Albanian province of
Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-U.S. (WASHINGTON) _ German chancellor-elect Gerherd
Schroeder met with President Clinton. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-GAYS (Johannesburg) _ In landmark decision, South
Africa's highest court decriminalized gay sex. By Donald G. McNeil
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHIATRIST-BLAMED (CHAPEL HILL, N.C.) _ Wendell Williamson, an
inmate in a state psychiatric ward, has brought and recently won a
suit against a psychiatrist who had seen him just half a dozen
times eight months before he committed two killings. He claimed
that the doctor should pay him damages because he did not diagnose
him properly, did not explain how serious his illness was and did
not follow up after their sessions ended. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   WHITECOLLAR-DRUG-RING (NEW YORK) _ Law enforcement officials
announced the indictments Friday of 102 members of a sophisticated
drug operation that discreetly sold millions of dollars' worth of
crack cocaine to white-collar workers in midtown Manhattan. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   WYO-GAY-BEATING (LARAMIE, Wyo.) _ A gay student at the
University of Wyoming was savagely beaten, burned and left to die
outside Laramie. Three University of Wyoming students were arrested
with more arrests expected. Police were investigating whether the
brutal beating was motivated by the victim's sexual orientation. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GOV-RACE (NEW YORK) _ Although many Democratic candidates
across the country are uneasily keeping their beleaguered president
at arms' length, Peter Vallone, the Democratic candidate for
governor, is politically embracing Bill Clinton head on. By Amy
Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-GOV-RACE (MIAMI) _ The Florida governor's race: Buddy
MacKay, the Democratic lieutenant governor, is struggling to gain a
foothold against Jeb Bush, but the polls show a continuing double
digit lead for the Republican. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (WASHINGTON) _ Settling the question of what
kind of impeachment investigation the House of Representatives
wants did nothing to settle the partisan squabbling about how it
should be conducted, and Judiciary Committee members immediately
began arguing about a range of issues. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (WASHINGTON) _ Legislation to protect patients'
rights died Friday, a casualty of heavy lobbying by the insurance
industry and of the sex scandal that has enveloped President
Clinton. By Robert Pear. (with photo)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RELIGION (WASHINGTON) _ The Senate on Friday
unanimously approved a compromise bill that would require the
government to respond to countries that persecute its citizens for
their religious beliefs with measures ranging from the mildest
private rebuke to tough economic sanctions. The House then approved
it by a voice vote. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPECIES (WASHINGTON) _ Congress is considering
attaching a rewrite of the Endangered Species Act _ never voted on
by either House _ to the omnibus spending bill. By John H. Cushman
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LIVENT-DRABINSKY (Undated) _ Details of the fall of Garth
Drabinsky, former chief executive at the entertainment company
Livent. By Melody Petersen. (with photo)
</P>
<P>
   BANKING-LAWS (WASHINGTON) _ With a lone senator standing in the
way, a bill to overturn Depression-era restrictions on the
financial-services industry was put into a legislative deep-freeze
on Friday, its prospects for passage reduced to almost nothing. By
Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-YEN (TOKYO) _ The yen's sudden jump against the dollar
threatens to take the momentum out of Japan's export surge _ which
would make it more costly for Americans and Europeans to buy
Japanese products _ and could prolong Japan's worst postwar
recession. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND (Undated) _ Developments in the bailout of Long-Term
Capital Management. By Peter Turell.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKH-OIL (ALMATY, Kazakhstan) _ To the benefit of energy-rich
Kazakhstan, as foreign investment has drained from most emerging
markets and global crude prices have tumbled, the Caspian's stature
as the most prized oil property in the world remains high. By Steve
LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-DELAY (Washington) _ The judge hearing the Microsoft
case delayed the trial's start by four days, to Oct. 19, and
ordered Microsoft to give the government access to financial
database records. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ The 1990s model of high-flying self-made
zillionaire is as different from his 1980s predecessor as a fully
loaded Jeep is from a Porsche.
</P>
<P>
   But I wondered as I stood before a locked cabinet filled with
small bottles of balsamic vinegar that cost more than those vials
of coke Wall Street traders were snorting in the '80s. Is it
progress that our new rich can turn salad dressing into a status
symbol? By Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Ah, excuse me. I don't mean to
interrupt the fun Congress is having with its impeachment hearings
and all. But, well, there's just this little problem going on in
the rest of the world. It has to do with economics. By Thomas L.
Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ARATON-COLUMN (CLEVELAND) _ Suddenly, what is supposed to be
the greatest season in American League history is drifting on a
raft, like the one Orlando Hernandez rode out of Cuba. Suddenly, it
is the Cleveland Indians, not the Yankees, who look like the team
slated for the World Series. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-HERNANDEZ (CLEVELAND) _ Armed with a video camera,
Hernandez walked through the Tower City Mall here Friday, taping
sights and sounds for the benefit of his two young daughters living
in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, a Cuban defector, hopes that he has good reason to
send them videotape of his Game 4 start Saturday against the
Cleveland Indians and Dwight Gooden. By Buster Olney
</P>
<P>
   HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS (NEW YORK) _ Low-scoring hockey need not be
boring. The New York Rangers and the Philadelphia Flyers
demonstrated that Friday night at Madison Square Garden in their
energetic season opener.
</P>
<P>
   Although the show was entertaining for the loud capacity crowd,
the result was unsatisfying for the home fans as the Flyers headed
home with a 1-0 victory. By Joe Lapointe.
</P>
