   INTERNATIONAL (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CACASUS-PIPELINE (Washington) _ A two-year campaign by the
Clinton administration to persuade major oil companies that they
should quickly build a multi-billion-dollar pipeline in the
Caucasus, a campaign that has become a centerpiece of U.S. foreign
policy, appears to be on the brink of failure. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CONTROVERSIAL-CANONIZATION (Rome) _ At a Mass in St. Peter's
Square on Sunday, Pope John Paul II will pronounce Edith Stein, a
renowned Jewish intellectual who became a Carmelite nun and died at
Auschwitz, a saint and a martyr for the Roman Catholic faith. Edith
Stein, while undoubtedly a remarkable woman, is perhaps one of the
most contested choices for canonization of John Paul's pontificate,
which celebrates its 20th year next week. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   With:
</P>
<P>
   CANONIZATION-STEIN (Undated) _ The miracle that qualified Edith
Stein for sainthood began with the kind of thoroughly avoidable
childhood accident that haunts the imagination of every
conscientious parent. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CULT (Tokyo) _ The cult that planted nerve gas in the
Tokyo subway three years ago, killing 12 people and injuring
thousands more, is back. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDBANK-MEDIA (Washington) _ After surveying the Asian
financial crisis, the World Bank has decided that a strong and
independent news media could be an important protection against
economic mismanagement and government malfeasance in developing
nations. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-CONFLICT (Calamar, Colombia) _ The bloody struggle over
the future of Colombia, raging between shadowy groups of men and
women with masks and false names, is closing in on Calamar, a main
transit point in the coca trade scratched out of the jungle 20
years ago by the refugees of earlier conflicts in this stricken
country. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-AID (Nairobi, Kenya) _ In 1989, the world's governments
launched Operation Lifeline Sudan. Now, nearly a decade and more
than $2 billion later, the situation is virtually identical,
despite one of the largest relief operations ever. The expenditure
will grow endlessly, relief officials said this week, unless there
is an end to the war. And it does not please the donor governments
and relief agencies that rebel leaders have bluntly declared that
they expect the aid to continue so the war can. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WASH-VOTER-DISCONTENT (Longview, Wash.) _ There is no question
that voters are upset here in Washington, a state that has been a
particularly accurate electoral bellwether in recent years. But
three and a half weeks before Election Day, it is also clear that
many voters are not at all sure where to direct their anger. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENICIAN-SHIPS (Undated) _ The Phoenicians were the master
seafarers of antiquity, but modern scholarship knows little of the
vanished people and almost nothing of their empire's basis, its
merchant ships. Now, however, the cold depths of the Mediterranean
have yielded a bonanza that might change all that _ if
archeologists and treasure hunters can learn to work together. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   AIR&AMP;SPACE-ANNEX (Silver Hill, Md.) _ The Air and Space Museum
expects to complete design work next month on a giant new
exhibition hall at Washington Dulles International Airport, with
room for objects that would never fit anywhere else, including the
prototype space shuttle and an early model Boeing 707. By Matthew
L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-PENSIONLESS-COPS (Tuscaloosa, Ala.) _ In 1966, Willie Bies
Jr. became a police officer in this university city, assigned to
the poor black neighborhood on the west side where patrol cars were
often pelted with rocks. In 1991 Bies retired, becoming one of only
two Tuscaloosa police officers to work for 25 years without getting
a pension. Like the other officer, Herbert Harris, Bies is black.
The case of the two officers' fight for police pensions illustrates
how a third of a century after the civil rights movement extended
equal treatment under the law to all Americans, people employed
under the rules of the segregationist South are still battling for
justice. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   PIKES-PEAK-EROSION (Cascade, Colo.) _ Hiking below the
spectacular Pikes Peak Highway, Gail Snyder points out the
behind-the-scenes damage to the mountain. For decades, rain water
has drained unchecked off the gravel road leading to the
14,110-foot summit, carving gullies deep enough to swallow
ponderosa pines whole. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PODESTA-PROFILE (Washington) _ John David Podesta, the lean, wry
roller-coaster enthusiast who senior White House aides say is
likely to become their next chief of staff, keeps an unusual
photograph of President Clinton on his office wall. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   UNUSED-BOMB-DETECTORS (Washington) _ The Federal Aviation
Administration has spent more than $122 million on machines to
detect bombs in checked baggage, but those machines that have been
installed sit idle for most of the day, according to investigators
from the Department of Transportation. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ GOP cover story. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ FOBs: Femmes of Bill. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
