<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SCENE-450&AMP;AD     10-10 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SCENE-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CONGRESS, A BREAK IN A SEASON OF SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Miss., Va., Calif., Mass., Ga.) (jw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress savored the sheer comfort of asexual
political skirmishing this weekend as lawmakers struggled with lost
legislative causes and artificial doomsday deadlines in their
attempt to quit and go home to face the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sent here to talk about Monica Lewinsky,'' said Rep.
Dennis Kucinich, hurrying from committee room to House floor as the
leadership pushed, then failed, with a plan to finish by Sunday. He
darted about as the nation's lawmakers tried to disentangle
themselves from a harrowing closing week that was dominated by the
House's impeachment challenge to President Clinton even as other
issues wilted on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going home to talk health care, Social Security, jobs and
education,'' Kucinich, D-Ohio, insisted, radiating delight at the
hometown prospect of Monica-free vox pop, far from the madding
Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone numbed by the White House scandal, the last-minute
hagglings between and within the two houses in the Capitol was a
tonic in the closing days. Public debate can once more romp far
from the body politic's erogenous zones to topics like the usual
last-minute repriming of the federal budget, the length of the duck
season in Mississippi and the Sense of Congress Resolution
Concerning the Inadequacy of Sewage Infrastructure Facilities in
Tijuana, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The simple sight was bracing when two gangs of rival politicians
crossed each other's paths in the Capitol press gallery to fence
and parry over the patients health care bill, which was failing on
Friday even as the impeachment inquiry took off. They verbally
charged and countercharged beyond all grand-jury risk of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan scrum featured lighthearted exchanges of greetings
at the door, then hard stares of umbrage before the cameras. And
the only thing close to a document dump _ the lurid signature event
of the long presidential inquiry _ was a mere scrap of campaign
e-mail from the Democrats' health care arsenal, somehow purloined
by Republicans. Mercifully for this, no one demanded the
appointment of an e-mailgate independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, House members marked time at their rhetorical
oars with campaign themes while their leaders privately negotiated.
``A Do-Nothing Congress!'' came the debating charge to the
Republicans as Democrats sarcastically insisted that the session's
main accomplishment was the renaming of National Airport to Ronald
Reagan National Airport. David Dreier, R-Calif., smiled back in
rebuttal, spewing a long list of claimed accomplishments and
declaring, ``Guess what? The 105th Congress has the highest
approval rating of any Congress in recent history.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In their effort to escape the impeachment issue as much as the
session, the lawmakers' routine obligations seemed momentarily
ennobling. Tom DeLay of Texas, the Republican whip, had faced the
House in the impeachment debate on Thursday and morosely declared,
``I wish I could just ignore all this and make it go away.'' He
brightened considerably on the job by the next day when he took a
minute from the closing push to greet some Colorado schoolchidren.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders struggled to craft some sort of 105th denouement,
there were notes of poignancy in the fine print. Rep. Jay Kim,
R-Calif., who had suffered the ignominy of wearing an electronic
ankle bracelet in the Capitol in facing conviction for accepting
$250,000 in illegal campaign money, was duly pronounced guilty
under House ethics rules, too. But, already on probation and
rejected by primary voters, Kim was free of the people's business
after a six-year career.
</P>
<P>
   As the lawmakers sought to wind things down in the debating
chambers, Bob Scribner, an ebullient member of the Capitol Guide
Service, worked a floor below, fielding questions from weekend
visitors. Almost shyly, the subject of the president and the intern
and impeachment was occasionally broached, with a high school
student asking the guide if history points to how it will all turn
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what happens next,'' said Scribner, his
voice ringing in the stony majesty of the Capitol crypt. ``It's all
pretty much up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurrying through the House Rayburn office building, Martin
Meehan, D-Mass., rued the might-have-beens of this 105th Congress.
``The impeachment fight drained the energy from so many substantive
issues, and the most dramatic example was campaign finance
reform,'' he said as a frustrated co-sponsor of the campaign bill.
The measure passed the House with an unexpected surge, then
foundered as the public faced a summer flood of scandalous detail
about the presidential liaison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate killed reform without any fanfare,'' Meehan said.
``The president was handcuffed. The front pages were about Monica
Lewinsky. And the Senate didn't take any heat at all. We couldn't
even generate pressure on Al D'Amato,'' he said, underlining the
current campaign season, richer in contributions than ever. The
unmentioned advantage of Capitol incumbents eager to get home is
that the soft money levels have been quietly tripling over the last
congressional round, even as the nation's agenda is being set for
the impeachment struggle.
</P>
<P>
   For all the steely partisanship of the session, there were human
moments noted by lawmakers, even in Thursday's incendiary House
debate kicking off the impeachment inquiry. Members on both sides
of the aisle could be seen listening closely when Rep. Barney
Frank, D-Mass., conceded that the president lied but pleaded for
reprimand, not impeachment, as his punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, rarely accused of being humble, looked up at Speaker Newt
Gingrich presiding with the gavel and, in what could only have been
a painful moment, referred to the ethical lapses of both of them in
noting: ``Both the speaker and I have been reprimanded by this
House for lying before official proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank nodded peaceably toward the speaker and added, ``That has
not kept either of us from continuing to do our duty, to our best
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
