<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Hefty Charge Against Visa And Mastercard
</P>
<P>
   People who feel deprived of access to what now seems to be an
American right to buy on credit have a friend at the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the government filed an antitrust suit against Visa
and Mastercard, saying the nation's two biggest credit card
networks restrain competition and consumers' choices.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the lawsuit, Attorney General Janet Reno said
rules adopted by Visa and Mastercard for member banks were overly
restrictive, and therefore harmful to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Visa and Mastercard denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KENNETH N. GILPIN
</P>
<P>
   Dispute Over Nerve Gas  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   French experts detected traces of the nerve gas VX on Iraqi
warheads they examined but withheld their findings because they did
not want to damage Baghdad's efforts to have United Nations
economic sanctions lifted, according to several international
weapons specialists.
</P>
<P>
   France, which has major commercial interests in Iraq, officially
denied that it had found VX, or that it sought to help Iraq lift
the sanctions imposed after the Persian Gulf war. It asked the U.N.
commission investigating Iraq's weaponry to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Deaths Drop
</P>
<P>
   The federal government announced that 16,685 people died of AIDS
last year, less than half the number who succumbed in 1996, and a
stunning drop from the more than 43,000 in the peak year of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The drop was caused by the use of new drugs that can keep the
deadly disease at bay. But the number of people who annually become
infected by the HIV virus remains steady at about 40,000. So
accompanying the good news is a worry that infected people will be
living longer, giving them more chances to pass infections along.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN A. HOLMES &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Tales From the White House  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The investigations into Clinton administration officials
continued to yield startling tidbits last week.
</P>
<P>
   Two black members of President Clinton's cabinet said they had
to submit urine samples, apparently for drug testing, while two
white cabinet secretaries said they did not, according to testimony
by Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Carol Browner.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Browner described the conversation while testifying in the
trial of former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, who had to submit
a sample. Commerce Secretary Ron Brown also gave one.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said drug-testing
policy varied by agency. White House staff members are tested, he
said, but the president is not.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES BENNET
</P>
<P>
   Unconvicted
</P>
<P>
   Imelda Marcos will not be cooling her well-shod heels in jail _
not yet, anyway _ now that the Supreme Court of the Philippines has
overturned a corruption conviction against her.
</P>
<P>
   Is she off the hook? Not exactly. Other criminal and civil
matters loom, involving the billions that she and her husband,
Ferdinand, who died in 1989, are accused of stealing. And the
United States wants to discuss the small matter of $5 million in
unpaid income taxes from the Marcoses' days in Hawaii. She may be
barefoot yet.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   A Shorter Season  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 51 years and 35,001 games, the National Basketball
Association avoided losing regular-season games to labor strife.
But with the cancellation of the entire preseason and talks going
nowhere, Patrick Ewing and friends will be off the court awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't agree with their proposal,'' said Ewing, the
players association president, after both parties met Thursday.
They meet again Tuesday, which NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik
called the ``drop-dead date'' for canceling part of the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIKE WISE &QR;
</P>
<P>
   A Guilty Plea
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks before Christmas a 15-year-old fired at teen-agers
praying in the hallway of Heath High School in West Paducah, Ky.,
killing three and injuring five others.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Michael Adam Carneal pleaded guilty but mentally ill.
His pleas were accepted on the condition that he face the maximum
penalty of life in prison without the possibility of parole for 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY
</P>
<P>
   Sold, Time in Space
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for cash, Russia has agreed to sell the United States
most of its allotted research time aboard the International Space
Station for $60 million. The deal reduces Russia's role to mostly
that of a builder but not a user of the outpost during its five or
six years of orbital construction.
</P>
<P>
   NASA is also beefing up its own role. ``Our reliance on Russian
capabilities has to be reduced, not by eliminating their
involvement but adding layers of protection,'' NASA Administrator
Daniel Goldin told Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   HMOs Accused of Fraud
</P>
<P>
   Probably few executives at Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. or
Quorum Health Group ever gave much thought to tiny North Valley
Hospital in Whitefish, Mont. But now few will be likely to forget
it. The government said it had joined a lawsuit filed by a former
North Valley officer, who accused the two hospital companies of
defrauding Medicare through bogus expense claims.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed under seal almost six years ago, has already led
to federal investigations. Analysts expect that before it's all
over settlements might top $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KURT EICHENWALD
</P>
<P>
   Another Guilty Plea
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. DeBartolo Jr., the co-owner of the San Francisco
49ers, had bigger worries than his team's recent loss to the
Buffalo Bills. DeBartolo pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court in
Baton Rouge, La., to failing to report an alleged extortion plot
concocted by former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a plea bargain, DeBartolo agreed to provide evidence
that Edwards had demanded $400,000 in cash in exchange for using
his influence to shepherd a DeBartolo riverboat casino project
through the local Gaming Board. He was ordered to pay $1 million in
fines and penalties. Prosecutors have their eye on Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KEVIN SACK  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Bit of Lucre From Lucky Dog &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do Larry Hagman from ``Dallas,'' Isabel Sanford from ``The
Jeffersons'' and Joe Lynn Turner from the rock group Deep Purple
have in common?
</P>
<P>
   They are all dogs. At least, they help play dogs in television
commercials for the Lucky Dog Phone Company, the first brand that
AT&AMP;T has created in its 113-year history that does not actually
mention AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good reason for that. Since 1885, AT&AMP;T, the nation's
largest communications company, has built an image based on trust,
reliability, convenience and a sense of community (as in ``Reach
out and touch someone'').
</P>
<P>
   But the Lucky Dog campaign, which supports a new calling service
called 10-10-345, is based on, well, good old greed.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, AT&AMP;T will give away 345 prizes to people who use the
service, plus a $1 million grand prize in January. Its market
research found that people who like to save money with flat-rate
services like Lucky Dog (a dime a minute, a dime to connect) also
like sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   The research may also have discovered something else: that a
phone call is a basic consumer product rather than a high-tech way
to improve someone's life. Maybe that is why the AT&AMP;T executive who
invented Lucky Dog used to market Diet Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Hagman is the voice of a bull mastiff, Ms.
Sanford a basset hound and Turner a mutt.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH SCHIESEL
</P>
<P>
   Hers Was Fact, His Is Fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sex in America, at least for the rich and famous, is getting to
be an awfully high-risk activity. No, this isn't about AIDS _ it's
about people simply not being able to shut up about sex.
</P>
<P>
   Well, for one, there's the president's dalliance with . . . but
don't worry: the ``M'' word will not appear here.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the high-decibel, high-profile marriage of
Philip Roth and Claire Bloom. After it ended in a blaze of
ugliness, Ms. Bloom blasted into print with a 1996 memoir,
``Leaving a Doll's House'' (Little, Brown &AMP; Co.), in which she
depicts Roth as a control freak with a ``deep and irrepressible
rage'' at the very idea of being married and a ``profound distrust
of the sexual power of women.''
</P>
<P>
   Any thoughts, Roth? Well, nothing explicit. But he DOES happen
to have a new novel out, called ``I Married a Communist.'' And it
DOES involve a failed marriage to an actress named Eve Frame (Hmmm:
all those one-syllable names), who, as it happens, writes a
vindictive memoir about said marriage. And Ms. Frame has a teen-age
daughter who is a source of great friction in the marriage, just as
Ms. Bloom did.
</P>
<P>
   If it's revenge, though, is it also art? Roth, who has an
uncanny way of squeezing an awful lot of his own life into his
fiction, may well have envisioned the book as a sweet riposte, but
whether the work succeeds on a literary level is another matter
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``While such matters may be of passing interest to literary
gossip-mongers,'' Michiko Kakutani wrote in The New York Times,
``they are not transformed, in this case, into plausible or
compelling fiction.'' The novel is ``unfinished and overstuffed,''
she wrote; the characters just ``talk and talk and talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gore Vidal should have the last word about this steamy,
all-too-public battlefield. ``It's always best,'' he told a Times
interviewer when Ms. Bloom's memoir appeared, ``to stay out of
other people's divorces.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
</TEXT>
