<SLUG> BC-AIR&AMP;SPACE-ANNEX-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVIATION TREASURES TO LAND AT NEW SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Robert Padgett framed by aircraft propeller is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(ak) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SILVER HILL, Md. _ Robert Padgett worked slowly, lovingly, on
the Soviet surface-to-air missile, freshly painted gray but with
its Cyrillic markings intact, to make sure that it would be in
prime condition for historians a century from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Middle East unit _ it was full of sand when we got
it,'' said Padgett, a restoration technician at the Smithsonian
Institution's National Air and Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The missile was captured by the Israelis from the Egyptians in
1967, he said. An SA-2, the kind of surface-to-air missile that
brought down Francis Gary Powers' U-2 spy plane in 1960, it was
still sleek and nasty-looking, sitting on a trailer, casually
pointed at the Smithsonian's Hawker Hurricane, a mainstay of the
Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain, which was undergoing
restoration a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution is often described as the nation's
attic, but it has an attic of its own, called the Paul E. Garber
Preservation, Restoration and Storage Facility, here in suburban
Maryland. It is squeezed full of treasures that will not fit in the
Smithsonian's famous museums.
</P>
<P>
   For every plane on display at the National Air and Space Museum
headquarters in Washington, there are three more stashed away here,
in an obscure complex of pink corrugated metal buildings, crammed
with biplanes, spaceship parts, surface-to-air missiles, kamikaze
planes and gliders.
</P>
<P>
   But the Air and Space Museum is hoping to move some of them to a
new display place soon. The museum expects to complete design work
next month on a giant new exhibition hall at Washington Dulles
International Airport, with room for objects that would never fit
anywhere else, including the prototype space shuttle and an early
model Boeing 707.
</P>
<P>
   The National Air and Space Museum is the most popular tourist
attraction in Washington, drawing more than 9 million people last
year, but it displays only about 30 percent of its aviation
collection. Officials predict that the annex, several times the
size of the original, located off the end of runway 1-R at Dulles,
will attract 2.5 million to 3 million people in the first year
after its scheduled opening in 2003. It will show off not only the
objects, but also the restoration process. When restored, the
aircraft look good as new, but they are not actually flyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all restored to the condition they were in at the
last time they flew,'' said the director of the Air and Space
Museum, Donald Engen, a retired admiral and a former administrator
of the Federal Aviation Administration. ``We arrest the corrosion,
and put old hydraulic lines back into them.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Smithsonian's approach, he said, ``a hundred years from
now, people can come back and see the technology of the time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Engen, who was a dive-bomber pilot based on the aircraft carrier
Lexington in World War II, said the SA-2 missile is the kind that
killed his son-in-law, a pilot in the Vietnam War. He wants it
preserved along with the 200 other aircraft here, which would be
taken to the new Dulles museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Dulles museum is also expected to have a large-screen Imax
theater and a restaurant. The Virginia state government has
contributed $39 million for access roads and other infrastructure,
and Congress voted $8 million for design work. The museum still
needs $130 million, of which it hopes to get 20 percent from
corporate donors. Then it will start looking for individual
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The Garber center, named for the museum's first curator, is open
for tours every day, but reservations must be made two weeks in
advance. The new museum would make the collection more accessible,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Engen is especially proud of another aircraft being
reconditioned here, the last surviving Aichi Seiran, a plane built
by the Japanese to fit, folded up, inside a submarine. Taking off
from floats, it was supposed to bomb the Panama Canal. A Japanese
company that makes aircraft model kits, Tamaiya, contributed
$150,000 to help recondition the plane, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are also aviation curiosities, including jet engines that
never quite worked out, gyrocopters that were supposed to
revolutionize travel, an ``air scooter'' meant to hover over the
ground, a 3-foot-wide model of the ``mother ship'' flying saucer
used to make the movie ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' and
the ``Airphibian,'' a plane with a steering wheel and removable
wings, meant to be driveable on a highway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
