<HEADLINE>
SAME SONG, SECOND VERSE: A RE-ELECTION BATTLE  
A THRILLER, OF SORTS, IN FLORIDA POLITICS  
NAME RECOGNITION OF WRONG KIND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Md. Fla., Ark.)  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category ``p.'')  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAME SONG, SECOND VERSE: A RE-ELECTION BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Parris Glendening's bid for a second term as
Maryland's governor has been an uphill struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening, a liberal Democrat in one of the country's most
Democratic states, won his first term in 1994 by only 5,993 votes
and has battled mightily ever since to enlarge his constituency.
</P>
<P>
   But early in the final month of the current campaign, he remains
in serious political trouble, with several polls showing him locked
in a dead heat with his Republican opponent, Ellen Sauerbrey, the
conservative former state representative he barely managed to best
the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   For all their dominance of Maryland politics, Democrats still
seem unsure about just how much they love their governor, in part
because many in the state's heavily black metropolitan areas,
notably Baltimore and Prince George's County on Washington's
outskirts, think he has given them short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   The state's two most powerful black politicians, Mayor Kurt
Schmoke of Baltimore and Wayne Curry, the chief executive of Prince
George's County, did all they could in the summer's Democratic
primary to deny the governor renomination, with both backing his
main rival, Eileen Rehrmann, chief executive of Harford County.
Neither sided with him once he won the primary.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has tried repeatedly throughout the fall to win
over Schmoke and Curry, whose populous jurisdictions have become
crucial factors in statewide races in recent years. But until last
week, he had made no progress.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Thursday, under pressure from the national Democratic
Party and the White House, Schmoke and Curry called a news
conference and announced their support for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do all we can to encourage a big turnout,''
Schmoke said. Had the governor, in return, promised to pay more
attention to Baltimore and Prince George's, should he win
re-election?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing a whole bunch of votes and it's important that
our constituents be heard,'' Curry replied.
</P>
<P>
   Political doubters noted that Glendening was not at the news
conference, even though he later said he was ``very, very
pleased.'' Schmoke said there was not enough time to invite him.
</P>
<P>
   Among the doubters was Ms. Sauerbrey, who with the help of
national Republicans has recently mounted a major campaign of
attack advertisements against the governor and has also moderated
her conservatism a bit in an effort to woo even more of his
supporters. What did she think of the Schmoke-Curry announcement?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit-and-run endorsement,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   A THRILLER, OF SORTS, IN FLORIDA POLITICS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Down in Florida, they refer to it as Dead Man Running.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not one of those stories about a candidate who
managed to get on the ballot, only to die just before Election Day,
too late for his name to be erased and a substitute chosen. This is
about an imposter _ or so claims Diane Ellis of Palm Harbor, just
north of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis, a Democrat who works as a legal assistant, is running
for a seat in the Florida House of Representatives, struggling
every step for name recognition and financing. Her Republican
opponent is Gus Bilirakis, a well-known Palm Harbor lawyer and the
well-financed and well-connected son of the area's veteran
congressman, Rep. Michael Bilirakis.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ellis says Gus Bilirakis is dead, gone the better part of
three years. The man politically masquerading in his place, she
insists, is one Danny Divito, though she does not make clear
whether she believes he is the Danny DeVito of film fame, who knows
a bit about stand-in work, or whether it is some other Danny Divito
or DeVito.
</P>
<P>
   How? Why?
</P>
<P>
   In a note sent to Citizens for Fair Campaign Practices, a local
group that monitors elections, Ms. Ellis offered this cryptic
explanation: ``My Republican candidate Gus Bilirakis is a fake. His
name is Danny Divito/New York from Washington D.C. 40 years of age
_ Greek. Congressman Michael Bilirakis is paying him to replace his
son who is DEAD 1995 _ Sept. 23. He wants to win the seat!''
</P>
<P>
   Her information, she said, came from a private investigator. But
she declined to identify him, leading the Campaign Practices group
to label her assertion ``weird.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Gus Bilirakis _ the Gus spotted by local Floridians on
the street every day, always standing taller than the Hollywood
star, Danny DeVito _ he reports he is alive and well and chuckling.
But he says he also feels sad for Ms. Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Ms. Ellis' fellow Democrats, especially the local party
chairwoman, Nancy Whitman. Saying that Ms. Ellis ``is not going to
win any intelligence contests,'' she demanded the other day that
Ms. Ellis apologize to Bilirakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' Ms. Ellis said _ only to add that she still
believed her opponent was one Danny Divito.
</P>
<P>
   NAME RECOGNITION OF WRONG KIND
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Fay Boozman, the Republican candidate in this fall's
U.S. Senate race in Arkansas, is a hard-right conservative who
opposes abortion except in cases of rape, incest and when the life
of the mother is threatened. But insofar as rape is concerned, he
told a Kiwanis Club a couple of weeks ago, abortion is mostly a
moot issue anyway.
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning: Pregnancy rarely occurs after rape because the
stress of the assault triggers a biochemical reaction in the victim
that makes conception unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, who also is an ophthalmologist, said he knew this
to be the case from anecdotal information he had picked up over the
years and from his own medical residency in the 1970s at the
University of Arkansas Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the fall, Sen. Boozman has been struggling to catch
up with his Democratic opponent, Blanche Lambert Lincoln, a former
congresswoman. She leads him in the polls by close to 15 points, in
part, political analysts say, because she has much better name
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Or did have better name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a columnist for The Arkansas Democrat-Gazette wrote
about Sen. Boozman's talk to the Kiwanis, which had been little
noted until then. And now the senator has major name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights advocates called a news conference and accused
him of being ``insensitive to rape victims,'' thousands of whom
become pregnant every year, they argued.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lincoln, a moderate who supports abortion rights and whose
husband is an obstetrician, said that the senator, as a physician,
should ``know better.''
</P>
<P>
   It was ``inexcusable,'' she asserted, that he did not understand
that rape resulting in pregnancy is ``a woman's worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the senator apologized, acknowledging he had
``offended many'' with his ``lack of judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am now asking the people of Arkansas, and especially the
women and young ladies of Arkansas, to forgive me,'' Dr. Boozman
said. ``I am truly sorry for any hurt that I have caused.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
