<SLUG> BC-NATO-ORDER-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO NEARS FINAL ORDER TO APPROVE KOSOVO STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ak) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ NATO is ready to approve an ``activation order'' on
Monday, opening the way for its military commanders to order air
strikes against Serbian targets in Kosovo and perhaps in the
Serbian heartland itself, senior Western officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Once the order is approved, almost certainly at a meeting of
NATO ambassadors in Brussels on Monday, American officials believe
the pressure on Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, to
agree to withdraw his forces from Kosovo may reach a decisive
level.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, said one senior NATO diplomat, ``the safety catch
will be removed, the gun will be pointed, and we hope this will
trigger a switch in Slobodan Milosevic's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   With the experience of the negotiations to end the Bosnian war
behind them, American officials _ including the special envoy to
the Balkans, Richard Holbrooke _ have long been convinced that
Milosevic would only compromise under the imminent threat of force.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO preparation and planning is now moving forward with a
very strong momentum,'' Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's top commander in
Europe, said Saturday. ``If necessary, NATO air power will
systematically take apart Milosevic's air defense structure and
expose his military and police machinery of repression in Kosovo to
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it appears that at least a few days would be needed
between Monday's activation order and any air strikes. Although
NATO's operational plans are ready, aircraft still have to be put
into position.
</P>
<P>
   This would clearly be the period in which Holbrooke, who worked
closely with Clark on the peace accord that ended the Bosnian war
in 1995, would have maximum leverage with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, the NATO secretary-general, Javier Solana, said
Saturday that ambassadors from the 16-nation alliance had completed
all the work necessary to prepare for the authorization of air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North Atlantic Council has today cleared all the decisions
necessary prior to an activation order,'' he said, adding that
there was ``still no compliance on the ground and time is running
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav leader has been told to end all military and police
operations in Kosovo, withdraw his forces in a verifiable way and
open negotiations with Kosovo's ethnic Albanian community, which
accounts for about 90 percent of the population of the province. If
he fails to comply with these and other demands, NATO has said, it
will begin military action.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Milosevic has been consistent in at least one way throughout
Yugoslavia's slow death: he has maneuvered tirelessly to keep the
violence out of Serbia. As Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia
successively bled, not a shot was fired in Serbia. This suggests
that he may be ready to blink to avert NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   But the patience of Madeleine Albright, the secretary of state,
has clearly been tried. Her language about Milosevic this week _
including a reference to ``accumulated barbarity'' in Kosovo _ was
strikingly undiplomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is, of course, used to harsh Western criticism. But he
knows that the American coalition backing force is by no means a
resolute one, and no Western government wants to provoke Russia by
attacking, if that can be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Both Germany and Italy, which are between governments, have been
particularly concerned that the legal basis may not exist for NATO
airstrikes. But their hesitations have been overcome in the last
two days. Beniamino Andreatta, Italy's acting defense minister,
said Saturday that forces were ready to join their NATO allies ``to
mount the maximum pressure so that law is restored in Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
