<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES MORE MONEY FOR EDUCATIONAL PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala., N.Y. Nev., Fla.)   (jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton challenged Congress Saturday to
provide money in the budget being hammered out on Capitol Hill for
billions of dollars' worth of new education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to see this Congress walk away from America's
schoolchildren,'' the president said in his weekly radio address.
``We must use this moment of good fortune to make an historic
investment in the quality of our public schools, and we've still
got a few days to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed a second stopgap spending bill on Friday night to
keep the government running through midnight Monday. Republicans in
Congress and White House officials were meeting over the weekend to
negotiate a new budget to keep the government open.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides insisted they had no intention of shutting down the
government and interfering with functions like the issuing of
Social Security checks and keeping the national parks open. But, as
Clinton said Saturday, ``I can't keep granting extensions
indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of issues were on the table, ranging from how to conduct
the census in 2000 to various education programs to several
ideologically polarizing questions over contraception _ for minors,
for federal employees and for overseas family planning
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest items _ how much money to give to the
International Monetary Fund _ appeared close to being resolved.
Republicans said they would provide the president's full request of
$18 billion only on certain conditions, including having the agency
stop lending money at below-market interest rates and having it
operate more openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way,'' said Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., who
is chairman of the foreign operations subcommittee of the
Appropriations Committee. ``We're in a position to reach some type
of agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration also sounded optimistic. ``I think it's too
early to tell, but I think there are more hopeful signs than there
have been in quite some time,'' said Gene Sperling, Clinton's
national economic adviser. He added that ``the entire world is
waiting on this United States Congress'' to provide the money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the likelihood was strong that the IMF matter would be
rolled into one gigantic spending bill that Congress would present
to the president on a take-it-or-leave-it basis early next week.
Only with the president's signature would lawmakers be free to go
home to campaign for re-election, although many left Washington
temporarily this weekend while their leaders sat behind closed
doors hammering out the final package.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides seemed fairly confident of a settlement by early next
week. Clinton plans to be in New York on Monday raising money for
Rep. Charles Schumer, the Democratic Senate candidate, and Peter
Vallone, speaker of the New York City Council, who is running for
governor. On Tuesday, he plans to visit Florida for more
fund-raising and to join in an event with retirees to highlight his
contention that he has saved the budget surplus to shore up Social
Security for aging baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is one of the flash points with Congress.
Republicans argue that Clinton is actually raiding the surplus to
pay for billions of dollars in education and child-care programs
that he had expected to pay for with money from a settlement with
the tobacco companies, which never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   They also say he wants to take billions from the surplus to pay
for ``emergencies'' that are not true emergencies, like the
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia and fixing the year 2000 computer
bug, both of which were foreseen. They agree that some of the
emergency money the president seeks _ to improve security at U.S.
embassies around the world and to help Americans who were hit by
natural disasters _ are legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations stalled late last week, in part over the emergency
spending. Republicans said the president had not identified other
cuts to pay for his additional programs. The White House says the
Republicans want to break into the surplus for a tax cut. The
proposed tax cuts have dwindled over time from a high of $80
billion over five years to a current proposal of about $9 billion,
mostly in extending tax credits that were due to expire.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After the House voted on Thursday to open an impeachment inquiry
into the president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, Clinton was
eager to show that he was tending to the people's business _ and
eager to remind them why they voted for him in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   As he has since his election in 1992, Clinton cast himself as
the guardian of education and promoted his education agenda.
</P>
<P>
   It includes money to make sure all children can read by the
second or third grade, to help colleges provide mentors to students
beginning in the sixth grade to guide them toward college and to
repair old schools and modernize them for new technology. Clinton
also wants to hire 100,000 teachers in schools across the country,
particularly in difficult-to-recruit settings like inner cities and
rural areas, to reduce the size of the average class to 18 students
in the first grade. The total package would cost about $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is also concerned about some education issues
that have little to do with money. These include a Republican ban
on the president's proposal for national testing of fourth-grade
students in reading and eighth-grade students in math, and a
Republican plan to dissolve bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said: ``These are the education issues that the
American people support _ why they elected the president twice _
and what we need to have in this budget before the president can
feel strong enough about it to complete the budget and sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both houses of Congress have cleared only six of the 13 spending
bills needed to keep the government running.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate demonstrated just how contentious some of these
issues were and how fluid the situation was when one Democrat, Sen.
Harry Reid of Nevada, managed on Friday to sidetrack the bill that
finances the Treasury Department and U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   The contention involves a proposal, supported by Reid, to
require the federal government to provide contraceptive coverage
for the 1.2 million women of childbearing age who are federal
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Both houses had passed the measure and Republican leaders had
agreed to include it as part of the Treasury-Postal bill. But in an
effort to placate conservatives and pass the overall bill,
Republican leaders dropped the contraceptive measure at the last
minute. An infuriated Reid then vowed to kill the bill. First, he
stalled it by ordering a clerk to read out loud every word of the
bill on the Senate floor, a highly unusual procedure that paralyzed
the Senate for more than three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's maneuver prompted Republican leaders to pull the bill
from consideration. Now they plan to toss it into the omnibus
package, without the contraceptive measure. But Democrats are
pressing the White House to insist on restoring the measure before
the president agrees to the total package.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
