<HEADER>
A0051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-REFUGE-COX     10-10 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-REFUGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovo refugees find shelter in wealthy Kosovar's `goodwill'
 &HT;    WITH ALBANIA-REFUGEES
 &HT;    With PHOTO
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of locator map, Durres is on Albania's
Adriatic Coast, directly west of Tirana.
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ After living 30 years in Germany and
Switzerland, Rame Sylmetaj last year decided it was time to invest
_ and certainly to turn a profit _ in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, it was possible in Kosovo, Sylmetaj's home
region, for a young man to venture into the world to seek his
fortune. This would have been impossible in Albania, which did not
allow its citizens to hold passports until 1990. But as part of
Yugoslavia, Kosovars enjoyed far more freedoms than their brothers
in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   A careful and lucky investor, Sylmetaj, now 49, did well, but
for some time had wanted to return among the Albanian people.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, he bought some land near the road between Durres,
Albania's primary port city, and Tirana, the capital, and began
building a small apartment building. His family remained in
Switzerland. He had hoped to have the apartments up and rented
within a few months and move on to something else.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed.
</P>
<P>
   In February tensions in Kosovo between ethnic Albanian
separatists and the Serb-dominated government flared into warfare.
Sylmetaj read that thousands of Kosovars were being made refugees
by the fighting. He heard there were refugees in need of housing. A
man with housing, albeit unfinished housing, Sylmetaj organized a
small convoy of vans and headed to the mountain town of Tropoje
where he had heard there were refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got 60 refugees and brought them here,'' he said last week
as he gave a foreign visitor a brief tour. He said Kosovar
Liberation Army leaders gave him some money to provide for food and
other needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to borrow $8,000 to get these doors and windows
installed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, more refugees began showing up, so now Sylmetaj has 108 --
including 47 children -- in his care.
</P>
<P>
   The building is far from complete, and by U.S. standards hardly
inhabitable. The top floor is far from completion, so the refugees
inhabit 23 of the 24 bedrooms that are complete enough for people
to live in. He lives in the 24th room.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the walls are bare cinderblock, and there are no doors
between the small rooms.
</P>
<P>
   There are no kitchens, just electric stoves powered by rigged
wires connecting to poles outside. The women cook on the stoves and
boil their laundry clean. There are no lights in the rooms, and the
refugees sleep on thin cotton mattresses on the floor, which is
covered by cardboard and horsehair blankets.
</P>
<P>
   The new wood-framed doors and windows, which seem luxurious in
their rough settings, have been kept open over the hot, humid
summer, and flies swarm in clouds where there is food or water.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a garden hose provides the drinking water. The children
play on a muddy patch in front of the apartment house.
</P>
<P>
   For five months, they have lived there in a safe if somewhat
squalid sanctuary. Sylmetaj is paid no rent and is provided only
food and medical assistance by relief agencies, said Ilir Gjoni, an
official with the United Nations High Commission for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless him, he has kept us alive,'' said Sahit Tola, who is
living in one of the apartments with his wife and two small
children.
</P>
<P>
   Sylmetaj, who talks mostly about the practical needs of his
guests, has little to say about what moved him to help these
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a part of goodwill,'' he said. ``That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
