<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAZA-STUDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL BAN BURDENS STUDENTS FROM GAZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA STRIP _ As his classmates filed into lecture halls last
month to start the fall semester at Bir Zeit University in the West
Bank, Jamal Safi found himself stranded at home in a bleak refugee
camp in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Safi, 26, a mechanical engineering student from the Bureij camp,
south of Gaza City, was refused entry to the West Bank by the
Israeli authorities when he tried to cross from Jordan after a
summer course in Egypt. So instead of starting his fifth and final
year at Bir Zeit, he was chafing at his enforced idleness, one of
hundreds of students from the Gaza Strip who have been denied
permits to study in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel useless,'' Safi said as he whiled away another day in
Gaza, waiting for a response to another travel-permit application.
``I have nothing to do here.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time Safi was stopped trying to cross into
the West Bank from Jordan, but he had been barred from leaving the
Gaza Strip for various periods in recent years, along with the
other students from the area.
</P>
<P>
   Israel justifies the restriction on Gaza students traveling to
the West Bank, now in its third year, on security grounds, saying
students from the Gaza Strip include political militants who might
be prone to anti-Israeli violence. But the ban has disrupted the
education of thousands of students and contributed to the growing
isolation of Palestinians in the Gaza Strip from those in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   That separation began with a travel ban imposed during the 1991
gulf war and deepened in 1993 after a series of deadly Palestinian
attacks on Israelis. The Israeli authorities barred free passage of
Palestinians to Israel and between the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
instituting a restrictive permit system.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, periodic Israeli closings of the Gaza Strip and West
Bank _ including one in force for the past three weeks _ have been
put in effect after suicide bombings in Israel and other violence;
the closings have prevented even permit holders from leaving the
two areas. Gaza is surrounded by a security fence, and the only
exit for tens of thousands of laborers who normally commute to jobs
in Israel is an elaborate Israeli checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the Israelis and the Palestinians on opening
``safe passage'' routes through Israel between the Gaza Strip and
West Bank have bogged down during a 19-month stalemate in peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Students from the Gaza Strip, who at first could get permits,
albeit with difficulty, were evicted from the West Bank and banned
from traveling there after the militant Islamic group Hamas carried
out a series of suicide bombings in Israel in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen Gaza students were allowed into the West Bank with
permits early this year in what was supposed to have been a first
step in loosening the ban. But no further permits have been issued,
leaving hundreds of students who have sneaked in over the years
studying illegally in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Some have used false identification papers and other deceptions
to leave the Gaza Strip, staying in the West Bank during vacations
to avoid being stranded at home.
</P>
<P>
   Others have traveled to Egypt and then to Jordan and on to the
West Bank, or have flown to Israel from Turkey, making a circuitous
journey to reach campuses that are only a two- or three-hour drive
from their homes. In recent weeks, however, the Israeli authorities
have turned back Gaza students trying to cross into the West Bank
from Jordan, and controls have also been tightened at Ben Gurion
airport in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian academic officials call the Israeli policy a
``criminalization of education'' that has forced students to study
on the sly, under constant threat of eviction and arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Safa Abdel Rahman, 22, a Bir Zeit senior from the Gaza Strip,
first arrived in the West Bank four years ago. She has not returned
home for two years to avoid getting stuck in the Gaza Strip, and on
her daily ride to classes she sometimes has to bluff her way past
Israeli checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel this peace,'' she said of the Israeli-Palestinian
accord signed five years ago. ``It was supposed to make life
easier, but it has made it more difficult for me and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Ziyadeh, 23, an economics major from the Bureij camp, has
also not been home in two years; he commutes warily to the Bir Zeit
campus from his nearby apartment.
</P>
<P>
   In Ziyadeh's view, the ban on travel from Gaza to the West Bank
is part of an Israeli policy to divide the Palestinians and prevent
the establishment of a strong, cohesive Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make it difficult for the Palestinian
Authority,'' he said, ``when it declares our state, to mix people
and create one society with common traditions, where people will
support each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
