<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SUBMARINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL ADVERTISES FOR CLUES TO LOST SUBMARINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Seeking to solve a mysterious maritime
tragedy, Israel has appealed to the public in Turkey and elsewhere
to help it find the wreck of a submarine that disappeared 30 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-nine crew members were lost with the sub. Today they
constitute by far the largest group of Israeli military personnel
listed as missing in action. Despite many naval searches and quiet
inquiries in various countries, Israel still has no clue about how
they met their fate.
</P>
<P>
   A large advertisement signed by the Israeli military and the
Defense Ministry appeared in a leading Turkish newspaper in
September. It offered a reward of $5,000 to $300,000 for anyone who
``provides valuable information about the reason for the
submarine's disappearance'' or who ``produces any piece of the
submarine or items from it found on the coast or the open sea.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement was also published in Egypt, France, Greece
and Russia. The first three have Mediterranean coasts, and Russia
was apparently added because there is hope that a retired military
officer somewhere there might have information.
</P>
<P>
   Phones have begun ringing at Israeli missions in Istanbul and
Ankara. One caller said he had found a puzzling electronic device
on a Mediterranean beach and invited an agent to examine it.
Another said he had psychic powers and could locate the sub if he
saw a photo of it.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli diplomats say other Israeli missions abroad have also
begun receiving responses to the advertisements, as has the Defense
Ministry in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   The missing sub, the Dakar, was bought from Britain and set out
from Portsmouth for Haifa, its new home port, on Jan. 8, 1968. On
Jan. 24, as it was believed to be passing south of Crete, it lost
radio contact.
</P>
<P>
   A series of naval searches turned up no trace of the vessel.
Thirteen months later, one of its emergency buoys washed ashore in
Egypt, but since then there has been nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Searches off the Egyptian coast, made possible in the 1980s
after relations between Israel and Egypt improved, were
unsuccessful. So was a reported expedition near Rhodes, a Greek
island that lies close to Turkey's Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
   Because the submarine was lost only months after Israel fought a
war against Egypt, some have theorized that it might have been
attacked by Egyptians or their Soviet allies. There is no evidence
to support that theory, however, and Israeli experts say they still
believe there could have been a collision, fire, mechanical failure
or other accident.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the time that has passed, Israel has kept the
investigation active. Families of the victims have banded together
in a loose support group, and assemble each year at a memorial that
stands in a Jerusalem military cemetery. Israel is known for taking
extraordinary pains to find missing troops or their remains.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued in Jerusalem, the Israeli military said
naval investigators had ``invested great effort'' in their searches
and recently finished ``yet another searching season in the
Mediterranean.'' It said a U.S. naval crew had helped in this
year's effort.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to offer a reward, according to the statement, was
made ``in coordination with the families of the missing'' and was
part of Israel's determination ``not to leave a stone unturned in
its pursuit of solving the mystery of the disappearance of the
Dakar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
