<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-LETHARGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSS ACCUSES LETHARGIC LIONS (1-4) OF PLAYING ONLY FOR THEIR
PAYCHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Detroit Lions have Barry Sanders, a future Hall of Famer.
They have Herman Moore, one of the top three receivers in football.
They have all that talent, and just one victory, and coach Bobby
Ross has had enough.
</P>
<P>
   In a team meeting after the embarrassing loss to the Chicago
Bears last week, a heated Ross blasted his team, calling them
unmotivated and unfocused, and he promised harder practices.
Publicly, Ross was just as angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear about long practices,'' Ross said last
Monday. ``I shortened them last week and took them out of pads.
That may be the last time, too. I'll tell you that. If they don't
like it, they can lump it.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Chicago, which was 0-4 coming into the game, the Lions
had a fourth-quarter collapse and lost, 31-27. The loss seems to
have shaken up the Lions and Ross, who blamed almost everyone,
including his staff, for the poor game Detroit played. When Ross
spoke of his 1-4 team, he seemed exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like: `We want our checks and that's good enough
for us. Winning isn't that important as long as we get our
paycheck,''' Ross said. ``And that's exactly the way we finished
that game.''
</P>
<P>
   A head coach accusing his team of just playing for a paycheck?
It was a bold statement, one that Ross obviously made to fire up
his team. Some players, though, did not take too kindly to what
Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his opinion,'' said defensive end Robert Porcher.
``Everybody has one.''
</P>
<P>
   Now some Lions players are scared of losing their jobs. They
think Ross may make massive changes in the coming weeks if the team
does not play better. Moore has even privately expressed a concern
the team may trade him, which is highly unlikely. But when the
coach starts saying that heads will roll, even star players begin
checking their necks.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' anger is understandable. He is accustomed to success: he
has not had a losing record in six pro seasons, he took San Diego
to a Super Bowl, and he took the Lions into the playoffs last year
in his first season in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions have been chronic underachievers throughout the
1990's, and maybe it will take a blowup like the one Ross had to
shake the team out of its seemingly decadelong malaise.
</P>
<P>
   But Ross may have to endure several more weeks of misery.
Detroit plays Green Bay on Thursday night, and then Minnesota, now
5-0, on Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The way the Lions have been playing, winning either of those
games would take a small miracle. But Ross is convinced he can turn
the Lions' season around, and he made it clear it could be a
painful process for Lions players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got tunnel vision on how it's going to be done,'' Ross
said. ``And it's going to be done the right way. We're not going to
back off from it for one second.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're either going to have to conform and learn to do it, or
somewhere down the road something's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-98 1530EDT &QL; 
