<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTEBOOK: SPECIAL TEAMS; SACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Special Teams Improve
</P>
<P>
   There were 29 punts or kickoffs returned for touchdowns last
season in the National Football League. This year, there have
already been 15. Why the increase? One factor, special-teams
coaches and players say, is that teams are putting more starters on
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the days of trying to gain a respectable 15 yards are
over. Players want to break one every play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't catch a punt trying to get 10 yards,'' said Deion
Sanders, the great return man for the Dallas Cowboys. ``I catch a
punt trying to score every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacks Tougher Than Hits
</P>
<P>
   Which is tougher, hitting a home run or getting a quarterback
sack? To Minnesota Vikings defensive-line coach Andre Patterson,
there is no question that getting to a quarterback is the most
difficult single thing to do in sports. He uses Vikings pass rusher
John Randle, who had a league-leading 15{ sacks last year, to make
his point.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire had 70 home runs in 509 at-bats this season, or one
homer for every 7.27 attempts. Last season, Randle was in on almost
all of the 586 passing attempts made by Minnesota opponents. That
means Randle had a sack about once every 38 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
