<DOCNO> NYT19981010.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-REFUGEES-COX     10-10 1925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-REFUGEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovo refugees finding shelter in Albania a strain on resources
 &HT;    WITH ALBANIA-REFUGE
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    EDS: Optional add begins at 1500 words; for purposes of locator
map, Durres is on Albania's Adriatic Coast, directly west of
Tirana.
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURRES, Albania _ Many nights, Sahit Tola's 4 1/2-year-old
daughter will awaken in terror and crawl from her mat to seek the
sanctuary of her father's bed.
</P>
<P>
   The crackle of gunfire, an almost nightly phenomenon in this
unsettled country, startles her from slumber. The sounds play a
cruel trick on her sleeping mind, making her think for a brief
horrible moment that she is back home in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, after days of thunderous shelling near their small
hamlet of Djakovo, her parents decided the time had come to go. The
couple gathered their daughter, 8-year-old son and what things they
could carry.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving in mid-afternoon, they walked away from their village of
300 and headed west. For two days, the parents subsisted only on
the cold fresh water that flows in the Dinaric Alps, the jagged
mountain range that rises between Kosovo and Albania. The children
also had rations of candy. At night, they huddled together to keep
warm, not lighting any fires for fear they would be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, standing outside the half-built apartment house where
his family has found shelter near the port city of Durres, Tola
looked thin and tired as he retold his family's tortured odyssey.
He still wore the pale green sport shirt and jeans he wore the
afternoon he decided to flee. As he spoke, his daughter clung to
him, her blue saucer-like eyes not blinking as she studied a
visitor. She didn't return smiles; she said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's suffering from some kind of trauma,'' said Tola,
a 38-year-old factory worker. ``I've told my children about the
fighting _ they know who the Serbs are. But what more can I say to
them?''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Kosovo has made refugees of thousands of
families like this one. International monitors estimate that
250,000 ethnic Albanians have fled their homes during the seven
months of intense fighting between Serb forces and rebels of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo, which is about 90 percent ethnic Albanian, is the
southernmost province of Serbia, one of the two remaining republics
of Yugoslavia. Kosovo was largely self governing before 1989, when
Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic placed the region under
direct Serb rule.
</P>
<P>
   The loosely organized KLA is fighting for independence, while
Serb officials say they are trying to quell a rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   While most refugees have found shelter, up to 50,000 remain out
of doors in the rugged mountains of Kosovo. If they remain
unprotected, relief and government officials fear many may die when
the winter arrives in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 refugees have come to Albania, with officials here
preparing for another 20,000 _ in the belief that most of the rest
either will remain in Kosovo, or go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But what if more _ perhaps many more _ decide to turn to their
fellow Albanians for shelter?
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the question, Esma Boksi, an official in the northern
Albania town of Shkodra, takes a deep breath and lets the air
escape slowly through pursed, downturned lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then God help us,'' she says somberly. ``We can do no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Since June, 4,800 of the refugees have registered with Boksi, a
town hall worker pressed into service as refugee registrar. They
have come in waves of 1,000 or more, the ebbs coinciding with Serb
advances. These days, weeks after officials believe the refugee
flood has subsided, 20 or so a day still trickle into Boksi's
office. They seek identification cards, and information about food
and housing.
</P>
<P>
   Boksi sees some irony in the Kosovars' asking for help in a
place like Shkodra. ``This is the poorest place in Albania,'' she
says, noting a 20 percent unemployment rate and the that about a
third of the families here are on government relief. ``Yet, we give
them bread and cheese when they come, all we can give.''
</P>
<P>
   She needs no statistics to support her point.
</P>
<P>
   Outside her small office in a decaying building in central
Shkodra, the street is more pothole than pavement. Craters in the
street and sidewalks are filled with a milkshake thick ooze of
standing water and the gray silt that covers everything.
</P>
<P>
   A few streets away, venders sell fruits and vegetables from
blankets laid down over mud. Nearby, goats, bone-thin wild dogs and
pigs rummage through the garbage and rotting unsold produce. Many
windows have no glass, and few buildings seem to enjoy even basic
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   It is no easy task to distinguish between the living conditions
of host and refugee.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, about 2,500 refugees remain in the Shkodra district, many
in private homes, where the government has paid locals a supplement
of $10 a head to defray the costs of sheltering on average 15
refugees per family.
</P>
<P>
   Others have been placed in modest hotels and makeshift
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 have found shelter in a warehouse adjacent to the
Catholic Church of Lady Rosare. On Wednesday, construction workers
were laboring to convert the warehouse into living quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, more than 50 families -- usually two families to a room
-- live in the dormitory that rumbles all day with the sounds of
hammering and machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Fatos Stogha and her family of eight live in a room the size of
an American master bedroom. Stogha, 44, stands barefoot at the door
with her tall, lanky 15-year-old son Ruke, a bright-eyed boy who
seems eager for a diversion.
</P>
<P>
   The room is dark, poorly ventilated and affords no privacy.
There are two toilets in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Stogha said her family left Decani four months ago. The town,
about 44 miles from Pristina, the Kosovo capital, has seen some of
the war's fiercest fighting. She believes her house was destroyed
in a Serb offensive.
</P>
<P>
   In her room are four steel-framed beds. Along the walls are
cardboard boxes of their possessions. They take their meals in a
makeshift canteen.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the conditions seem harsh to an outsider, she says
she has been well cared for and expressed deep gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to go home,'' she says. ``I want to go there as
soon as it is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   With winter coming, officials are struggling to cope with the
needs of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be plenty of food thanks to international relief
organizations, but there is some concern about distribution once
winter comes and already difficult roads become impassable.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the single largest concern remains getting and
keeping roofs over the refugees' heads.
</P>
<P>
   It is a prospect made difficult because of the complex and
unstable political and legal conditions in this impoverished former
communist state. ``For example, they have the money to remodel
public buildings to make the dormitories,'' said Boksi, the Shkodra
official. ``But the town government has sold the public buildings
to private owners. There are very few public buildings left.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the refugees will have to leave, but no one hazards
a guess when that time will come. There are no plans to close the
border, and government officials and humanitarian groups are
planning for an indefinite stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will care for them as long as it is necessary,'' said
Tauland Dedja, the government official assigned to coordinate
refugee issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet international observers worry the presence of the Kosovars
is providing a destabilizing force for an already fragile
government. The country is a tinderbox where government armories
have been looted and most nights feature various levels of gunfire
-- usually just young men enjoying the power of firing a
semi-automatic rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can take care of the humanitarian needs,'' said
Daan Everts, the ambassador here for the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe. ``The bigger matter is the political
problem this poses for an already very difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian President Rexhep Meidani also worries that the Kosovars
will be destabilizing. ``This is a serious concern,'' he said
through a spokesman. ``Without international support, Albania does
not have a proper infrastructure to support the accommodation of
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult with a poor economy, great unemployment,
a lack of security and a high degree of criminality,'' he said.
``The influx of refugees makes an already bad situation even
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some refugees are angered by what they view as the
government's appeasing stance toward Milosevic. The Albanian
government does not support full independence for Kosovo but does
favor more autonomy for the province. ``We want a balance between
the right of the Kosovars to self determination and the right of
Yugoslavia to territorial integrity,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   But for refugees eager to lash out at the Serbs, this position
is too conciliatory, and Meidani worries they may be fomenting
dissension.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 200 refugees were among those arrested during the
September uprisings in Shkodra and the capital Tirana, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Meidani sees no easy and quick solution. ``With all that has
happened, all the killings and atrocities, there is a new memory,''
he said. ``This will take a long time for everyone to forget.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Refugees are in near unison in their assessment of what it will
take to make it possible for them to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry to see the power of the U.S. military employed to avenge
them, they want NATO forces to strike hard at the Serbs and drive
them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the Americans to deal with the Serbs,'' says Skender
Idrizaj, who is among the 50 or so refugees housed at the Hotel
Rozafa in Shkodra. The 52-year-old construction worker seethes over
the way he says the Serbs treated him and the other men from Decani
who escaped together last July.
</P>
<P>
   Idrizaj, a thin man with an enormous gray mustache, sits on his
haunches between two sofas in the hotel's large, dimly lit lobby
rolling cigarettes with thin white paper and finely chopped tobacco
as he talks.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces intercepted the group of Kosovars with which he and
his family were traveling in September, he said. The Serbs
separated the men from the women. ``They told us they were going to
liquidate the men,'' he said. ``They made us stand up for two days
and made us drink sewage water.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavian authorities deny mistreating the Kosovars and say
such stories are exaggerated to help convince the West to take
military action.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this and similar stories were repeated frequently and
consistently last week by Kosovar refugees in different parts of
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Serbs freed them: Idrizaj believes they feared
being caught by Red Cross and other relief workers.
</P>
<P>
   How long will the Kosovars remain in Albania?
</P>
<P>
   He closes the metal box of tobacco and stows in in his jacket
pocket. ``We will stay away until the Serbs leave,'' he says,
licking the paper and rolling it closed. ``But if NATO and the
Americans don't act, maybe we will go back anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't live in this hotel the rest of our lives,'' he says,
lighting the twist of tobacco-filled paper and taking a deep drag.
``We'll go back to die there, to die together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
