<DOCNO> NYT19981010.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-BIOBOX-COX     10-10 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BIOBOX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taiwan talks: the men at the table with China-Taiwan
 &HT;    By Marcia Kunstel and Joseph Albright
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ How do governments negotiate when they don't recognize
each other?
</P>
<P>
   Two honored octogenarians, both heads of ``unofficial''
organizations and both long-time confidants of their respective
leaders, are tasked with resuming the talks that may determine
whether China and Taiwan live peacefully or go to war.
</P>
<P>
   Here are their backgrounds:
</P>
<P>
   KOO CHEN-FU
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's lead negotiator is a savvy businessman from a native
family of the island's landed gentry. The Koos struck it very rich
after Chiang Kai-shek's government traded shares of Taiwan Cement
for much of their land in a so-called ``land-to-the-tiller''
program in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   The family enterprise grew into a 60-company conglomerate
including China Trust Commercial Bank, Taiwan's largest
privately-owned financial institution, and China Life Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Koo, 82, not only was a founder of the Taiwan Stock Exchange,
but also brought plastic to Taiwan: the credit card. He will not
likely endorse any agreement that might endanger Taiwan's deeply
embedded capitalist _ and more recently democratic _ system.
</P>
<P>
   Educated in law at National Taiwan University, Koo became a
political mover and shaker as president of an influential
industrial association. He has been an adviser to Taiwan's
president for a decade and a member of the Kuomintang's central
standing committee. He presides over Taiwan's Straits Exchange
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The industrialist lately returned to an early love: the Chinese
opera he studied in the 1950s. Koo resumed practice and performed
in full face make-up in one of the Beijing Opera productions his
family sponsors in Taiwan twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   WANG DAOHAN
</P>
<P>
   Wang is not so wealthy as his counterpart but is rich in the
experience of cutting through thickets of communist politics and
bureaucracy. A fixture since the communists took over China in
1949, he served first as minister of the East China Industry
Department and then for 13 years as deputy head of the First
Ministry of Machine Building. Later positions mostly related to
foreign finance, trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ministry of Machine Building in 1956 he encountered a
younger man whose path he would cross repeatedly. He was Jiang
Zemin, today the president of China, then just returned from
studies in Moscow. One affinity between Wang and Jiang: both sprang
from the engineering school of Shanghai's Jiao Tong University.
</P>
<P>
   Appointed mayor of Shanghai in 1980, Wang brought the city out
of isolation back to its old position as China's center of world
trade and finance. He spearheaded the Pudong project that created
an international industrial zone.
</P>
<P>
   He was followed in the job in 1985 by Jiang. Although Wang
assumed a lower profile after leaving the mayor's office, he is
said to have been a mentor to Jiang and to have remained a close
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, 83, has represented Shanghai at the Chinese People's
Congress and taught at the country's most prestigious universities:
Beijing, Fudan and Jiao Tong. He is president of China's
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Like Koo, he is a fan of Chinese opera but also a book-lover who
was known to wander alone through book stores of Shanghai when he
was mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
