<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981010.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS11-CO     10-10 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton challenges Congress to increase school funding
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Drawing a line in the sand in his budget battle
with an outgoing Congress, President Clinton warned Friday that
lawmakers ''should not go home'' until they increase spending on
classroom initiatives by about $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He said the money is needed to renovate schools, hire thousands
of new teachers and help children from low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans countered that Clinton was picking a fight
over education, the last smoldering pillar of what one called a
''failed agenda,'' as a smoke screen to deflect public attention
from his troubles over Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The public wrangling took place on a day when Clinton signed a
continuing resolution to avert a government shutdown by funding
federal operations through Monday night, to give White House and
congressional negotiators time to hammer out agreement on dozens of
outstanding spending issues.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting from budgeting to politicking, Clinton fired an
election-year broadside at the Republican-led Congress, chastising
legislators for failing to pass White House-backed bills aimed at
campaign finance reform, curbing cigarette sales to youths, raising
the minimum wage and providing low-income Americans with new
health-care guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ''But still, it is not too late for us to go forward together on
our children's future,'' Clinton said in a brief statement on the
South Lawn. ''Politics,'' he said, ''should stop at the classroom
door.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped short of threatening to veto legislation that
didn't fully fund his education proposals. But his top economic
adviser, Gene Sperling, said earlier, ''We would not sign, or would
veto, a budget that was weak on education. If it does not go a long
way toward meeting the president's priorities, the president will
not sign this budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has requested $17.7 billion in spending on education and
training programs for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The requests include $1 billion for building new classrooms and
another $1.1 billion to hire 100,000 new teachers, in an effort to
reduce class size to an average of 18 pupils per classroom for
grades kindergarten through three.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also requested $4.6 billion for Head Start and $7.8
billion for Title I, two programs aimed at improving the
educational prospects for children from low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the bill passed late Thursday night by the House comes
up $4 billion short of White House funding proposals, said
Sperling.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem with funding is that the White House had
originally counted on revenues generated by an increase in
cigarette taxes to pay for increasing the number of classrooms and
teachers in public schools. The prospect of receiving those
revenues collapsed earlier this year, however, with the defeat of
comprehensive tobacco legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's top domestic policy advisor, Bruce Reed, said there
was nevertheless no reason to also kill the prospects for reducing
class sizes, which can top 28 students per class in many elementary
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still need smaller classes,'' said Reed. ''We'd like this
Congress to get some work done. They killed the tobacco bill. They
killed campaign finance reform. They killed the patients' bill of
rights. We're not going to let them kill education.''
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans retorted that Clinton was playing politics with
schoolrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ''He did not make one call to any Republican congressional
leader to discuss improving education'' all year long,' said Rep.
John Boehner, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's attacks on our agenda are simply the politics
of deflection and avoidance: deflecting attention away from his
failed agenda, and avoiding the subjects of grand juries, perjury,
abuse of power and obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans said they had worked hard to pass an education
budget that addressed many of the priorities Clinton outlined, as
well as others he did not.
</P>
<P>
   ''Republicans have passed 22 major education initiatives,''
House Education and Workforce Committee Chairman Bill Goodling said
in a prepared statement. ''The president's bills didn't pass
because they don't focus on quality and they don't drive dollars
directly to the classroom. Instead, they create top-down federal
education programs run by Washington bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a showdown over education comes against a backdrop
of furiously paced negotiations over a host of budget areas,
ranging from Clinton's proposal for $18 billion in additional
funding for the International Monetary Fund to his request for more
than $1 billion to pay U.S. arrears to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 appropriations bills that provide a road map for how
the government will spend $1.7 trillion next year, only four had
been sent to the White House for Clinton's consideration as of late
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, Clinton has signed into law two, which pay for water
and energy and military construction. He has vetoed one, an
agriculture bill Clinton claimed came up short in funding for
emergency farm aid, and has not yet acted on the other, the giant
defense appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
