<HEADER>
A0072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN11-COX     10-10 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sales of Glenn memorabilia skyrocketing
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, FLA. _ The commemorative baby spoon in genuine
pewter is $5.95 and features the Discovery mission insignia etched
into the handle. The key ring has a 1960s-era John Glenn grinning
from his silver suit between emblems of his first space mission and
his latest. It runs $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can spend more, too.
</P>
<P>
   The decorative plates, in blue with gold rims, will set you back
$21.95 and come in two versions: Glenn the Mercury Program pioneer,
and Glenn the 77-year-old space shuttle astronaut. And for real
money, upwards of $69.95, you can buy framed portraits of Glenn
inset with mission patches or lapel pins.
</P>
<P>
   John Glenn the senior senator from Ohio, America's original
space hero and soon to be the world's oldest man in orbit, is
currently starring on Florida's Space Coast as John Glenn the
merchandiser's dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 29, Glenn and the six other astronauts aboard the
shuttle Discovery will lift-off for nine days in space, and already
the selling of Glenn and his return to orbit is well underway.
</P>
<P>
   And going great.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been selling out of everything John Glenn,'' said
Karen Kleinschmidt, a spokeswoman at the Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hats and buttons and refrigerator magnets that tell the story of
Glenn's historic first orbit in seven short lines are flying out
the door. And T-shirts, lots and lots of T-shirts. From the
standard white with the Discovery mission insignia, to the deep
blue ``John Glenn's Return to Glory,'' to the bluntness of a
block-lettered, ``Once Is Not Enough, do it again John Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Keegan of Cincinnati finally opted for none of the
big-ticket items. At 41, the X-ray technician vividly remembers the
grade-school day Glenn first rocketed into orbit 36 years ago, and
while visiting the space center last week she said she wanted to
get something to commemorate his latest effort. She chose a simple
cachet, an envelope decorated with Glenn's face and carrying a
shuttle fact sheet that will be mailed to her on launch day,
postmarked from the Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted a keepsake, something I could hand down,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's shuttle mission has her excited, but not like when she
was as a youngster. ``Then it was so unknown, there was a lot more
of that fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The Space Shop at Kennedy's Visitor Center may be ground zero
for the commercial celebration of Glenn's return to space, but it
is by no means cornering the market. Lowell Murrell runs a computer
graphics company called American Illustrator in Cocoa Beach, and he
is getting in on the Glenn boom, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had a John Glenn launch every month,'' Murrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell's company does special shirts for every shuttle flight,
but typically he only sells about 5,000. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went by that number already,'' Murrell said, without being
specific. ``We've had major hotel chains without gift shops buy
1,000 shirts. They're building them into their (rate) packages.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn himself has tried mightily during his seven months of
training to direct attention away from the sentiment of his return
and toward the scientific experiments he'll be conducting while in
space. Just last week, he scolded reporters and photographers
assembled in Florida for focusing on him, not the science, and he
read off a list of experiments to be done on the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often you get into the human aspects of this, you don't
get into the scientific stuff,'' Glenn said. ``If I came out and
said the BRIC program, or the Biological Research In Canisters,
you'd be completely turned off by it, wouldn't probably print a
word or say a thing about it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   But not even NASA, which does carry science books in its stores,
is selling T-shirts with BRIC initials on them. In fact, around the
corner from the Space Shop at the Visitor's Center is a freebie way
to participate in Glenn's return to flight and it's devoted
entirely to the glory of a once and future space hero.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-foot by 40-foot poster has been stretched across a wall for
people to sign, decorated at one end with a black and white collage
of images from Glenn's Mercury days, and at the other with a
portrait of the Discovery crew. Across the top it says ``Godspeed
John Glenn and Crew of STS-95,'' and in between is a web of
scrawled good wishes, too numerous to count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Act your shoe size, not your age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Return with Honor!''
</P>
<P>
   And one six-foot long, ``Geronimoooooo!''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Savino, 70, of Tallahassee, Fla., signed the wall and in
the few minutes she stood around afterward three others asked to
borrow her pen. She said she's thrilled by Glenn's return to space
in part because of his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have space travel in our generation, that's wonderful,''
she said. ``He's just seven years older than I am, and I don't
think I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So what did she write on the poster to Glenn?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just signed my name,'' she said. ``It's all full. Where I
put it there's very little space. There's a `Good Luck' and `God
Bless' and I'm in right about the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
