<HEADER>
A0076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILL11-COX     10-10 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When the social security bills come due
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hilda Meltzer is 71 years old, lives
alone in a subsidized one-bedroom apartment, has $700 in the bank
and goes out to dinner once a month _ ``usually Chinese or Italian
and never for more than $10 or $11,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't bought a dress since 1996 _ and it might be a lot
longer if the government gets what it's looking for: Meltzer
received a letter last month telling her she owes Social Security
$18,000.
</P>
<P>
   The three-page letter came from a service center in New York and
explained that her husband, Joseph, had been overpaid for three
years before he died in 1994. Meltzer said she wasn't aware of any
overpayments. But like any debt, a widow is liable for money her
husband owed, said John Raffa, a spokesman for the Social Security
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   So the letter Meltzer received said she was on the hook for the
money and that her entire monthly checks would be used to recover
the sum, starting in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be dead before they get it all back,'' Meltzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the appeals process described at the bottom of the
letter might have comforted the widow. If she can't afford to pay
or if it wasn't her fault, according to the letter, she can appeal
the claim.
</P>
<P>
   But Meltzer has been down this road once before.
</P>
<P>
   In March, she received a similar letter demanding $1,100.
Meltzer appealed the claim and lost. Since then her monthly Social
Security check _ the only income she receives _ has been reduced
from $561 to $551.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the settlement,'' she said. ``They're taking it out
of my checks $10 at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like we tried to make it as painless as possible,''
Raffa said. ``But it also sounds like she didn't keep going with
the appeals process. She may need someone to hold her hand, but we
have 240,000 people in Palm Beach County getting checks so we don't
always have somebody to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Raffa said the agency won't make Meltzer pay back the
$18,000 if she can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly our intention is not to take back money from a
71-year-old woman who really needs it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
