<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURE-DISCRIMINATE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge's order keeps lawmaker from hiring insurance analyst
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas insurance companies have managed to block
a Fort Worth legislator's attempt to have an industry critic review
their business practices to make sure Texans are getting affordable
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of insurance companies, District Judge Suzanne
Covington on Friday approved a temporary order that prevents state
Rep. Lon Burnam from hiring an outside expert to review Department
of Insurance records. A lawyer on the Legislature's legal staff
called the ruling unprecedented. The battle revolves around company
records that Burnam and industry critic Birney Birnbaum, a
recognized insurance data analyst, say will prove illegal
discrimination against minorities and poor Texans. Such
discrimination _ according to Burnam, other lawmakers and consumer
advocates _ makes it difficult for minorities and poor Texans to
find affordable insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The records show, by ZIP code, where companies have sold and
canceled auto and property insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Burnam, a Democrat whose district includes many Hispanic and
elderly residents, has asked the Texas Department of Insurance to
provide him with the records, which it has begun to do. But he said
neither he nor his current staff has the expertise to analyze the
information; therefore, he wants to hire Birnbaum to review it. He
said he has found no one else with Birnbaum's experience and
background.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum is a recognized expert in analyzing insurance industry
information. He previously worked for the Insurance Department and
has served as an expert in other insurance-related debates.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum acknowledges being a consumer advocate, but says he has
not skewed his statistical analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, insurers object to his involvement. They say courts
have made it clear that the records are not public information,
though they are open to lawmakers and their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Birnbaum is in essence, by becoming a member of a
legislator's staff, circumventing a . . . court order,'' said
Beverly Reeves, an attorney for State Farm, a lead plaintiff in the
court action joined by about a dozen other companies and two
industry trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said as an employee of the Insurance Department, Birnbaum
improperly released secret insurance company records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a concern that our claims of confidentiality have not
been respected in the past by Mr. Birnbaum,'' Reeves said.
``Perhaps they won't be respected again.''
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum said he did not improperly release company records and
would face civil and criminal penalties if he released the ZIP code
information from Burnam's office.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he's disappointed that the insurance industry has
``flexed its muscle'' to temporarily prevent Burnam from hiring him
to review the records.
</P>
<P>
   Although issued against Birnbaum, Covington's temporary order in
effect prevents Burnam from hiring Birnbaum to analyze the
information, according to Birnbaum's attorney, D.J. Powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really working at not being angry,'' Burnam said. ``I'm
really interested in getting this information and analyzing it
properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Collins, the head of legal affairs for the Texas
Legislative Council, said he's unaware of any court order that has
affected lawmakers' ability to use their staff as they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my memory, there is no similar circumstance in my 22 years
of working for the Legislature,'' said Collins, whose agency is an
arm of the Legislature that provides legal advice to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said of the insurers, ``They are creating a veto power
over who Representative Burnam gets to hire. They want an
uninformed Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, insurers have said the fight isn't about Birnbaum
but about maintaining the secrecy of sensitive information that
would reveal their marketing strategies and hurt competition. But
Friday's court hearing focused clearly on Birnbaum, not
competition. Attorneys for the insurers stopped just short of
saying they wouldn't have sought the restraining order if Burnam
was going to hire any other person to review the information. After
Birnbaum analyzed similar data last year, the department began
investigating seven insurance companies for illegal discrimination.
One of those investigations, against Nationwide insurance, has
resulted in a recommendation that the company be fined $10 million
for discriminating against minorities and other Texans based on
their age.
</P>
<P>
   The department has said legal action is pending against two
other companies, and other investigations turned up no wrongdoing
or have not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Conway, another State Farm attorney, said the records
being provided to Burnam show where insurance is sold, not why.
</P>
<P>
   ``They show rich people buy more insurance, like they buy more
of everything else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Covington's temporary order will last for two weeks. A hearing
for a more permanent order has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of irritating,'' Burnam said of the court fight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
