<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South African urges race dialogue in U.S.
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The head of South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission _ charged with exorcising the specter of
that country's racist past _ told an audience at the University of
Texas Law School that the United States must better examine its own
racial conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found the difference that unlike in South Africa where we
are taking on this question head on, America doesn't want to talk
about it,'' Alex Boraine said Friday. ``They say the problem's been
solved.'' Boraine, a South African attorney who is now a visiting
professor at New York University's law school, spoke about the
controversial truth and reconciliation commission, which began
hearings in 1995 to assess and come to terms with the years of
apartheid. ``The commission is enabling them to tell South Africa,
and indeed the world, of the deep-seated racism and rejection''
that took place, Boraine said. ``It's their story and it had to be
heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The South African community is shaped by our history and our
own peculiar transition from a dictatorship and something akin to
slavery to democracy,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But critics have said the hearings held over the past two and a
half years have only served to highlight atrocities committed
during the apartheid regime from 1960 to 1994, preventing any
racial healing. Others say the commission hearings should instead
be war crime trials similar to the Nuremberg trials held for Nazi
leaders after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compromise had to be made. It was a tough choice,'' Boraine
said of the transition to a democratically-elected government.
``But a (limited) amnesty is the price we had to pay for a
remarkably peaceful election.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report and recommendations will be presented to
South African President Nelson Mandela Oct. 29, when they will also
be released to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Boraine spoke to a group of about 50 as part of the UT law
school's Tom Sealy Lectureship. He is now working on a book about
his experiences in South Africa and on the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Carter, a professor of history at Emory University in
Atlanta, said some people in the United States mistakenly believe
that racial equality has been achieved and are dismantling
affirmative action programs in some states.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Hopwood court ruling effectively ended race
preference programs in Texas public universities and became a
festering sore at UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the progress of the past 40 years, America remains
deeply divided along the color line,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boraine said South Africa is not the only nation
searching for a way to resolve historical racial disputes, pointing
to conflicts in Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astonishing that we haven't learned. The whole question
of 'Never again.' has actually resulted in 'Again and again,''' he
said. ``We're not merely dealing with the past, but we're building
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
