<HEADER>
A0081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDFISH-PHONE-SERVICE     10-10 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDFISH-PHONE-SERVICE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redfish device automatically finds cheapest rate
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Trying to pin down just which long-distance
company really offers the lowest rate has given more than one
consumer a big headache. Many give up.
</P>
<P>
   But Redfish Telemetrix, a newcomer operating out of Austin and
Costa Mesa, Calif., will start selling on Monday what it bills as
the answer: Rate Seeker, a gadget that attaches to the telephone
and, on each long-distance call, dials using the company charging
the lowest rate at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   And _ this could prove a threat to family peace in some homes _
Rate Seeker also displays a running total of how much a
long-distance call is costing.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Romines of Austin, chief technology officer for Redfish
Telemetrix, said the device should help consumers get a grip on
their long-distance bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bought gasoline like you bought long distance,''
Romines said, ``you'd go to a pump with no price (of gas shown),
you would not know how much fuel you put in your tank (and) a month
later or so, you'd get a bill for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rate Seeker, which also can serve as Caller ID box, will cost
about $89 and come with a three-month subscription. Subscribers
then pay $5 a month for automatic updates of long distance rates.
(Or $4 a month if they buy an annual contract.)
</P>
<P>
   For those who spend at least $50 a month on long-distance calls,
the company claims, Rate Seeker can save up to 60 percent a month.
However, that estimate is based on a comparison with standard
long-distance rates, which are usually higher than the rates
available in various monthly plans from long-distance providers.
</P>
<P>
   When a customer dials a long-distance number, the device uses an
internal database to select the lowest rate from among 700
long-distance providers _ including AT&AMP;T, MCI and Sprint _before
selecting one and completing the call. Romines said users will not
notice any time delay.
</P>
<P>
   Once a month Rate Seeker will automatically connect with Redfish
Telemetrix's service center in Austin to download the latest rate
information.
</P>
<P>
   A consumer still would sign up for a rate plan with whichever
long-distance company they wish. Long-distance calls completed by
companies other than the usual provider would show up on their
local phone bill, said Romines, a former director of information
systems at the Public Utility Commission of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Janee Briesemeister, who follows phone issues for Consumers
Union in Austin, had not had a chance to study Rate Seeker but said
it probably would help only those making a lot of long-distance
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The device could save money for customers who make a lot of
short-haul long-distance calls, the only kind still handled by
Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. and other local phone companies,
Briesemeister said.
</P>
<P>
   But many long-distance plans with reduced rates require a
monthly subscription and are not available on a call-by-call basis,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Vanston, an Austin telecommunications consultant who also
had not yet had a chance to study Rate Seeker in detail, said the
$50 threshold might be too low to make it worthwhile for many
customers. But he said small businesses with a heavy load of
short-haul long-distance calls might find it worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Redfish chose Austin to launch its first product for several
reasons, including its willingness to try new technologies and a
still relatively large area code zone, Romines said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a market big enough to prove our technology and
still small enough to manage effectively,'' Romines said. ``We
won't go and bite off Southern California until we get a little
experience here in a smaller market.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will directly sell Rate Seeker by telephone, (877)
473-3347, and on the Web (www.redfishtm.com). It will advertise on
buses and radio and in print.
</P>
<P>
   Redfish Telemetrix, started in 1996 and privately held, was
founded by Romines; its president, Christopher Miner, of Newport
Beach, Calif.; and Lance Brewer, a Costa Mesa lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
