<P>
   OUTDOORS
</P>
<P>
   SCUBA-DIVING _ Scuba diving, once thought of as dangerous sport
only for the most adventurous outdoorsperson, is becoming safer
every year. Now, nearly anybody can dive, and many are, judging by
the increase in participants. And the sport also is becoming more
family-oriented; even day care is provided by some dive packages.
The industry also is considering lowering the minimum age to be
certified from 12 to 10. (Bernarde, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOOR-ALMANAC _ The outdoors almanac, braggin' rights, on the
bookshelf, the week ahead, product reviews, etc. (Bernarde,
Mitchell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-CLUB-EXPO _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Don't call them a bag of
sticks. At least not this weekend, when more than 600 custom golf
club makers from 41 states and 10 countries are in town for the
10th annual Golf Clubmakers Association International hosted by
Austin-based manufacturer Golfsmith International Inc. (Breyer,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOHLS-COLUMN _ DALLAS _ The team's best quarterback is throwing
passes some 10 hours and another football classification away for
Division I-AA Murray State. The wishbone offense implemented in the
spring has been junked. Its three best offensive linemen were
injured last week, two of them out for the season. The losing
streak is two in a row and counting. Life goes on as usual at the
University of Oklahoma, if you can call this living. (Bohls, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
