</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just a matter of time until OU boots Blake
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The team's best quarterback is throwing passes some 10
hours and another football classification away for Division I-AA
Murray State. The wishbone offense implemented in the spring has
been junked. Its three best offensive linemen were injured last
week, two of them out for the season. The losing streak is two in a
row and counting.
</P>
<P>
   Life goes on as usual at the University of Oklahoma, if you can
call this living.
</P>
<P>
   Most Sooners fans would not, which is why they are bracing
themselves for the worst after the ugliest back-to-back seasons in
school history _ 4-8 and 3-8. Three years into the rebuilding era
under first-time head coach John Blake, OU doesn't seem anywhere
nearer to being a finished product than it was when it fired Howard
Schnellenberger after one desultory season in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only thing close to meeting a construction schedule
was Blake's lavish, just-completed, $598,000 home in northwest
Norman. Many north of the Red River feel the 36-year-old head coach
made his bed, but he might be allowed to live in it only another
few months.
</P>
<P>
   The book on Blake is he'll be looking for work after the season
finale against Texas Tech on Nov. 21 even though he has two years
left on a five-year deal paying him about $575,000. Critics would
call him the Gerry Faust of Oklahoma but for fear of insulting the
former deposed coach of Notre Dame. Blake could be the worst hire
in college football history.
</P>
<P>
   The line to succeed the 20th head coach at OU will form behind
Tulane's hot commodity Tommy Bowden and Georgia's Jim Donnan, a
former Sooners offensive coordinator who has been bypassed for the
OU job three times and never been interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern's Gary Barnett might have taken the job if Oklahoma
only had been willing to wait until after the 1995 Rose Bowl to
make a decision, and he might be interested again. There's even the
annual Lou Holtz sighting when it comes to head coaching
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   The bleak Blake situation at OU couldn't be any more
diametrically opposed to Mack Brown's rose-petaled foundation at
Texas. Quite simply, while Brown is the second coming of Darrell
Royal, OU just wishes Blake would go.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has unified every UT faction, healed any divisiveness
created by his predecessor, made tremendous recruiting strides and
is riding an early crest of goodwill and even better coaching moves
that have endeared him to Longhorns everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, on the other hand, has been vilified for lying to the
media, alienating some high school coaches, failing to have a clue
on offense and just not having the organizational or communication
skills necessary to lead a program.
</P>
<P>
   Writers say Blake has rubdowns during office hours, rarely held
staff meetings last year and quit talking to his starting
quarterback at midseason. Last recruiting season, OU courted two
dropback passers and two option quarterbacks. Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Blake has ditched the wishbone, claiming star tailback De'Mond
Parker can't block well enough even though his blocking has never
been highly regarded. Blake ran off quarterback Justin Fuente, who
this season has passed for 1,448 yards and 14 touchdowns for the
4-1 Murray State Racers. The revolving door continues at
quarterback, but split end Eric Moore moved back to quarterback and
could be a surprise under center today.
</P>
<P>
   After Berry Tramel's column in The Daily Oklahoman railed on
Blake's stupid decisions but stopped short of calling for his head,
more than 150 e-mails that arrived a day later were running 4-to-1
against Blake. Future schedules bring games with Notre Dame, UCLA
and Alabama, and Nebraska and Kansas State return in the Big 12
rotation in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What really cuts Oklahomans to the quick was their inability to
lure Brown to Norman as Gary Gibbs' successor after the 1994
season. Then-athletic director Donnie Duncan felt he had the North
Carolina coach all but signed until Watson Brown, Gibbs' offensive
coordinator, intervened and begged his brother not to ruin his own
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Mack gentlemanly bowed out in deference to Watson, and for
Sooners fans the rest is misery.
</P>
<P>
   Since OU turned to Howard Schnellenberger in a disaster that was
compounded by the hiring of Barry Switzer's hand-picked choice of
Blake, the bowl-less Sooners have won only 14 of the last 38 games.
</P>
<P>
   Over that same span in North Carolina and Texas, Mack Brown's
squads boast a 30-12 record. His last three North Carolina teams
went to bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns have finished in the Top 25 three of the last four
years. The Sooners can't claim a Top 25 finish since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, sitting at 2-2 with only one team with a losing record
among its final seven opponents, almost certainly has to win six
games and probably beat Texas or Oklahoma State or both to save his
job. Won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   After Texas' 34-24 win today, OU will get that much closer to
realizing its mistake and doing something to correct it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
