<SLUG> BC-GOLF-CLUB-EXPO11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf makers around the globe link up at Austin trade show
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Don't call them a bag of sticks.
</P>
<P>
   At least not this weekend, when more than 600 custom golf club
makers from 41 states and 10 countries _ folks who go by names such
as Jack the Gripper and the King of Clubs _ are in town for the
10th annual Golf Clubmakers Association International hosted by
Austin-based manufacturer Golfsmith International Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin conference, which runs through Monday, is the world's
largest annual event for golf club makers.
</P>
<P>
   Participants are in town for classes such as ``The Cardinal
Rules of Club Fitting'' and ``New Realizations of Shaft Fitting.''
They'll get to see the test results from a Golfsmith swing robot.
There's a trade show and hands-on technical demonstrations. And of
course, like any conference, there's a golf tournament, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Golfsmith is widely known for its 23 golf superstores
in the United States and Canada, the company got its start in 1967
as a club component company. Founders Carl and Barbara Paul sold
the club parts out of their two-bedroom apartment.
</P>
<P>
   For 31 years, Golfsmith has assembled golf components and
shipped them to 90 countries, evolving into the largest mail-order
supplier of golf equipment and accessories in the world. The
company ships thousands of orders a day from its
190,000-square-foot headquarters at 11000 N. Interstate 35, making
it is one of United Parcel Service's largest Central Texas
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although our retail business has been in the news, the
component side of the business is still very important to us,''
Nancy Nesbitt, spokeswoman for Golfsmith, said of the weekend's
conference. ``We're getting back to our roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
