<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0138 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-CHICAGO-MARATHON-     10-10 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CHICAGO-MARATHON-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: ILL., N.Y.)  
 SEEKING A RECORD AND A U.S. UNIFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Khalid Khannouchi and his wife is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(ak) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSSINING, N.Y. _ For Sunday's Chicago Marathon, where he has a
chance for a repeat victory and a world record, Khalid Khannouchi
will follow a familiar ritual.
</P>
<P>
   First, he will slip on a ring bearing the likeness of a dolphin.
The ring was given to him by his wife and coach, Sandra, who
believes that dolphins bring good luck. She keeps dolphin good-luck
charms all over the house: dolphin plates, dolphin figurines,
dolphin sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Khannouchi will give her husband a kiss at the start, and
then she will run a short portion of the 26.2-mile race. Maybe a
couple of miles. Once she was a serious runner herself, but now she
runs with her husband more for ceremony than for achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to see me there; it calms him down and makes him feel
better,'' she said. ``It sounds stupid, but we don't want to
change. Why break something that's been working?''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in his first marathon, Khalid Khannouchi won Chicago
in 2 hours 7 minutes 10 seconds, then the fourth-fastest time in
history. His was a classic immigrant's tale. He had come from
Morocco to Brooklyn four years earlier, washing dishes in a
restaurant, training after midnight on potholed streets, determined
to make it as a world-class runner.
</P>
<P>
   After dropping out of a race in Hartford in 1995, he sought a
ride home and got one from the woman who would become his coach,
his agent, his masseuse, his nutritionist and his wife. And after
Chicago, he became an international star who hoped to gain his U.S.
citizenship in time to compete at the 2000 Summer Olympics in
Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely that Khannouchi, 27, will run for the United
States in Sydney, given the strict requirements for obtaining
citizenship. And setting a world record on the fast Chicago course
this weekend has become considerably more challenging. On Sept. 20,
Ronaldo da Costa of Brazil lowered the record by a stunning 45
seconds, to 2:06:05 from 2:06:50, by running the second half of the
Berlin Marathon in a searing 1:01:23 after running the first half
in 1:04:42.
</P>
<P>
   Da Costa lowered his personal best by three full minutes in that
race. Sandra Khannouchi said she wondered if the Berlin course was
accurately measured. Khalid Khannouchi said he was happy for da
Costa but surprised at the time, because the Brazilian had not
given much indication that he was ready to run that fast. He was
especially taken aback by da Costa's ability to run the second half
three minutes faster than he ran the first half. ``A lot of people
can run under 2:06:05, but I don't think anyone else is going to
run it that way,'' Khalid Khannouchi said. ``It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three other sub-2:08 marathoners running the flat,
inviting course in Chicago: Elijah Legat and Moses Tanui of Kenya
and Gert Thys of South Africa. If da Costa's time is daunting,
Khalid Khannouchi said, the others can take encouragement from the
fact that they have beaten him routinely in other road races.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are thinking, `If da Costa can run 2:06, I can run
better,''' he said. ``I have run with him many times and I always
beat him by one or two minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   To set a record, Khannouchi feels he must run the first half of
Chicago faster than the 1:04:10 he ran last year. He will be happy
if he finishes in 2:07 or better, Khannouchi said. Finishing first
is as important as finishing fast. He was stung last year by
remarks that his Chicago victory was somehow a fluke, that he was a
lucky rookie who hit a home run his first time at bat. ``I have an
opportunity to prove that it wasn't a fluke,'' Khannouchi said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last June, the Khannouchis moved out of Brooklyn to the quieter
streets of Ossining; Khalid trains in nearby Rockefeller State Park
Preserve, where the traffic travels on feet or hooves, not tires.
He enters the 1998 race with fewer races and fresher legs. Last
month, he set a world record for 20 kilometers (12.4 miles) of 57
minutes 37 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he was a road racer who had to be coaxed into
running a marathon by his wife. Sandra Khannouchi is a former 2:42
marathon runner for her native Dominican Republic. She knew that
fast times were in her husband's legs before he did. Now that he is
a star, everybody is interested in him. Even the Moroccan track and
field federation.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi left his homeland because, he said, he was not
allowed to travel to important competitions. Now that officials
want him to represent Morocco, he is not interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to have anything to do with them,'' Khannouchi
said.
</P>
<P>
   A onetime soccer player who did not begin running until he was
15 or 16, Khannouchi now dreams of running for the United States in
the 2000 Summer Games. However, he received his green card only
last month and must now wait three years before he is eligible for
citizenship. He is seeking congressional help, but the Immigration
and Naturalization Service has been reluctant to speed up
citizenship for someone simply because he is an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my dream,'' Khannouchi said. ``I want to do it for my
country. I got a lot of help and support here. I got my family
here. I got my career. I got everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
