<SLUG> BC-NJ-NEWARK-ARTS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS DISCUSS HOW THE ARTS CAN AID NEWARK, N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: GREAT BRITAIN, Calif., Ohio, Pa., S.C.)  (mk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The arts saved Cleveland and Pittsburgh and they
can save Newark, too, participants in a conference at Rutgers
University were told Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, titled ``Arts Transforming the Urban
Environment,'' brought together experts from around the world to
discuss ways that cities can discover an identity, take pride in
their cultural attractions and find the money to rebuild and
revitalize themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Such thoughts have been on many minds in Newark in the year
since the $180 million New Jersey Performing Arts Center opened
with the goal of reviving a city in a protracted physical, social
and economic decline. Because of ``Newark's large civic gamble on
the arts,'' as Annette Juliano, a professor of art history at
Rutgers, put it, the conference was organized to explore and learn
from other communities' efforts. The four-day conference is
sponsored by Rutgers and ends Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Civic leaders from Cleveland and Pittsburgh described how
arts-related construction and arts districts had revitalized their
cities, and officials from Charleston, S.C., said the preservation
of that city's distinctive cultural heritage had sustained it. But
beyond the talk of bricks and mortar, there were insights into the
arts' less tangible benefits.
</P>
<P>
   South African artists described using art and culture to create
a ``nonthreatening zone'' in which blacks and whites could come
together in a still tense post-apartheid Johannesburg. Adolfo
Nodal, Los Angeles' general manager of cultural affairs, said the
introduction of a chamber music group into a crime-ridden park had
made it safer.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this role for art and artists is an old one, said
Trevor Phillips, chairman of the London Arts Board. He read
passages from Dickens' novels about the squalor of 19th-century
London and noted that the public outcry the novels had provoked had
led to reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been romantic to see the artist as a marginal
figure in society,'' Phillips said, ``but they are at the center of
things. When we talk about culture, we are talking about all of the
artistic endeavor a people can muster to say where they have been,
what they are and where they are going.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In one workshop, Lawrence Goldman, president of the Performing
Arts Center, said that in the past, growth of the arts and culture
followed economic development. But in the last 15 years, he said,
the order has been reversed in many cities. As generators of
revenue, centers like Newark's rank below sports stadiums in the
eyes of public officials, but that will change, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with stadiums, cultural centers are ``the bargain of
the century,'' said Art Falco, president of Cleveland's Playhouse
Square Foundation, which spent $55 million a decade ago to renovate
four historic but run-down theaters into a downtown arts district.
Falco said studies had shown that the city's arts sector in 1994
generated $165 million in revenues for the city, compared with $79
million from its sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Trust for Cultural Resources transformed that
city's red-light district with performance and gallery spaces, said
Carol Brown, president of the trust. According to a recent survey,
the new arts district, nestled on the banks of the Allegheny River,
draws up to 35 percent more visitors annually than the city's
sports arenas do, she said.
</P>
<P>
   What this investment in the arts says about a society and its
people remains a crucial question, said Stanley Katz, director of
the Center for Arts and Cultural Policy at Princeton University.
Katz said he wondered whether large halls like Newark's were an
efficient way of accomplishing social goals like instilling an
appreciation for the arts in children, and whether efforts to
promote cultural tourism were good ways to invest public and
private funds in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question in the end,'' said Katz, ``is not so much
whether there is economic development, but whether there is civic
development and a move to a more civil society. What is the real
relationship between the jobs created and the building of a civil
society?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
