<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-PITCHERS-800(2TAK     10-10 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PITCHERS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATING LEAGUE LINEUPS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla., Md., Ill., Mich.)    (jw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Kevin Brown, who has been the most dominant pitcher
in the postseason, will be a free agent in a couple of weeks.
Baseball executives only shake their heads when they are asked what
they think he will get. Pedro Martinez, at $12.5 million a year, is
the highest-paid player at the moment. Start somewhere north of
that figure.
</P>
<P>
   With one run and eight hits allowed in three postseason starts,
Brown has pitched the San Diego Padres to the cusp of the World
Series. Whether he winds up staying with the Padres or going
elsewhere, the 33-year-old right-hander is expected to remain in
the National League.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, some executives believe, pitchers prefer the
National League over the American. Gene Budig, the AL president,
and his chief aide, Phyllis Merhige, shouldn't take it personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free-agent pitchers don't want to go to the American League,''
Doug Melvin, general manager of the Texas Rangers, said.
``Basically, it has to do with facing the designated hitter instead
of the pitcher. In the American League, you have Scott Brosius
driving in 98 runs batting ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the NL, Melvin said, pitchers bat ninth and that makes the
No. 8 hitter ``someone you can pitch around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a pitcher,'' he added, ``you have to look at that. I've
heard pitchers comment on how it's a mental grind to have to go
through an American League lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Minaya, the Mets' assistant general manager, who previously
worked under Melvin in Texas, said NL parks, strike zones and
earned run averages also make the league more attractive.
Furthermore, he said, not only does the pitcher as batter make the
NL lineup easier to negotiate, but NL teams also often sacrifice
hitting for defense with their middle infielders so the lineup
becomes even less hazardous to pitchers' health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard pitchers often say they like the National League,''
Minaya said. ``Seeing the way Randy Johnson pitched, he must really
like the National League.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson indeed will join Brown in the free-agent market. Al
Leiter will be in that group, too, unless the Mets cut him off at
the pass and re-sign him before he becomes a free agent. Whether he
remains with the Mets or goes elsewhere, Leiter is one of those who
prefers the NL.
</P>
<P>
   Not all pitchers opt for the NL, Leiter said, citing David Cone
and Roger Clemens as two who have stayed in the American. But he
noted that he and Clemens have the same agents, the Hendricks
brothers, and said, ``I tell Alan all the time, if Roger
experienced what National League baseball was all about, he'd want
to be there, too _ getting up to hit, bunting, playing creative
baseball. It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, who began his career in the AL, added, ``If they
actually experienced it, I can't imagine any pitcher choosing the
AL as long as you had equal deals or didn't have a family reason
for being somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And the presence of the pitcher in the lineup instead of the DH?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had arguments with other pitchers who don't believe it's
as important as I do,'' he said. ``I think it changes the dynamics
of a whole season. I'm not talking about the difference in two or
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Facing Brosius instead of Leiter, second and third and Brosius
coming up, I better be careful. Second and third and the eighth
hitter coming up with the pitcher in the hole, I know what I can
do. That over the course of 200-plus innings can mean the
difference of 15 to 20 runs, and that can be the difference between
a 2.5 and a 3.1 ERA or a 3.1 and a 3.8.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter pitched with Brown on the Florida Marlins in 1996 and '97
_those Florida Marlins _ and has enjoyed watching Brown become the
dominant pitcher he has been with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's good, and he obviously has the numbers to back
him up,'' Leiter said. ``He's feeling comfortable about himself as
a person rather than listening to people saying he is an
underachiever and talk about these mental things that went with
him. Those things bogged him down a little bit. Now he knows he can
dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has a reputation of being difficult with managers and
players, but Leiter said, ``He's a pussy cat as far as I'm
concerned. He was one of the nicer guys on the team. He might say
some things that you wouldn't normally say, but if you get to know
him he's certainly able to take criticism and communicates well
enough to not get anyone teed off.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, who became the Texas general manager just as Brown was
leaving there as a free agent, said the pitcher's attitude has
always been questioned but asked, ``Is it an attitude or a hungry
desire to win?''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies plan to find out firsthand. Several
baseball executives said they expect the Rockies to pursue Brown as
aggressively as any player has been pursued.  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
