<HEADLINE>
A SIMILAR TALE  
 A BIPARTISAN PITCH  
 MEMORIES OF BELANGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy Johnson, meet Doyle Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was traded to Houston minutes before the trading
deadline July 31, then proceeded to compile a 10-1 record and a
1.28 ERA in 11 starts for the Astros, who won their division
championship. Johnson pitched four shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Alexander was traded to Detroit in mid-August, then
reeled off nine victories without a loss and posted a 1.53 ERA in
11 starts. He pitched three shutouts and gave up no runs in two
other starts totaling 15 innings. The Tigers, who were in second
place when they acquired Alexander from Atlanta, won all 11 of his
starts and edged Toronto for the division title
</P>
<P>
   In the playoffs this year, Johnson allowed San Diego only three
earned runs in 14 innings but lost both of his starts as the Padres
won the division series.
</P>
<P>
   In the league championship series in 1987, Alexander also lost
twice, his near-perfect pitching punctured as he gave up 10 runs in
9 innings. The Tigers lost the series to the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   A BIPARTISAN PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Before the House of Representatives last week passed the Curt
Flood Act altering baseball's antitrust exemption, several members
spoke in favor of the bill. Among the speakers were Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., and John Conyers, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been the last time this year Hyde and Conyers are
on the same side of an issue. Hyde is chairman and Conyers the
ranking Democrat of the House Judiciary Committee, which will spend
the rest of the year investigating whether or not there are grounds
for the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIES OF BELANGER
</P>
<P>
   As a labor leader, David Cone said, Mark Belanger ``had a lot of
Marvin Miller in him.'' In labor circles anywhere, no one could pay
anyone a higher compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was executive director of the Major League Baseball
Players Association when Belanger first became involved with the
union as the alternate player representative for the Baltimore
Orioles in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the younger reps, at least in the beginning, would
be spectators,'' Miller said. ``Mark never was. He was an activist
at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger, a union official since he retired as a player in 1982,
died last week at the age of 54. He lived through every work
stoppage baseball has had. No one else on the players' side was
involved in all five strikes and three lockouts as Belanger was as
a player and a union official.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely conscientious,'' Miller recalled. ``Player
reps came in all sizes and shapes. This one was there when the
meeting opened and there when the meeting closed, actively asking
questions, making appropriate comments, being an active part of
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He developed all along, and by the time we got to the 1980 and
'81 negotiations, he was remarkably valuable. He had a kind of feel
for all of the nuances of those negotiations as they went from one
phase to another and we knew a strike was inevitable. He was
completely reliable when you wanted honest feedback, when you
wanted to check your own reactions. That was a very valuable asset
when you're in a crisis mode.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger also was a very valuable asset to the Orioles as a
shortstop, the best defensively of his time. He harbored no false
modesty about his ability. Doyle Pryor, a union lawyer, recalled a
story that attested to Belanger's view.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said he was telling Belanger one day about a shortstop he
had read about who was being touted as his team's shortstop of the
future. It'll never happen, Belanger said. Why not, Pryor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him play in spring training,'' Pryor said Belanger
replied. ``A ball went through his legs.''
</P>
<P>
   So? Pryor asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never happened to me,'' Belanger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
