<HEADLINE>
YANKS WIN AS TEAM, AND STRUGGLE AS TEAM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Yankees distinguished themselves with 114
victories during the regular season by pushing themselves hard
through otherwise meaningless games. They took the lowly Kansas
City Royals as seriously as they did the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But the intensity that worked so well for the Yankees for six
months has seemed to be working against them in the playoffs. Going
into Game 4 of the American League Championship Series here
Saturday night, they had fallen into their worst offensive slump of
the year, and their manager seemed convinced that at its core, the
trouble was that everybody was trying too hard. The Yankees had
just four hits in losing, 6-1, to the Cleveland Indians in Game 3
here Friday night, to fall behind by 2-1 in the four-of-seven-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure I'm concerned about us not swinging the bats,''
Manager Joe Torre said. ``Everybody is trying to do it themselves
because we are going through a little bit of a flat time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Yankees had not been through anything like this all
year. They had scored a total of two runs in Games 2 and 3, or one
fewer than they scored in any two-game span this season. After
scoring five runs in the first inning of Game 1 in this series, the
Yankees had managed just four runs in the last 28 innings, and were
batting .167 over all and .125 with runners in scoring position.
And their slump had roots more than a weeklong: They scored just
nine runs in three games of the Division Series against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have better at-bats, we need to put better swings
on pitches,'' said Joe Girardi, the Yankee catcher. ``When you get
in situations like this, guys tend to try to do a little bit too
much. You just need to get back to where you were and do what your
part is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's Bartolo Colon finished with a four-hitter in Game 3,
allowing one run, but he was staggering through the first three
innings. He could not throw any of his breaking pitches for
strikes; he appeared uncomfortable and frustrated on the mound.
During the second inning, both Sandy Alomar, his catcher, and Mark
Wiley, the Indians' pitching coach, went to the mound to settle
him.
</P>
<P>
   But when the window of opportunity was open on Friday night, the
Yankees did not go through. They scored a run in the first inning
and Chili Davis led off the second with a walk, before Shane
Spencer worked Colon to a three-ball count. But Spencer swung
wildly at what appeared to be ball four, a collarbone-high
fastball; he eventually struck out, and instead of having runners
at first and second and no outs, the rally was stunted.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill walked with one out in the third, before Bernie
Williams grounded into a double play, the first of three turned by
the Indians. Cleveland scored four runs in the fifth inning, and
Colon started throwing all of his pitches for strikes, his fastball
reaching 98 mph in the ninth inning. And that was all. ``We got
some pitches to hit,'' Torre said, ``fouled them off and hit some
balls hard, but double plays played a big part in his success early
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees played the game as if they expected to struggle for
runs. Chuck Knoblauch led off the first inning with a single and
Derek Jeter then bunted, apparently on his own; all year, Torre has
told Jeter he does not want him sacrificing himself, but Jeter felt
compelled to push ahead a runner.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the second inning, Torre ordered the infield to
play in with the score tied at 1-1 and a runner at third base, a
sign that Torre was unwilling to trade an out for a run in the
early innings and intended to cut off every run possible.
</P>
<P>
   Torre suggested afterward that he would probably alter his
lineup for Game 4 Saturday night, and for starters it figured that
Spencer _ who was 1 for 10 in the series, his glass slippers at
least a little cracked _ would be replaced by either Chad Curtis or
Tim Raines in left field. But it was not as if just one or two
Yankees were struggling. Most of the regulars seemed to be fighting
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter challenged Williams for the lead in the American League's
batting race in early September, but as the end of the season drew
near, Jeter seemed intent on hitting his 20th homer. As Torre has
mentioned, Jeter's swing changed down the stretch: He was trying to
pull the baseball, rather than maintaining his usual approach of
driving the ball to the opposite field or through the middle. Jeter
went 1 for 9 against Texas in the Division Series before getting
two hits in Game 1 of this series, but he did not appear
comfortable at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was batting .333 in this series, 4 for 12, but he was
having difficultly keeping himself from chasing high fastballs out
of the strike zone when he batted left-handed. Williams started
slowly because of this tendency, and got hot when he stopped
chasing the high fastballs. The Yankees needed him to be more
patient.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez, the Yankees' first baseman, was mired deeply in a
funk from which it seemed he might never emerge in this
post-season. Martinez was hitless in 13 at-bats in the series, with
6 strikeouts, and there had been times in the first three games
when he appeared to have no clue as to what he wanted to do, and no
confidence that he would execute. Martinez is like Andy Pettitte:
The harder he tries, the worse he gets.
</P>
<P>
   One baseball executive watching the playoffs said that
Martinez's problems might start with his hands: In the past,
Martinez's hands were ``quiet,'' or very still. Now he was waggling
the bat as he waited for a pitch, a habit that might cause him to
start his swing an instant too slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Raines is a disciplined hitter who usually has good at-bats, but
already Raines had four strikeouts in his first six at-bats in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is a patient hitter who knows how to draw walks, work
pitchers and extend an inning, and with that approach, he can help
the Yankees' production _ so long as the hitters around him are
contributing. But with Williams and Martinez slumping ahead of him
and Spencer and the catchers' struggling behind him, Davis' walks
were benign.
</P>
<P>
   At the time that Darryl Strawberry's cancer was diagnosed, it
did not appear as if the Yankees would miss him on the field. After
all, Spencer was hitting, providing power, and Davis and Raines
have the experience to share time as the designated hitter. Now,
Torre probably would love to have Strawberry as an option, for his
big left-handed swing, for the potential of an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Torre could have dropped Martinez in the lineup, but that might
have only added to Martinez's already phenomenal collection of
angst. Torre could have promoted Scott Brosius _ the Yankees' most
consistent hitter in the post-season _ into the middle of the
lineup, but Brosius moved higher in the lineup early in the year
and never seemed comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   What Torre likely would do, other than a change in lineup, was
wait for them to start hitting, for the leaders O'Neill and Jeter
to propel a breakout. ``We need to have fun,'' Torre said, knowing
full well that if the Yankees didn't, they could be home soon,
thinking about what might have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
