<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-REFUGEES _ TIRANA, Albania _ As ethnic Albanian refugees
flee the violence and coming winter in Yugoslavia's southern
province of Kosovo, thousands have come to northern Albania. We
talk to them, the people who are taking them in and humanitarian
groups about the refugees' plight, and how they plan to survive the
winter. (Roughton, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-REFUGE _ TIRANA, Albania _ In the midst of all the
turmoil of trying to care for and house tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanian refugees flooding into this country from Yugoslavia's
Kosovo province, one man's efforts to help stands out. An ethnic
Albanian who left Kosovo for a better life with his family in
Switzerland many years ago, the man returned to Albania to build
apartments. Before he could finish putting windows and doors on his
first building, the refugee crisis erupted. Seeing that the people
needed shelter, he borrowed $8,000 to finish the building and is
now housing _ for free _ 108 people in 24 apartments. Although they
are sleeping on floors with no lights and running water, to them he
is a godsend. (Roughton, Cox News Service, 450 words).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTO to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN _ BEIJING _ China and Taiwan have stepped gingerly
in recent weeks to avoid stamping on each other's sensitive
political toes. They are getting ready for the highest level public
contact since 1993, a resumption of ``cross-straits talks'' (Oct.
14-19) that seek a way for peaceful co-existence between the giant
communist China and the small democratic island that broke away in
1949. Despite the gentle words heard lately _ Taiwan canceled
military exercises, China promised unprecedented concessions if the
two unite again _ deep differences remain. And the stakes are huge.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BIOBOX _ BEIJING _ A bio box on the two negotiators, Wang
Daohan of China (Shanghai's former mayor and an aging mentor of
China's President Jiang Zemin) and Koo Chen-fu, a political elder
in Taiwan. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Now that the 105th Congress is
history, how many of President Clinton's lofty legislative goals
for this year have survived the storms of scandal and partisanship?
A scorecard for the agenda Clinton laid out in his State of Union
address in January. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ Glenn is everywhere at the Kennedy Space Center. There's
John Glenn memorabilia at the gift shop. And when people enter the
KSC visitors center they see a giant mural of Glenn that says
GODSPEED JOHN GLENN, and visitors are signing it, wishing him luck.
This story looks at how the excitement has already taken over this
part of Florida. (Montgomery, Cox News Service). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVATE _ A caravan of buses and vans will pull into the back of
James D. Ray State Prison just before dawn Tuesday with the first
50 medium-security Georgia convicts to be locked up by corporate
America. This is the future, for better or worse. (Cook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES _ Ten years after the federal government sued Florida
for letting sugar growers pollute the Everglades, a judge in Miami
is about to rule. The hearing Oct. 13 will find the Feds, the state
and sugar on the same side _ all saying that the Everglades cleanup
is going so well that judge should do nothing. But environmental
groups and the Miccosukee Indian tribe say the cleanup is moving
too slowly, violates the federal Clean Water Act, and is plagued by
insufficient money, an interfering legislature and constant
undermining by sugar growers. U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler
(who presided over the trials of Manuel Noriega and Cali drug
cartel members) could do just about anything: dismiss the case,
call it to trial or put a federal overseer in charge of the
cleanup. (King, Palm Beach Post). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With box on the players and their positions.
</P>
<P>
   BILL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hilda Meltzer is 71 years old,
lives alone in a subsidized one-bedroom apartment, has $700 in the
bank and goes out to dinner once a month. She hasn't bought a dress
since 1996 _ and it might be a lot longer if the government gets
what it's looking for: Meltzer received a letter last month telling
her she owes Social Security $18,000. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   REDFISH-PHONE-SERVICE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Trying to pin down just
which long-distance company really offers the lowest rate has given
more than one consumer a big headache. Many give up. But Redfish
Telemetrix, a newcomer operating out of Austin and Costa Mesa,
Calif., will start selling on Monday what it bills as the answer:
Rate Seeker, a gadget that attaches to the telephone and, on each
long-distance call, dials using the company charging the lowest
rate at that moment. (Hight, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INSURE-DISCRIMINATE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas insurance companies
have managed to block a Fort Worth legislator's attempt to have an
industry critic review their business practices to make sure Texans
are getting affordable insurance. (Elizondo, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The head of South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission _ charged with exorcising the specter of
that country's racist past _ told an audience at the University of
Texas Law School that the United States must better examine its own
racial conflicts. (Shah, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
