<HEADLINE>
STRATEGY, NOT SPEED, WILL BE KEY IN ARKANSAS  
 AROUND ALONE UPDATE  
 NORTH AMERICAN CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: FRANCE, Ark., Conn., N.Y.)  (ak) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the half-million people who live within 30 minutes of Lake
Maumelle in Little Rock, Ark., access to clear water and
undeveloped hillsides is part of the metropolitan landscape. But
the area, which is staging a national sailing championship this
week, is not your average port of call for yachting's elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are curious,'' said Drew Daugherty, the regatta
chairman. ``Many have never sailed in Arkansas before. We get
comments like, `What coast is that on?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen sailing teams will be arriving for the Championship of
Champions, one of 11 major regattas sponsored this year by Rolex
Watch U.S.A. U.S. Sailing, the sport's governing body, invited the
1998 champions of about 80 one-design classes in the country. On
average, 20 teams show up at the event, said Greg Fisher, U.S.
Sailing's committee chairman for the 22nd annual event.
Three-member crews will be competing Wednesday through Friday in a
fleet of Flying Scots, 19-foot sloops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always look for new and different places to have
regattas,'' Fisher said. ``The Grande Maumelle Sailing Club is one
of the most active and competitive clubs in the country. Not that
many sailors on the East and West Coast know about it. But it has a
very strong background in one-design sailing. When we asked them if
they wanted to do this race, they jumped at the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, just ask David Dellenbaugh, an America's Cup veteran
from Easton, Conn., about sailing in Little Rock. ``I didn't even
know they had a lake there,'' Dellenbaugh said. Lake Maumelle,
which is about 10 miles long, is used as a reservoir for Little
Rock's drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Dellenbaugh, a tactical expert who sailed as the
only man on the women's Mighty Mary America's Cup team in 1995,
expects a demanding competition. ``It probably will be a tactical
series as opposed to a boat speed contest,'' he said. ``The fleet
of Flying Scots all have new sails, which ought to make the boats
fairly equal in speed.''
</P>
<P>
   As publisher of a monthly newsletter on race tactics, Speed and
Smarts, Dellenbaugh plans to play every angle. To keep his team's
weight down _ a race tactic for medium-to-light winds _ Dellenbaugh
has asked his sailing partner, Jimmy Crane, to bring his
12-year-old son, Robbie, as the third crew member. The Dellenbaugh
crew weighs about 450 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Sailing against them will be some of the best one-design racers
in the country. They include George Szabo, of San Diego, two-time
defender of the title. He is also this year's titlist in the highly
competitive Snipe class.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite to win is Kelly Gough, an Olympic contender in
1980, who is national champion in the Flying Scot. Other one-design
classes represented include the Lightning, Thistle, Y-Flyer, Blue
Jay, Holder 20 and Ensign.
</P>
<P>
   Around Alone Update
</P>
<P>
   The French, who have long had a lock on single-handed racing,
are leading so far in the Around Alone, a sailboat race around the
world for solo skippers. Ahead by 50 miles in Class I is Marc
Thiercelin, skipper of the 60-foot racer Somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In Class II, Pierre Mouligne leads a pack of nine 50-foot boats
by only a few miles. The leaders are about 4,500 miles from their
first stopover, Cape Town. The 26,000-mile race began Sept. 26 from
Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Thiercelin's French rival, Isabelle Autissier, was ahead until
last week, when she broke the forestay on her 60-foot yacht, PRB.
The rigging problem prevented Autissier from flying her largest
genoa through light winds last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Thiercelin and Autissier were the first to break off from
the easterly track most of the fleet took after leaving
Charleston,'' said Herb McCormick, a race spokesman. ``They were
the first to dip south toward Cape Town after riding out a
southwesterly breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   Autissier has dropped to fourth in Class I. Ahead of her, but
within 100 miles, are Josh Hall on Gartmore Investment Management,
and Mike Golding on Team Group 4.
</P>
<P>
   North American Championship
</P>
<P>
   One of the few mostly amateur big-boat classes in the country,
the J/44, has gathered 11 boats this weekend on Long Island Sound
for the 1998 North American Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his 1997 title is Jimmie Sundstrom of Rye, N.Y.,
skipper and owner of the J/44 Stampede. The three-day regatta began
Saturday at the Seawanhaka Corinthian Yacht Club in Oyster Bay,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
