Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) OSSINING, N.Y. -- Oct. 10, 1998 --
RUN-CHICAGO-MARATHON-1, 10-10 -- Khalid Khannouchi, 27, training
for Sunday's Chicago Marathon. He won Chicago last year in his very
first marathon, in 2 hours 7 minutes 10 seconds, then the
fourth-fastest time in history. Only four years earlier, Khannouchi
had come from Morocco to Brooklyn, washing dishes in a restaurant,
training after midnight on potholed streets, determined to make it
as a world-class runner. (George M. Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) ROME -- Oct. 10, 1998 -- CANONIZATION-STEIN, 10-10 --
Benedicta McCarthy and Emmanuel Charles McCarthy at St. Peter's
Square before the canonization of her namesake, Sister Teresia
Benedicta. Benedicta had been named for Edith Stein, the Jewish
philosopher who was killed in Auschwitz as Sister Teresia
Benedicta, the name she took when she converted to Catholicism and
became a nun. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SILVER HILL, Md. -- Oct. 10, 1998 -- AIR&AMP;SPACE-ANNEX,
10-10 -- Robert Padgett works to restore treasures that are part of
the Smithsonian Institution's National Air and Space Museum
collection. The items are currently stored in a complex of
warehouses throughout Maryland. But the Air and Space Museum is
hoping to move some of them to a new display place soon. The museum
expects to complete design work next month on a giant new
exhibition hall at Washington Dulles International Airport. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 10, 1998 -- PODESTA-PROFILE, 10-10 --
John David Podesta, currently the White House deputy chief of
staff, far right, during a White House news conference on Friday,
has been repeatedly dragged back to a damage control post. Podesta
has led efforts to defend President Clinton against accusations
over the Whitewater land deal, dismissals at the White House travel
office and, most recently, Monica Lewinsky. White House aides say
Podesta is likely to become the next chief of staff. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 10, 1998 -- CLIFFORD-OBIT, 10-10 --
Clark Clifford with President Lyndon Johnson in 1964 died Saturday
morning at the age of 91 at his home in Bethesda, Md. Clifford, who
advised presidents across half a century of American history, faced
a rigorous ordeal in his final years, insisting on his innocence to
the end as he faced charges of fraud, conspiracy and taking bribes
in the biggest banking scandal in history, the collapse of the Bank
of Credit and Commerce International. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- Oct. 10, 1998 --
ALA-PENSIONLESS-COPS, 10-10 -- Willie Bies Jr., 62, joined the
Tuscaloosa, Ala., police force in 1966 and seven years after
retiring is still fighting to get into its pension plan. Bies, a
reitred corporal, is one of only two Tuscaloosa police officers to
work for 25 years without getting a pension. Like Bies, the other
officer, Herbert Harris, is black. The board of the Tuscaloosa
Police and Firemen's Pension Fund, argues that Bies and Harris are
not entitled to pensions because they did not make contributions to
the pension plan. (Michael Clemmer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CASCADE, Colo. -- Oct. 10, 1998 -- PIKES-PEAK-EROSION,
10-10 -- The unpaved road to Pikes Peak is the center of a dispute
between environmentalists and road racers. Many environmentalists
want the road paved to help control erosion. But asphalt would be a
sacrilege to auto racing fans and drivers who gather at Pikes Peak
every Fourth of July for a noisy, dusty day of events billed as the
Race to the Clouds. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
