<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-COX     10-10 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fate of Everglades in judge's hands
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Ten years ago today, the federal
government filed a landmark lawsuit accusing Florida of polluting
the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Since then:
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers have spent more than $20 million on lawyers and $137
million to start a 12-year cleanup project.
</P>
<P>
   The Feds have become allies with the state but are fighting the
lawyer who filed the suit for them.
</P>
<P>
   The pollution continues _ and probably will for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the case may finally reach a rare milestone: a
ruling from the judge.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler could merely ratify the
status quo, accepting the $763 million plan that Tallahasse and
Washington have agreed upon for cleaning polluted farm drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Miami judge, best known for presiding over the trial of
Manuel Noriega, could send the Everglades case spinning.
</P>
<P>
   He could declare the plan unconstitutional, require dramatically
shorter deadlines or appoint a federal overseer, as
environmentalists have requested at various times. State officials
say those steps would raise the costs and delay the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeveler even mused last year that he could call the case to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   All he has said lately is that he intends to rule _ on
something.
</P>
<P>
   It would be his first major move since February 1992, when he
accepted a state-federal settlement that later drowned in
challenges by the sugar industry. He never has accepted the state's
current cleanup plan or its December 2006 deadline, even though the
federal lawyers asked him to three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the sugar industry, which is blamed for the bulk of
the pollution, say it's time for Hoeveler to bow out.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that industry-financed research proves that the
Everglades' pollution problems, exaggerated to begin with, are
already ebbing. And they say the suit has served its purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we need a federal court with a hammer over our heads
when there's a plan in place that is working?'' asked Barbara
Miedema, spokeswoman for the Sugar Cane Growers Cooperative of
Florida. ``The Everglades are not on the brink of collapse, as some
would like you to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and the Miccosukee Indian tribe maintain
that Hoeveler may be the only force that can keep the state from
abandoning the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there's oversight and pressure to do it, we don't think
it can get done,'' said Miccosukee attorney Dexter Lehtinen. ``We
believe the government's going to get rid of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen was acting U.S. attorney a decade ago when he filed the
lawsuit accusing the state and the South Florida Water Management
District of funneling polluted farm drainage into the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   But as the tribe's lawyer, Lehtinen has filed numerous legal
challenges against the 1994 cleanup plan that eventually arose from
his suit. Last month, he won a ruling from another federal judge
that the plan violates the U.S. Clean Water Act by letting
pollution persist until 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, including the Florida Audubon Society and
the Sierra Club, want Hoeveler to make water managers finish the
cleanup by July 2002.
</P>
<P>
   That's the deadline water managers agreed to seven years ago,
before lawmakers approved the current plan. But they say it would
be impossible to meet that deadline now.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen said he will accept the 2006 deadline _ but not the
government's promises. He pointed to a recent court filing by the
U.S. Justice Department, which acknowledged that the cleanup will
probably miss some of the deadlines the government is asking
Hoeveler to approve.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen wants Hoeveler to appoint an expert, called a special
master, to keep track of the cleanup. He said it's a common
procedure in complex suits such as cases involving prison crowding.
</P>
<P>
   But water district lawyer Paul Nettleton said a special master
would only tangle an already complicated case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know one day to the next what Dexter is claiming,''
Nettleton said.
</P>
<P>
   The district, the state and the Justice Department have asked
Hoeveler to accept the state's plan. It relies on creating 66
square miles of marshes in Palm Beach and Hendry counties to filter
polluted water flowing into the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The drainage is laden with phosphorus, a chemical found in
fertilizer and the Glades' muck soil.Government scientists say the
phosphorus is causing thick stands of cattails to spread, driving
out saw grass and making it hard for wading birds to hunt. They say
the chemical also is killing the brown algae that form the base of
the Everglades' food chain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hoeveler's inaction, the state's Everglades Forever Act
of 1994 required water managers to start the cleanup. They finished
the first of six filter marshes last year and are in the middle of
building three others.
</P>
<P>
   The marshes can't remove all the phosphorus, and government
scientists say some other technology _ possibly doubling the price
_ will have to make the water clean enough for the Everglades'
health.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar industry scientists dispute those claims, arguing that
government research has exaggerated everything from the spread of
the cattails to the harm caused by phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Hoeveler rules, the cleanup will lie under numerous
legal clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Challenges by the Miccosukees have snarled key permits, and
water managers are feuding with the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
over the terms of their federal dredging permit. Environmentalists
also have sued the district to try to make growers pay more of the
costs.
</P>
<P>
   But water managers have overcome other hurdles, including a
now-vanished budget deficit that they once expected to exceed $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm ``Bubba'' Wade, senior vice president for United States
Sugar Corp., said he sees a pattern: Under Hoeveler's watch,
once-intractable problems have simply found solutions _ maybe
better ones than if he had ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we look back on all this 10 years from now,'' Wade said,
``we may find that Hoeveler was the smartest of all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
