<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS HITS SNAG ON EDUCATION SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Aiming to turn the protracted budget talks into a
campaign advantage, President Clinton and Democratic leaders
Saturday insisted that Congress not leave town until it approves
new money to build schools, create after-school programs, and
decrease class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have sought the money all year, but they decided to
escalate the theme Friday during a White House meeting on strategy
for 11th-hour budget talks that are now under way. Republicans said
Clinton and his colleagues were merely creating an issue to carry
into the Nov. 3 elections, and that the president had failed to
negotiate seriously for his proposals until now, when Congress is
trying to wrap up its work for the year so that members can return
home for the fall election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has missed several deadlines for approving a spending
plan for the current fiscal year, which began Oct. 1. It is now
working under a temporary plan that keeps the government running
until Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   As budget negotiations continued in meetings around the Capitol,
Democrats highlighted their push for education money in several
speeches and press conferences, previewing a message they will
carry into an election campaign dominated by news of Clinton's
affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are selling our children short. Republicans are ready to
walk away without doing anything. But we won't let them,'' House
Democratic leader Richard Gephardt said in a press conference that
featured teachers talking about the importance of small class
sizes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton used his weekly radio address to call on
Republicans to back his education plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were visibly irritated by the education campaign.
They said that if Clinton was serious about negotiating for his
proposals, he long ago would have provided a list of ``offsets,''
or proposed cuts to existing programs that could fund the
president's new plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president appears to be more interested in solidifying his
liberal base than in working with Congress on bipartisan solutions
to our problems,'' said Representative Bill Archer, the Texas
Republican who leads the House tax-writing committee.
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott said Clinton had chosen to
``demagogue'' the education issue rather than negotiate with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the late Democratic campaign had undermined the spirit
of cooperation needed to reach deals on a range of other remaining
issues, such as spending levels for hundreds of federal programs, a
possible tax cut, terms for carrying out the next census, and new
money for the International Monetary Fund, the agency arranging
emergency loans for nations hurt by the global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Progress on talks over those issues appeared modest Saturday.
``We've still got a lot of issues that we're far apart on,'' White
House Chief of Staff Erskine B. Bowles said when leaving a meeting
with Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pessimistic about our ability to come to closure on a lot
of these things by Monday night, at the pace we're going,'' said
South Dakota's Thomas Daschle, the Democratic leader in the Senate.
Most government operations will end early Tuesday morning unless a
budget deal is signed or Congress and the president agree to
another short-term funding measure.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers seized on the education theme as a way to
energize them through the budget talks and into election season.
Smaller classes, more teachers, and new schools ``are all things
that, frankly, poll well in communities around the country,'' said
a top aide to a Democratic senator. ``If they go in the omnibus''
spending bill, ``it's clear that Democrats are responsible for
that. And if they don't, it's clear that Republicans dropped the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Saturday noted that Clinton in recent weeks helped
kill a five-year, $80 billion tax cut passed by House Republicans,
to be funded by future federal budget surpluses. His main weapon
against the tax cut was his argument that the money should instead
be set aside until a plan is found to shore up the Social Security
program.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clinton wants ``to squander the surplus with a bunch of new
federal spending,'' said Senator Don Nickles, Republican of
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said they had proved their commitment to
education by passing the Higher Education Act, which cut the
interest rate on new student loans and set spending for a host of
student-aid and teacher-training programs. Republicans said they
had also passed laws this year to improve vocational education and
Head Start.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing angry at times, Lott took to the Senate floor to rail
against ``pampered people who went to private schools'' and are now
pushing more federal control of public classrooms. Lott later told
reporters that ``of course, the president and vice president never
spent a day in public school in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Republicans are proud to give more money to schools,
but they wanted decisions on how to use it to be made by local
officials rather than the federal government. ``Who do you trust on
education: the local officials, the parents, or Washington
bureaucrats?'' Lott asked.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations over the education spending and other programs has
been complicated by the lack of a sweeping settlement of lawsuits
against tobacco companies, which would have provided billions of
dollars to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Details of a tax cut were still being negotiated. The package is
expected to total about $9 billion over 10 years, with most of the
benefits going to businesses and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement seemed near on funding for the International
Monetary Fund. The White House is seeking $18 billion, which would
trigger other nations to give several times that amount to shore up
the IMF's reserves, now depleted by various rescue packages for
nations during the global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Senator Edward M. Kennedy has been a champion of
the new education programs. His office said the president and
Democratic lawmakers are seeking:
</P>
<P>
   -- $1 billion this year to hire more teachers, the first step in
a $12 billion, seven-year plan to put 100,000 more teachers in
classrooms. Democrats say this would cut average class size in
kindergarten through third grade to 18, down from between 25 and 26
today.
</P>
<P>
   -- $3.3 billion over five years to help local and state
governments issue $22 billion in bonds for school construction.
</P>
<P>
   -- $200 million next year and in following years to create and
run after-school programs. Current annual funding for the program
is $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   -- Additional money for literacy programs, which have been
promoted by Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
