<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ANSWERS OU'S DARE TO PASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Texas running back Ricky Williams can run.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows that. Oklahoma knows that. They had nine men
waiting for him on every down, and he still had 139 yards on 31
carries with two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   What many seemed to have forgotten is that the Longhorns can
pass, too.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Major Applewhite and receiver Wane McGarity combined
on the longest touchdown reception in Longhorns history _ a 97-yard
completion on a post route with 11:46 remaining in the third
quarter for a 24-3 lead. The touchdown eliminated the swooning
Sooners' hopes of coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach \Roffensive coordinator Greg\S Davis has always had the
mentality of not being passive on the goal line,'' Applewhite, a
redshirt freshman, said of the second-and-nine situation from the
Longhorns' 3. ``Their game plan was to stop Ricky, and I felt that
if they did that, we'd take it as a challenge to open it up. ...
Coach Davis said if they walk their safeties up, cut their
throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners had been walking their safeties up to the line all
day to little avail. Williams gained 113 of his yards on 18 carries
in the first half, to which Applewhite added nine completions in 14
attempts for 129 yards and an interception.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Applewhite was not necessarily ``The Bomb,''
but he threw one: On third-and-six at the Texas 44, the Longhorns
lined up with a fullhouse backfield with Kwame Cavil in the middle.
Cavil went in motion, came out of the backfield and curled over the
middle, where Applewhite placed a perfect pass.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-yard touchdown was, until McGarity's 97-yard reception,
the longest Longhorns touchdown catch since McGarity's 66-yarder
against Nebraska in the 1996 Big 12 Championship.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Longhorns hadn't exactly been known for
throwing deep. Before Cavil's reception, the longest Applewhite had
managed was a 42-yard pass against Kansas State and another against
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity had 153 yards receiving on six catches. Cavil had three
receptions for 93 yards. Applewhite amassed 293 yards on 14-of-27
passing, surrendering only the one first-half interception.
</P>
<P>
   Williams added three catches for 27 yards, a telling footnote to
his running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They literally played nine men in the box the whole game,''
Williams said. ``The receivers took advantage of that and had a
great game. I think we showed people we'll beat them with passing,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooners defensive coordinator Rex Ryan maintained the Sooners'
focus wasn't entirely on stopping the run, but OU's strategy belied
the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to spend so much attention in stopping him
\RWilliams\S that you're vulnerable in other areas,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Like, oh, maybe, the Longhorns' rejuvenated offensive threat _
the deep passing game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
