<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RECAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RITE OF NON-PASSAGE COMES TO END FOR 105TH CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 105th Congress began with the reprimand of
House Speaker Newt Gingrich and ended with launching an impeachment
inquiry into President Clinton. In between, lawmakers enacted the
smallest number of laws in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charged that the two-year session made Harry S.
Truman's original ``do nothing'' 80th Congress 50 years ago look
hyperactive in comparison. Clinton had signed 241 bills into law by
late last week, 39 percent of the average of 612 laws per session
of Congress over the last 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995, Newt Gingrich's Republicans shut down the government.
In 1998, Newt Gingrich and the Republicans shut down the
Congress,'' said House Democratic leader Richard Gephardt, who
declared the 105th as ``the worst Congress that has ever sat in
this building.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans point to passage of the landmark balanced-budget
agreement of 1997 that included substantial tax cuts, the largest
highway-funding bill in history, and a higher-education measure
that will lower the costs of college for students as key
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   But even GOP leaders acknowledge that making new laws was not
necessarily a priority for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy being so good, most Americans just checked
out of keeping a close eye on Washington,'' Ohio Representative
John Boehner, chairman of the Republican conference, said Friday.
``When the public is not engaged, things are going to flounder a
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   When Repubicans in 1995 took control of the House for the first
time in 40 years, Gingrich vowed to use congressional oversight to
ride herd on the Democratic White House. A recent Democratic report
found that 50 separate investigations of the Clinton administration
were under way in the House alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Congress has been one of investigation rather
than legislation,'' said Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of
South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   This has not damaged the public's view of Congress, however.
Public opinion polls have consistently shown the public giving high
marks to Congress and high favorability ratings to their individual
representatives and senators.
</P>
<P>
   Boehner blames Clinton for much of the legislative inactivity,
particularly this year when the accelerated pace of independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr's investigation distracted the White
House. ``The president has just been AWOL,'' he said. ``Lots of
issues require presidential leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislative priorities of both Republicans and Democrats
failed to become law. Republicans were unable to get an $80 billion
tax cut through the Senate, where GOP moderates balked at its size.
The Republican educational priorities, vouchers and educational
savings accounts, went down because of presidential vetoes. As the
session was ending, many measures pushed by social conservatives
that affected abortion rights and birth control had to be
jettisoned to get spending bills approved.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Democratic wish list landed in what Daschle called
``the GOP legislative landfill,'' including restrictions on
managed-care plans, campaign-finance reform, a minimum wage
increase, legsilation to regulate the tobacco industry, and money
for public school construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been one of the great unaccomplished sessions under the
Republican stewardship,'' said Senator John F. Kerry. ``It has been
marked by disorganization and avoidance.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Republicans became victims of their own success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The historic agreement last year on the balanced-budget plan
culminated three years of work,'' said Boehner, who said he
predicted in December that the pace would be slow this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told Gingrich ``all the big issues have been dealt
with and the next phase is not ready yet.'' The next phase would
include long-term solutions to Social Security and Medicare and a
fairer tax code, issues that require broad bipartisan and public
consensus that can take years to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, the key architect of the House GOP majority, survived
his reprimand but was weakened enough that some rebellious
Republicans mounted an unsuccessful coup in the summer of 1997 to
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the investigation into Clinton's relationship with
Monica S. Lewinsky so dominated Washington that the languid
lawmaking barely attracted public notice. House members typically
flew into town for votes after 5 p.m. on Tuesdays and left late on
Thursdays for most of the year. The Congress met for the least
number of work days in decades, about five weeks less than the
average over the last 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the balanced-budget deal, congressional Republicans
clearly made a conscious decision to ratchet down sharply,'' said
Norman Ornstein, a fellow at the American Enterprise Institute.
``Public sentiment that had been fairly clear for a while was, the
country is on a roll, we are very happy, so don't screw it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have been frustrated by the way the Lewinsky story
dominated news coverage. They hope to make their unfinished agenda
a campaign issue in the final weeks up to the Nov. 3 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Senator Edward M. Kennedy pushed this year for a
``Patient Bill of Rights'' that would have imposed new rules on
managed-care plans and allowed patients to sue their health care
providers. In a last-minute ploy on Friday, Senate Democrats
brought to the floor the Republican version of that bill, which had
been approved earlier by the House, to test if the GOP wanted a
managed-care bill to pass, but the measure as defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue now goes to the voters,'' Kennedy said after the
vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
