<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FORDHAM-PENN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN IS VICTORIOUS OVER FORDHAM
</HEADLINE>
   (js) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Through the season's first four games, Fordham had
compensated for its suspect defense and rushing game with an
aggressive passing attack. On Saturday, Steve O'Hare and his
receivers provided a spectacular comeback, but no victory.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, displaying two potent weapons in quarterback Matt Rader
and running back Jim Finn, built a 20-point lead in the third
quarter and hung on to defeat the Rams, 34-31, at Jack Coffey
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you invested what our players invested, it's difficult
for people to comprehend what it might feel like after a defeat
like this,'' Fordham coach Ken O'Keefe said.
</P>
<P>
   The Quakers (3-1) avoided becoming Fordham's third upset victim
by exploiting the Rams' weaknesses. The Fordham defense had allowed
350 yards a game. The Quakers gained 480. Fordham (2-3) had
averaged a paltry 88.8 yards a game rushing. Penn stuffed the Rams
into a measly 73.
</P>
<P>
   The Quakers, despite a shaky fourth quarter, are emerging as an
Ivy League favorite. Their only defeat came against Richmond, a
school with a scholarship program. Their victory prospects will
rely heavily on the health of Rader and Finn. Rader left the game
early in the third quarter with a gash on his right shoulder _
apparently caused by a defender's face mask _ and the quarterback
platoon of Reed Warner and Edward Mebs did not produce a point
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   That let Fordham concentrate on stopping Finn. The Rams were
successful for a while, but in the game's waning moments they were
not. Finn, a 6-foot-1-inch, 240-pounder, helped the Quakers run the
clock out on the final drive by converting on a third-and-6 and a
fourth-and-1 as Fordham used up its timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Finn carried 29 times for 198 yards and 2 touchdowns, including
a 69-yard sprint in the first half. Rader, who need stitches for
the cut on his shoulder, completed 19 of 25 pass attempts for 256
yards and 3 touchdowns, including a 39-yard fluttering heave to
David O'Neill with four seconds left in the first half. The
touchdown made the score 27-14 just after the Rams had sprung to
life on O'Hare's 2-yard touchdown loft to Gerry McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, breaking tackles and outjumping the Quakers' shorter
defensive backs, caught nine passes for 125 yards and 3 touchdowns.
He played the fourth quarter with a sprained shoulder. When he
plucked his third scoring reception to make the score 34-20 in the
third quarter, one Penn assistant coach screamed, ``I can't believe
this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare was even more unbelievable. Hobbled by a sprained right
ankle and harassed by Penn's rush, the senior quarterback still had
a career day. He connected on 23 of 37 passes for 323 yards and 4
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' O'Hare said. `'My dad came up to me and
said I played a good game. It wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It almost was. O'Hare's 24-yard touchdown pass to Chris Auferio
brought the Rams within 34-28 with 11 minutes 43 seconds left.
Meanwhile, the Rader-less Quakers could not advance the ball.
</P>
<P>
   On the Rams' final scoring march, O'Hare's third-down pass in
the end zone trickled off McDermott's fingertips, and the Rams
settled for Brian Colsant's 25-yard field goal, making the score
34-31 with 6:52 to go. The Rams went nowhere on their next drive,
and Finn ran 7 straight times to chew up the final 3:48.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
