<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Oct. 11. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DERAIL _ Investigators in the 3-year-old derailment of the Amtrak
Sunset Limited in Arizona upturned stolen cars and rumors of bodies
and dynamite in car trunks Saturday at a remote mine shaft. By
DENNIS WAGNER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RACES _ Republican Gov. Jane Hull has a 25-point lead over Democrat
Paul Johnson in a new Arizona Republic poll. But the point spread
in other statewide races is not as large, and their outcomes rest
with a sizable number of undecided voters, the survey found. With
less than a month to go before the Nov. 3 election, Hull leads
Johnson, 52 percent to 27 percent, in the governor's race,
according to the statewide poll of 811 registered voters. By
MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PROPS (Undated) _ Don't bet on the Arizona Lottery disappearing
anytime soon. A new Arizona Republic poll shows a solid majority of
voters _ 60 percent _ aren't ready to bury Windfall Willie, the
Lottery's plucky prospector, or any other state-sponsored game of
chance. The survey also shows 55 percent of Arizona voters believe
Lottery dollars are a financial boon to the state. Voters will
decide Nov. 3 to extend of the life of the Arizona Lottery to July
1, 2003. By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PROTEST (undated) _ Manuel Gray entered Sky Harbor International's
Terminal 4 in suit and tie, a crisply pressed white shirt, carrying
a designer garment bag and matching carry-on. A social worker who
stands six-feet-four, has impeccable posture and a shaved head, he
passed smoothly through the aiport's X-ray checkpoint. But when he
and a friend - also an African American - arrived at their
Southwest Airlines boarding gate, a female employee pulled them out
of line and told them she needed to search their luggage. Right
there. On the counter top. In front of all the other passengers in
the terminal. By VICTORIA HARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FEUD (undated) _ Rick doesn't like the way Joe runs his jails. Joe
says Rick is just jealous because people like him better.Joe is mad
because he thinks Rick snitched on him to Uncle Sam. Rick is upset
because Joe accused him of being a lousy lawyer. And so it goes in
the political mudwrestling match between the Valley's two top law
officers, Sheriff Joe Arpaio and County Attorney Richard Romley.
For five years they've been at each other's throats, publicly and
privately sabotaging one another with venomous determination. But
the feud boiled over last week following recent clashes over the
arrest of a hairdresser, a postal worker spraying a dog with mace,
and a plan to bust people who steal off-road vehicles. By DENNIS
WAGNER and WILLIAM HERMANN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHOPPERS (Undated) _ News helicopters are standard scenery in
Phoenix skies, battling for airspace over tragedies, their
high-tech eyes offering close-ups of carnage to television viewers.
Although the choppers have flown in the Valley for decades, they've
never done so in such numbers or with such fervor. By RICHARD
RUELAS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EAGLE _ He was known simply as JD _ and he was the king of bald
eagles in Arizona. At 19, he was the longest-lived male bird of his
kind in the state. He fathered more eaglets than any other Arizona
eagle. And he amazed scientists with his calm regard as they banded
his brood for research. Now, wildlife officials are mourning his
death. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI (column) _ Earlier this year, a gravely ill father from
Casa Grande was able to take his children to Disneyland, for free,
because of Jim Adameak. Not long afterward, an ailing woman from
Phoenix took the trip to San Francisco she'd always dreamed about,
for free, because of Jim Adameak. A Mesa family, the mother very
sick, traveled to a family gathering in Michigan, for free, because
of Jim Adameak. A Tucson grandmother got to see her grandson; a
Phoenix woman visited relatives in Washington, D.C.; a Scottsdale
mother watched her son play baseball in California. All for free.
All because of Jim Adameak, a 39-year-old working guy whose actual
vocation, it turned out, was working miracles. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL;
