<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCEAST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFC EAST: FROM BEAST TO LEAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cowboys, the only winning team in the once legendary NFC
East, are being heralded for having ``taken charge'' of the
division.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Cowboys are in charge of nothing. At 3-2, they are
a game up on the field with 11 to play, and the NFC East represents
the NFL's version of nothingness.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL's six divisions each are fraternities, then the NFC
East is ``Animal House.''
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to a division that produced five of six Super
Bowl champions from 1990 to 1995; that once featured powerful
coaches such as Joe Gibbs, Jimmy Johnson, Bill Parcells and Buddy
Ryan matching wits; that once had participants boasting was so
intense, so physical, so bitter, that it steeled its members
against playoff pressure?
</P>
<P>
   It's been nine years since the New York Giants advanced beyond
the wild-card round of the postseason, and seven years since the
Washington Redskins made the playoffs. The Philadelphia Eagles have
won two playoff games since 1981. The Arizona Cardinals have won no
playoff games in this half-century.
</P>
<P>
   Says Eagles receiver Irving Fryar: ``In this division this year,
8-8 gets you into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? What happened?
</P>
<P>
   There are the usual suspects: Bad drafts, bad financial
decisions, bad breaks. But look deeper: The Cowboys' four foes in
the NFC East _ with its dearth of Pro Bowl types at quarterback,
its four losing teams, and its two coaches in job jeopardy _ can
each pinpoint one event that caused their present travails.
</P>
<P>
   Where to place specific blame with each of the four losers, in
order of their NFC East standing:
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants
</P>
<P>
   Maybe getting off to a slow start will become a trademark of Jim
Fassel's Giants. The rookie coach started 1-3 last year before the
Giants' domination of East foes (New York was 7-0-1 in the
division) drove New York to a 10-5-1 record and a title.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a difference this season. While the '97 Giants faced
only two playoff teams after a 1-3 start (wild-cards Detroit and
Tampa Bay), these 2-3 Giants are looking down the barrel of a
schedule that includes meetings with 3-1 Atlanta, 3-2 Dallas, 4-1
Green Bay, 3-1 San Francisco, 5-0 Denver and 4-1 Kansas City _ five
first-place teams, and all six playoff contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants raised expectations last season, causing observers to
forget that maybe a fifth-place schedule produced a first-place
team. And this year? A first-place schedule has been foisted on a
Giants club that, if not for the East's ineptitude, might be a
fifth-place team.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   You want instability?
</P>
<P>
   They've changed their geographic name four times in 40 years
(from Chicago to St. Louis to Phoenix to Arizona).
</P>
<P>
   Including the 1996 hiring of Vince Tobin, they changed coaches
eight times in 18 years. Including the current No. 1, promising
Jake Plummer, the Arizona media guide recalls 11 ``usual starting
quarterbacks'' in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The one constant? Look for a bow tie (or now, a bolo tie in an
apparent kissup to the Southwest). Look for a padlocked wallet.
Look for that dark cloud that follows the Bidwill family since
1948.
</P>
<P>
   Look for William V. Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   It's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the way it is because of the oppressively bad judgment
of owner Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   True story: Last year, on a long cross-country plane ride home
from New York, Cardinals players were looking forward to an
in-flight movie. The testosterone-driven young athletes voted for
any movie with a little action, a little adventure, a little sex
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Bidwill let his wife, Nancy, choose the film.
</P>
<P>
   So the Arizona Cardinals spent the flight home watching Bette
Midler's ``Beaches''. Philadelphia Eagles
</P>
<P>
   It's a nightmare,'' coach Ray Rhodes says. ``It's a nightmare
for everybody, from the coaches to the trainers. A nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting that Rhodes would make mention of the vast number of
people affected by the franchise's failure, because there are a
vast number of people whose arm wrestling over decision-making
authority is at the root of the Eagles' illness.
</P>
<P>
   At different times in Rhodes' five seasons, he's been in charge
of personnel decisions. At other times, owner Jeff Lurie _ whose
background is as a movie producer but who says he models himself
after legendary basketball boss Red Auerbach _ has seemed in
charge. This year long-time Steelers personnel man Tom Modrak was
hired to give the front office direction.
</P>
<P>
   But it might take time to recover from the influence of Lurie
pal Joe Banner, who has grown into the job of capologist, but is
limited beyond that by a resume that is highlighted by his
experience as a radio show producer, a clothing manufacturer, and
reportedly, a Fantasy Football nut.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a few years there, before Modrak came over, they had three
or four people pulling in three or four different directions,''
says one NFL executive.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes produced a 20-12 mark in his first two seasons and made
the playoffs twice. But he is 6-15-1 in his past 22 games, has lost
eight consecutive games, is 0-5 this season and could match the
franchise record for futility established by the 2-11-1 Eagles of
1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad,'' Rhodes says. ``How can it be any worse than it is
right now?''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it can and will get worse. The Eagles will fire their coach.
And then Lurie and Banner will hire the next man scheduled to
engage them in a divisive power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Redskins
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn from all your experiences,'' Redskins coach Norv
Turner says, managing a weak smile. ``But we've had enough (bad)
experiences. I've learned enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Turner learned everything he needed to know about
Washington's demise shortly after his first draft, in 1994, when he
spent the third overall pick on Tennessee quarterback Heath Shuler.
</P>
<P>
   That choice came shortly after late Redskins owner Jack Kent
Cooke predicted Turner woud someday be inducted into the Pro
Football Hall of Fame. Might have come true, too _ had he not
chosen Shuler.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's contract runs through 2001. But he's 0-5 this year with
a career mark of 26-42-1 and, like Rhodes, is in danger of losing
his job. And unlike Rhodes _ who didn't always have control _
Turner's problem is the decision he made when given control.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts say Turner overrated Shuler's intellect, but whatever the
reason, Turner is haunted by not going with other options. What if
he'd waited a year to draft his quarterback and positioned himself
for a first-rounder like Kerry Collins of the Panthers or Steve
McNair of the Oilers? Or a second-rounder like Kordell Stewart of
the Steelers? (And how much more developed might those sometimes
struggling youngsters be under the guidance of QB guru Turner?)
</P>
<P>
   What if the Redskins had taken the other ``blue-chip''
quarterback in the 1994 draft, Trent Dilfer, who went to Tampa Bay
two picks later?
</P>
<P>
   Says Turner, defending his coaching style and philosophy: ``What
we do works.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in this case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-98 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
