<DOCNO> NYT19981010.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0215 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ADAMS-TEX     10-10 1803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ADAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAMS EMERGES AS A MONEY PLAYER FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ As he normally does with prize rookies, Cowboys
owner Jerry Jones gave second-round pick Flozell Adams a big
signing bonus and some advice last summer about how to safeguard
his money.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to help future millionaires like Adams keep their
hard-earned cash out of the hands of unsavory characters. For some,
who went through college with barely enough spare change to
occasionally buy some new clothes or go out on Friday nights, talk
about mutual funds and certificates of deposits can be
mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case with the 23-year-old Adams. The 6-foot-7,
335-pounder took Jones' $890,000 check and laid out his financial
potential. Oil futures. Money markets. Stock options. Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed, almost taken aback by his knowledge, his
thought process and how sophisticated he was about financial
matters,'' Jones said. ``He whipped out rates, dissected value of
dollars and safety considerations that you'd expect to hear from a
financial advisor. It was a very good indication that he has his
stuff together. It's unusual ... rare for someone that young.''
</P>
<P>
   Unusual. Uncommon. Rare. Adams is all of these. And grand. And
powerful. And ferocious. And he is making his first start today as
the Cowboys' right guard against the Carolina Panthers at Texas
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He is here because of the strength of a mother who for five
years never let on how sick she was, fearing that the oldest of her
two children would give up on football if he knew she was dying of
liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He is here because of a doting aunt who would not let him think
about quitting at his lowest emotional moment.
</P>
<P>
   He is here because of high school coaches who had the courage to
stand in the face of a 6-foot-5, 300-pound 16-year-old and tell him
that he'd go nowhere if he didn't strive for greatness.
</P>
<P>
   He is here because of college coaches who nurtured his talent
and because the Cowboys had the sense to take him with the 38th
pick in last April's draft after other teams passed on him because
they doubted his desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy developed into a tremendous football player, and made
a commitment to be the best he could be,'' said Nick Saban, Adams'
coach at Michigan State. ``We didn't stand over him with a whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That all came from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Before all-state and All-American honors, before the money and
before the fame, Adams was just big.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in the middle-class Chicago suburb of Maywood, he grew so
fast it seemed every month he was needing new shoes, some trousers,
a new shirt. He was nearly 6-feet tall in middle school, 6-1 as a
freshman, 6-5 as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   He was too big to wear the clothes of his 6-foot father, Flozell
Sr., who earned his keep working for a steel company.
</P>
<P>
   So his mother, Rachel, a hematology supervisor and later a
sheriff's department inspector, would borrow clothes from relatives
to put on Flozell's back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd spurt every two or three weeks,'' said Alice Daniels,
Flozell's aunt. ``My sister would ask if he could wear my husband's
shoes. He outgrew those. Then she came back and asked if he could
wear his coat. A month later, she needed some shirts. He was just
too big for everything. We would shop at the big and tall stores.
But since he had size 15 shoes, we had to get those from shopping
out of a catalog.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he was somewhat embarrassed by his size at first, but
soon got over it. He went out for the wrestling team as a sophomore
and made it to the Illinois state heavyweight finals as a junior.
He only wrestled a few times as a senior because he had trouble
getting down to the state's 275-pound weight limit.
</P>
<P>
   He also threw the shot put. But he didn't go out for the
football team until his junior year when Proviso West coach John
Wilson saw him walking the halls at school. Wilson took one look at
Adams and gave him a position on the offensive and defensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Adams' play frustrated coaches. Wilson recalled
defensive coordinator Tim McAlpin exclaiming, ``I don't care how
big he is but he can't play for me,'' before kicking Adams off the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not give up on Adams as an offensive lineman, but
pulled him into his office on numerous occasions and admonished
Adams not to blow his chance for a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to get greatness out of him and he was just a
kid,'' Wilson said. ``He didn't work very hard, and he didn't
realize what sports was all about. He couldn't figure out why
everyone was yelling at him to run faster, to go harder. Because of
his personality, really quiet, he was totally bewildered, baffled
at what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would ask him, `Do you know what the future holds for you?'
We were trying to explain to him how good he could be. He had the
size, everything. The rest had to come from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said high school was a time when ``I didn't know what I
wanted to be or what I wanted to do with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had plenty of things to keep him occupied. He was in the
German club and the Spanish club. He helped make floats for the
homecoming parades. He loved computers (he owns a personal laptop
to keep track of stocks, bonds and oil futures).
</P>
<P>
   He also played trumpet in the band. To play for the band and the
football team called for some quick action on game days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before halftime, he'd run off the field, take off his football
stuff, put on his band uniform and perform at the half,'' Daniels
said. ``Then, at the end of the performance, he'd sprint back, take
his band stuff off, put his uniform on, then go out and play
(football).
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so happy doing that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he became excited about playing football. He was a high
school All-American as a senior. As Wilson promised, scholarship
offers poured in, and Adams considered Illinois before deciding to
attend Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   But he struggled early in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came here, Flo was 370, maybe more,'' said Saban, who
replaced George Perles as Michigan State's head coach prior to
Adams' sophomore year in 1995. ``He wasn't in very good condition.
He could never sustain anything for more than 10 yards. We saw some
ability. He had good feet. But he was just a young player that had
never played.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then,'' Saban added, ``something in him changed. He lost
50 pounds. His body became more defined. He became a really good
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the change came when he was told he'd have a chance
to start. He converted that chance into a second-team All-Big Ten
selection as a sophomore and a junior at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Flozell never knew how sick his mother was. Rachel Adams had
surgery in the fall of 1995 and only told her sister, Alice. She
made Alice swear not to tell another soul about the liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   When she missed one of her son's football games the following
fall, Flozell was not aware of how badly his mother felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just told him that she wasn't feeling well,'' Alice said.
``Then she got up and kept going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I knew she had cancer,'' Flozell said, ``and I was
devastated. She knew it. Then she told me they got rid of it, the
cancer. She was telling me so I wouldn't have to worry about her,
so I wouldn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Flozell knew everything. When her condition worsened, in
January 1997, the family put her in a hospital and called Flozell
home. That was a Saturday. She died on Wednesday. She was 49.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Flozell remained devasted by his mother's
death. He went to his aunt's house and briefly flirted with the
idea of giving up football. Both cried. There were tears and hugs.
Having lost her father, Alice could understand the desperation felt
by young Flozell.
</P>
<P>
   But she was not going to let him stop pursuing his dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Oh, you are going to the NFL _ you may as well get
that craziness out of your mind,''' she said. ``I told him that God
gives you people and God takes them away. I said, `You are a young
man with so much going for you _ do you know how many people would
give their right arm to be in your position?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom would not have wanted me to quit and she wouldn't want
me to sit around and sulk,'' Flozell said. ``I could hear her now,
had I quit, telling me not to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he was disappointed about not being selected until
the second round of last April's NFL draft. Scouts wondered how
much Adams, who made things look so easy, wanted to play
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kept calling and asking me how important football was
to Flozell,'' Saban said. ``They were all concerned about his
psychological profile. He's kind of laid back. I think people read
too much into that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It also did not help that Adams played much of his senior season
with an ankle sprain that limited his mobility, and that he had
gone through college with a partial hearing loss in his right ear.
</P>
<P>
   The fear was that Adams would have trouble hearing the snap
count in noisy stadiums. But Adams, who played at Notre Dame and at
Michigan, laughs at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was blown out of proportion because I had a hearing test
which showed I had just a slight hearing loss, 10 percent,'' Adams
said. ``As a freshman, I jumped offsides a lot at left tackle. They
figured I couldn't hear the signals. I jumped offsides a lot
because I was a freshman and didn't know what I was doing. They got
me a hearing aid. But I never wore one and still don't because I
don't need one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys drafted North Carolina's Greg Ellis in the first
round because they needed help on the defensive line. Then they
went after Adams, whom they were all too delighted to see drop into
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Garrett, a team scout, filed this report about Adams:
``Aggressive, and at times nasty.'' The film the Cowboys saw that
best showed Adams' college dominance was the 1997 Michigan
State-Michigan game. Adams completely manhandled All-American Glen
Steele. Another clip from the game showed Adams knocking a defender
to the ground and jumping on top of him. The play drew an
unsportsmanlike conduct penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Senior Bowl, during pass rushing drills, he looked
bored the way he was throwing guys,'' Cowboys scouting director
Larry Lacewell said. ``He made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flozell has the three things you need as offensive tackle.
You've got to have great feet. If you don't, then you are dead in
the water because you are playing more finesse than you'd think
with all the speed rushers you go against. Then you need long arms
to lock guys out. Then you need to be intelligent. He is all those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   And more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
