u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-     10-10 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES MORE MONEY FOR EDUCATIONAL PROGRAMS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs throughout to add details from Saturday's discussions on
Capitol Hill.)  
 (Attn: Ala., Fla., Miss., Mo., Nev., N.Y.)   (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a campaign-style effort to regain their
political footing after last week's impeachment vote, President
Clinton and Congressional Democrats challenged Republicans Saturday
to enact broad education initiatives in the new budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to see this Congress walk away from America's
schoolchildren,'' the president said in his weekly radio address,
delivered as Republicans and White House officials remained far
apart on numerous spending matters that must be resolved before
members of Congress can leave town and fully engage in their
re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   One major issue that did appear headed toward a compromise was
financing for the International Monetary Fund. Republicans said
they were willing to provide the $18 billion requested by the
president to shore up the fund's reserves, but only if the
administration agreed to impose certain conditions on the fund.
Both sides said Saturday night that they were close to an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But occupying the front burner was education. Republicans
indicated Saturday evening that they would cede to the president's
request for $1.1 billion next year to hire 100,000 teachers, on
condition that the administration identify cuts of an equal amount
elsewhere in the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Erskine Bowles, the president's chief of staff and top
negotiator on Capitol Hill, emerged from a meeting Saturday night
with Speaker Newt Gingrich, saying: ``I think we have made some
progress. I think they clearly have heard what we were saying on
education and I'm optimistic in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich agreed. ``I don't currently see anything which is
impossible to bridge,'' he said, adding that he hoped negotiations
could be concluded by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Such pushing and pulling marked the nation's 10th day without a
federal budget beyond the Oct. 1 start of the new fiscal year. The
president signed a second stopgap spending bill on Friday night to
keep the government running through midnight Monday. Congress has
cleared only six of the 13 spending bills needed to keep the
government open and is negotiating with the White House over what
to include in one big omnibus package to present to the president.
</P>
<P>
   There was little chance of action before Monday, because the
Senate and the House have postponed all recorded votes until Monday
afternoon and many members have left town for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats have insisted they do not want to
shut down the government and, with the Nov. 3 elections looming,
are eager to set their broad campaign themes.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans wanted to leave town with the focus on the enduring
image of a wounded president subjected to an impeachment inquiry
over a sex scandal. Democrats demonstrated Saturday that they
wanted additional time to change the subject to education, an issue
that voters have said is of prime importance.
</P>
<P>
   The president's two major education proposals call for hiring
100,000 teachers for hard-to-recruit schools in inner cities and
rural areas, to reduce the size of the average class to 18
students, and for upgrading old schools and making them
Internet-compatible by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have criticized the programs as pork-barrel spending
that offers a big-Government solution to problems that should be
solved locally.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, said that
the Democrats' emphasis on education was ``pure politics, pure
demagoguery.'' He said that the White House had not identified
where to find the $4 billion for its education package because that
would cut into other programs sought by liberals.
</P>
<P>
   He also cast doubt on Clinton's engagement in the process,
noting that the president would be out of town on Monday and
Tuesday, when negotiators might be stitching together their final
budget package. Clinton plans to be in New York on Monday to raise
money for Rep. Charles Schumer, the Democratic Senate candidate,
and Peter Vallone, speaker of the New York City Council, who is
running for governor. On Tuesday, Clinton plans to visit Florida
for fund-raising and to join senior citizens and declare that he is
protecting the budget surplus to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans demonstrated that they were just as ``on message''
as the Democrats, returning throughout the day Saturday to the
president's woes. ``Clinton has held just two Cabinet meetings this
year,'' Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla., said on the House floor.
``The first one to lie to his Cabinet, and the second one to
apologize to his Cabinet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader, spoke
at a news conference packed with Democrats left idle as the
chairmen of various spending committees met with administration
officials to work out dozens of matters, ranging from emergency aid
for farmers to polarizing questions of contraception _ for minors,
for federal employees and for overseas family planning
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having spent four weeks talking about impeachment, surely we
can spend four hours on the president's education initiatives,''
Gephardt said in criticizing House Republicans for spending ``not
one minute, not one second'' debating the president's education
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest items on the table _ how much to give to the
IMF _ appeared close to resolution. Republicans said they would
provide the full $18 billion under conditions that curbed what they
called the fund's profligate lending practices. They want the fund
to stop lending money at below-market rates and to operate more
openly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long way,'' said Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., the
chairman of the foreign operations subcommittee of the
Appropriations Committee. ``We're in a position to reach some type
of agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration also sounded optimistic. ``I think it's too
early to tell, but I think there are more hopeful signs than there
have been in quite some time,'' said Gene Sperling, Clinton's
national economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus is major flash point with Congress. Republicans
argue that Clinton is raiding the surplus to pay for his education
and child-care programs. He had expected to pay for them with money
from a settlement with the tobacco companies, which never
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   They also say he wants to take billions from the surplus to pay
for ``emergencies'' that are not true emergencies, like the
peacekeeping mission in Bosnia and fixing the year 2000 computer
bug, both of which were foreseen and could recur. Republicans agree
that some of the emergency money the president seeks _ to improve
security at U.S. embassies and to help Americans who were hit by
natural disasters _ are legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   After the House voted on Thursday to open an impeachment inquiry
into Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, Clinton was eager
to show that he was tending to the people's business. At a news
conference with Democrats in Congress, he presented himself as the
guardian of education and a safety net against Republican
extremists.
</P>
<P>
   His education agenda includes money to make sure all children
can read by second or third grade and to help colleges provide
mentors to students to guide them toward college.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is also concerned about some education issues
that have little to do with money. These include a Republican ban
on the president's proposal for national testing of fourth-grade
students in reading and eighth-grade students in math and a
Republican plan to dissolve bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   In other business, the House passed without dissent a bill that
would require the government to deal with countries that persecute
citizens for religious beliefs by using measures ranging from the
mildest private rebuke to tough economic sanctions. The bill passed
the Senate unanimously on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
