<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS STAMPEDE PAST SOONERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GENE MENEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For those who may have doubts, yesterday's game at the
Cotton Bowl was Texas vs. Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   That was Texas that stonewalled the Sooners to just three
points. That was Texas that featured an air-it-out attack that
rolled up 293 yards and did not depend on Heisman Trophy candidate
Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   As if the 11:30 a.m. kickoff and Williams wearing No. 37 weren't
strange enough.
</P>
<P>
   The game might not have ranked near the best in the
Texas-Oklahoma rivalry, but it ranked at the very top of the
Longhorns' performances this season. With the staunch defensive
effort and the newly found deep-passing attack, Texas took another
step on its quest for improvement with a 34-3 victory against the
Sooners before 75,587 at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been improving each week and coming together more and
more, and we really played as one heartbeat today,'' Texas
linebacker Dusty Renfro said. ``The biggest statement \Rfrom the
game\S is the 'Horns are back in town.''
</P>
<P>
   The proclaimed return for Texas (4-2 overall, 2-1 Big 12) came
against a bumbling Oklahoma (2-3, 0-2) team that committed 14
penalties for 109 yards, turned the ball over four times, fumbled
six times, including two on one play, and had a punt partially
blocked. The outcome _ Texas' biggest victory in the series since a
41-9 rout in 1970 _ was as much about Oklahoma's ineptitude as it
was Texas' aptitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to come down here and lose like this,'' said
Sooners senior defensive tackle Kelly Gregg, whose team allowed 34
unanswered points. ``This is terrible. It was just a terrible
game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a banner game for the Longhorns' passing attack. With
Oklahoma sending up to nine men near the line of scrimmage to stop
Williams, Texas burned the Sooners' defense with touchdown passes
of 97 yards _ the longest in Texas history _ and 56 yards.
</P>
<P>
   On the 56-yarder, Texas quarterback Major Applewhite dumped a
pass to Kwame Cavil, who came out of the backfield, and Cavil raced
untouched through the Oklahoma secondary to give the Longhorns a
14-3 lead. On the 97-yarder, Texas receiver Wane McGarity ran past
Sooners defensive backs Corey Ivy and Mike Woods and caught a
perfectly thrown ball from Applewhite, who finished 14-of-27.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity also scored untouched, giving Texas a comfortable 24-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two-deep coverage,'' Oklahoma defensive coordinator Rex
Ryan said, ``but I guess it was not deep enough.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity's touchdown came two plays after Sooners quarterback
Brandon Daniels fumbled the snap while trying a quarterback sneak
from the Texas 1-yard line. Longhorns defensive tackle Casey
Hampton recovered the fumble, and instead of Oklahoma possibly
making the score 17-10 early in the third quarter, the Sooners
found themselves trailing by three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a chance there in the second half,'' Sooners coach John
Blake said, ``but that fumble on the goal line really hurt us and
took a lot out of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas defense, which entered the game allowing 444.4 yards
of total offense per game, allowed only 197. Oklahoma running back
De'Mond Parker rushed for 93 yards on 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've ever seen our defense play since I've
been here,'' said Renfro, a senior from Alvarado. ``It was really
great.
</P>
<P>
   Donning the No. 37 in tribute to SMU great and Heisman Trophy
winner Doak Walker, who died on Sept. 27, Williams gained 139 yards
and two touchdowns on 31 carries. On both touchdowns, he pointed to
the sky, and 5tGv .2C &QR; 2
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
