</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NEGOTIATIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS U.S. PRESSES TALKS ON KOSOVO, HOPE OF AVERTING AIR STRIKES
RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs grafs 2-6 to update status of talks; adds last graf on
Yugoslav Army preparations for possible airstrikes; polishing and
tightening throughout.)   (See also KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC)  
(ak) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ The continuation of negotiations Saturday
by the U.S. envoy, Richard Holbrooke, with both the ethnic Albanian
leadership in Kosovo and the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, suggested that enough common ground was being found to
avert NATO air strikes, Western diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke spent about an hour and a half with Ibrahim Rugova,
the ethnic Albanian political leader, in Pristina, the capital of
Kosovo, and returned for seven hours of talks with Milosevic, which
ended after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the official news agency Tanjug said that ``all the
conditions are there'' for a political solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But immediately after the end of the session, Holbrooke returned
to the U.S. Embassy here to consult by telephone with Washington.
He had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official travelling with Holbrooke dismissed the
statement calling it ``old wine in an old bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer talks go on and the more exchanges that take place
between the two sides in the Kosovo conflict, the greater the
chances for a peaceful resolution, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Milosevic backs down, however, many Serbs in this
frightened capital say the mere threat of air strikes has enabled
the Yugoslav leader to strengthen rather than weaken control of his
economically depressed country.
</P>
<P>
   There was still a high likelihood, the diplomats said, that NATO
would formally declare an activation order, the last step necessary
to authorize air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general of NATO, Javier Solana, said Saturday in
Brussels that the alliance had completed all the necessary
decisions before declaring the order.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have consistently said they believe that it would
take the final authorization of air strikes to push Milosevic to
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs Saturday in Belgrade that Milosevic had decided
that taking NATO air strikes was not the most profitable route to
his political survival.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph, an independent newspaper that in a crisis
like this is considered to reflect a sense of what the secretive
Milosevic is mulling, reported Saturday that the Yugoslav leader
``objects to some parts of the proposed agreement'' but that a deal
was in the making.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Milosevic was against NATO soldiers being
part of a peacekeeping force in Kosovo. Senior Clinton
administration officials have said in the last several days that an
``international presence'' would be necessary in Kosovo to verify
the withdrawal of Milosevic's troops.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have also suggested that the ``presence'' would be
used to help the international aid effort that will be needed over
the winter to assist about 250,000 ethnic Albanian refugees who
were forced to flee their homes during a three-month offensive by
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have not been specific about the composition of
the ``presence'' that is being contemplated. Holbrooke has noted
the opposition in Congress to sending American soldiers to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph also reported that Milosevic had asked for
all economic sanctions to be lifted against Yugoslavia, including
the ban on loans from the International Monetary Fund and financing
from the World Bank. The newspaper said that Holbrooke had offered
a gradual lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Holbrooke was characteristically tight-lipped about his
discussions Saturday in Pristina. The situation was ``just as
serious'' as some days ago, he said, before taking the 40-minute
flight back to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   He met with a three-man negotiating team for the ethnic
Albanians in Pristina but spent the bulk of his time with Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova has led the ethnic Albanian policy calling for the
independence of Kosovo rather than some kind of enhanced autonomy
within a Yugoslav framework. His peaceful pursuit of independence
has earned him Western backing over the violent guerrilla tactics
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, an ethnic Albanian group trying to
win independence on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Holbrooke was the U.S. ambassador to Macedonia,
Christopher Hill, the main author of an interim political plan for
the status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's plan would restore to Kosovo some degree of autonomy,
stripped away by Milosevic in 1989, but postpone for several years
the question of independence. It also lays out details of much
greater representation of ethnic Albanians _ who outnumber Serbs
nine to one _ in the province, in the police force, the courts, a
legislature and other bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Holbrooke is armed with six points of negotiation
that he brought with him from a meeting with the so-called contact
group in London Friday. The group consists of Russia, the United
States and European countries that monitor events in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The points include the withdrawal of the Yugoslav national army
and the Serbian police in Kosovo to the levels that pertained
before March, when the crackdown against the guerrillas began, and
the storage of heavy weapons, the freedom for the 250,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees to return to their homes without intimidation
from Serbian police, and the start of talks based on the Hill plan.
</P>
<P>
   But at the heart of the talks, according to U.S. officials, have
been the Serbian and Yugoslav military issues _ an immediate end to
hostilities and the withdrawal of troops and weaponry. Unless these
forces are reduced and the reductions can be verified, those ethnic
Albanians whose homes have not been destroyed in the summer
offensive will lack the confidence to return to their villages, the
American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas, which after a series of car bombs and similar
attacks in the past two years have fought openly since the spring
for Kosovo's independence, said Saturday that they would continue
to respect a cease-fire they announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, a well-informed daily news report, VIP, which is
read closely in Western embassies, said in its latest issue that
preparations by the Yugoslav Army against possible NATO air strikes
had not gone well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
