<SLUG> BC-RAC-LEMANSNOTE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Petit Le Mans notebook
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even before he knew Road Atlanta would have a
monumental mob attending Saturday's inaugural Petit Le Mans, Don
Panoz was already at work expanding the concept.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the American Le Mans Series announced an agreement in
principle with the Automobile Club de l'Ouest to expand the series
over three continents.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will establish a Le Mans Series in Europe and Asia
as well as the American Series, which debuts next year.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, the presence of the world's top drivers, beautiful
weather and the sounds of racing created an electricity not seen in
more than a decade at Road Atlanta and got Panoz driver Doc Bundy
so excited he exclaimed: ``There's the Daytona 500 for stock cars
and the Indy 500. America has needed a sports car race like that
and this might be it. Don Panoz brought a piece of the biggest
sports car race in the world, Le Mans, to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's right, only it will be bigger with the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement, when finalized, will support Don Panoz' global
visition for sports car racing in the future,'' said Michel Cosson,
president of ACO. ``It's important that the Le Mans name will be at
the forefront of this aggressive reorganization of sports car
racing worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, one or two endurance events (minimum of
1,000 kilometers) will be held on each continent as part of an
Endurance Cup Challenge with $2 million (U.S.) in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The series could have enormous implications for sports car
racing, especially in the U.S. where it has been a fragmented
affair, dwindling in competition and fans until Panoz stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers are already looking at Panoz as a Moses of sorts,
leading sports car racing out of the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panoz is a man with a vision,'' said Wayne Taylor driver of
the Atlanta-sponsored Lease Plan Ferrari 333SP. ``Sports car racing
has been up and down over the years. Hopefully, this (Petit Le
Mans) will turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Yannick Dalmas, driver of the 24 Hours of Le Mans-winning No. 26
Porsche that crashed on Saturday said, ``This weekend is the start
of something different in the way sports car racing has been done.
It has taken a lot of committment, initially by Panoz, to get this
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Petite Le Mans was the star of the weekend at Road Atlanta,
but there was some excitement in the supporting races, too.
</P>
<P>
   Like the good old days, a fan came to the rescue of a racer who
needed parts that weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   The Toyota Supra of owner/driver Ahmed Sabban, Saudi Arabia,
co-driven by Peter Tonelli of Westboro, Mass., was having some
suspension problems and could have missed Sunday's Speedvision Cup
race.
</P>
<P>
   Fan Ivy Johnson III heard about the problem while mingling in
the pits area and offered his own Supra as a parts car. It is
sitting on blocks until after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a little problem finding transportation,'' Johnson
joked, ``but it's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
