<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-ADVANCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Superspeedway dishes up bevy of surprises
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ If Mark Martin had his druthers today, odds
are he would have the Winston Cup circuit running at Texas,
California or Bristol, three of the seven sites where he has
celebrated in victory lane in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Talladega and the Winston 500, the first of
back-to-back restrictor plate races. And for Martin it's like
taking a dose of medicine in his pursuit of Jeff Gordon and his
174-point lead for the Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another race on the schedule and it's what's coming
up,'' said Martin, who qualified eighth Friday. ``I said before, I
look at the two restrictor plate races back-to-back as some
medicine that you need to take and you may as well take it all at
once because when you're finished, you're through. We've gotta run
'em, and if you spread 'em out ... this way we'll do it and it'll
be over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's restrictor plate record at Talladega is a mixed bag.
He's won twice in 25 events, once in the Winston 500, once in the
DieHard. His last six finishes here are 23rd, first, 30th, 34th,
third and first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we can finish anywere,'' Martin said. ``We've won
Talladega twice and we could certainly do it again. We could go to
Daytona next week and handle right and run up front. The realist I
am, I say a two-dollar part will break any momentum there's ever
been.''
</P>
<P>
   Restrictor plates or not, overall there's little to choose from
between Gordon and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has a string of 15 consecutive finishes of fifth or
better, including seven victories and four seconds. His worst are a
pair of fifths, at Bristol and Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those places where anything can happen,'' said
Gordon, who won in 1996, but has finished 24th or worse five times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't come down to the way the chassis handles. It can
come down to a pit stop. Mark is running good everywhere we go.
They're a strong, strong team, and right now they're certainly one
of the cars to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need to finish close to him or in front of him, if we
can. But I think what it comes down to, especially the next couple
of weeks, is staying out of trouble and not have anything break. It
doesn't have anything to do with Mark and the six car. It has
everything to do with the 24 car and our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's run is almost as impressive as Gordon's. Four
victories, five seconds in six consecutive starts and eight other
finishes of seventh or better. The only blemish came at Darlington
where a blown motor left him 40th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things are going to happen,'' Martin said. ``If you call
the car we have a good car, which it is by our standards, we don't
have another one. If we tear this one up, we'll just be a lame duck
at Daytona. We've got a good starting spot here, and we're going to
do everything we can to hold up and do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
