<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Geoff Bodine awaits his fate
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Bodine, whose contract with owner Jim Mattei ends this
season, is ride-hunting for 1999. It doesn't mean, however, he
won't be back in the No. 7 Ford. ``I wish I knew what my plans
are,'' Bodine said. ``Right now I've been talking to several team
owners. Hopefully I'll know something in the near future.'' Mattei
is expected to announce his plans in the next week.
</P>
<P>
   Flock honored
</P>
<P>
   Tim Flock's widow, Frances, was presented a check for $67,584.96
last week at Darrell Waltrip's race shop in Harrisburg, N.C. Funds
were raised through the sale of commemorative diecast race cars, as
well as through Winston Cup teams and fans. Flock died of cancer
earlier this year. ``I wanted to pay tribute to one of our sport's
former champions,'' Waltrip said. ``Tim helped make this sport what
it is today. He was a dear friend of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   No bull
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup series moves to Talladega with five drivers
eligible for the No Bull 5 program _ Jeff Gordon, Jeff Burton, Dale
Jarrett, Dale Earnhardt and Jeremy Mayfield. Should one of them
win, he'll pick up the $1 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly: The Richard Petty Driving Experience will open a fourth
permanent location by Jan. 1. The Atlanta office will be
self-sufficient with its own staff, mechanics and fleet of cars. It
will be a year-round operation . . . With Mark Martin's victory
last Sunday, Ford and Chevrolet are even in the manufacturers
points standings with 201 each. Pontiac has 130.
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH
</P>
<P>
   Allen &AMP; Sawyer
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Allen Jr. will drive the No. 38 Barbasol car in 1999,
joining Elton Sawyer on the Atkins/Suton Motorsports team. Allen
moved from J&AMP;J Racing to join. ``I wanted to go somewhere that was
established and successful,'' said Allen, who is winless in 83
events. ``I feel like I have something to give Elton and he has
something to give me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarity for Cope
</P>
<P>
   Derrike Cope will make his first Busch start in more than a year
when he comes to Atlanta Motor Speedway to run in the Stihl 300,
which was rained out in March. Cope will run a limited schedule in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week
</P>
<P>
   Mike McLauglin's margin of victory last week at Charlotte was
24.074 seconds over Matt Kenseth, the largest in a Busch race since
Kenny Wallace beat Chuck Bown by 27.15 seconds on July 14, 1991, at
Loudon. McLaughlin's victory was the first for a Busch regular at
Charlotte since Chad Little in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFTSMAN TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Baffling Biffle
</P>
<P>
   Greg Biffle is on one of those streaks that few rookies can
believe. He's won three straight poles and leads the Rookie of the
Year standings by 18 points over Andy Houston heading into the
Sears Point race today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly hope I can continue this string, but I rather
doubt it,'' Biffle said. ``We have some really good experienced
road racers. Ron Hornaday and Joe Ruttman will be tough on the road
course. But, then, they're tough everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Road courses haven't been Biffle's strength this season. He
finished 27th at Watkins Glen and 21st at Heartland Park. The first
time he ran a road course at Watkins Glen, he was seven seconds off
the pace of the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   New course
</P>
<P>
   Drivers will see a new track configuration at Sears Point,
shortened to 1.949 miles from the previous 2.52-mile layout with
the construction of a chute that links turns 4 and 11. The change
added nearly five mph to the Bud Pole speed for this summer's
Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   Sauter to return
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sauter will return next year as the driver for Richard
Childress Racing. Sauter, Childress's choice since 1997, is the
only driver on the truck series who hasn't posted a DNF. ... The
Craftsman trucks made quite an entrance on their way to Sears
Point, crossing the Golden Gate Bridge with a California Highway
Patrol escort . . . Three different drivers have won at Sears Point
_ Ron Hornaday in1995, followed by Dave Rezendes and Joe Ruttman .
. . Ruttman has won three of the past five series road courses.
Like Hornaday, he has won on each venue _ Sears Point, Watkins Glen
and Heartland Park Topeka.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
