<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES311-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Counting down to victory
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson and Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Nine. That's how many peanuts Kevin Towers lined up
on the hotel bar that fateful night of October 14, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Now San Diego's general manager, Towers was a scout then for the
Pirates and in Toronto, scouting the AL Championship Series. That
night, the ALCS done, Towers sat in the bar at the Toronto Hilton
with Pirates assistant general manager Cam Bonifay and head scout
Lenny Yochim. They were watching Game 7 of the NLCS from Atlanta,
where Towers lived. With Pittsburgh ahead 2-0 after six innings and
Doug Drabek pitching, Towers lined up nine peanuts on the bar. One
for each out the Pirates needed to record to reach the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Game 6, had an off day,'' said Towers, who lived
then in the Club Tower at 16th and West Peachtree. ``I could watch
Nomar Garciaparra and Jay Payton play at Tech from my window. I ate
at the Varsity.''
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Towers was in Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium
when Tim Wakefield's knuckler and three Bucs homers ripped Atlanta
13-4. Once Pittsburgh took that 2-0 lead in Game 7, Towers thought
Pittsburgh was a lock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably one of the greatest feelings I ever had,'' Towers
said Saturday before Game 3 of the NLCS. ``We're up 2-0, Game 7,
Drabek on the mound and we're going to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the peanuts were disappearing. Towers tossed one
away with each ensuing out. The steady stream of flying nuts
suddenly sputtered in the ninth inning, especially after Stan
Belinda relieved Drabek. ``I think I was down to two,'' said
Towers. No. One peanut remained when Francisco Cabrera came to bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I saw a bunch of guys jumping on each other at the
plate,'' Towers recalled. ``And I called out, 'We didn't lose, did
we?'''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Sid Bream slid home with the winning run. Braves won, 3-2.
And that last peanut left on the bar? ``Threw it at the
bartender,'' said Towers.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, when San Diego sought to take a commanding 3-0 lead
in the NLCS, Towers assumed nothing. ``We're up 2-0,'' Towers said.
``But we realize we're facing Greg Maddux.'' Bottom line: There
were no peanuts lined up in the San Diego general manager's private
box.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch, that hurts
</P>
<P>
   The Braves dodged a pregame disaster when Kevin Millwood took a
batting practice line drive to the head and was able to walk away
from it. Millwood was stationed behind a screen in shallow center
field and had just poked his head around it to pick up a ball when
Ryan Klesko sent a liner up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The ball nearly hit Greg Colbrunn, who was running from first to
second and caught Millwood flush on the right side of the head near
the ear. He went down for approximately a minute before leaving the
field under his own power. He was able to run out during pregame
introductions.
</P>
<P>
   This has become a macabre Braves NLCS tradition. In 1995, Javy
Lopez drilled David Justice with a batting-practice line drive that
knocked him out of Game 4. Mike Devereaux, who started in his
place, wound up the series MVP. Last year, Greg Colbrunn hit
Chipper Jones in the head with a shot before Game 5 at Florida.
Jones was able to start, but went hitless the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Old No. 27
</P>
<P>
   When Greg Maddux's blue batting practice jersey was discovered
missing, the Braves starter borrowed an extra shirt from Gerald
Williams and prompted all sorts of conspiracy angles while two
Williams were on the field during batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually Jimy Williams','' said Maddux, recalling the
departed third base coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``A psychological advantage,'' Williams said. ``They're going to
think I'm all over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads up
</P>
<P>
   Braves team officials are sitting in two new rows of seats
installed up the third- and first-base lines, less than 90 feet
from the plate and in dangerous position for foul balls. When
Braves general manager John Schuerholz discovered his seat was the
first exposed to the plate, he was presented with a batting helmet
by traveling secretary Bill Acree and was modeling it in the dugout
before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
