<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's on deck for Game 4
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   -- When: 7:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   -- Where: Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   -- Radio/TV: Channel 5, WSB 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   -- Probable starting pitchers: LHP Denny Neagle (16-11, 3.55
ERA; 4-2, 2.73 lifetime vs. Padres) vs. RHP Joey Hamilton (13-13,
4.27; 2-8, 5.68 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   -- Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 272-216 and
won the season series for an eighth straight year, 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   -- Past meetings: The Braves were 1-2 at Qualcomm Stadium in the
regular season, the first losing record the club has accumulated
there since going 4-5 in 1991. Since the Padres joined the league,
Atlanta has a 130-115 record in San Diego, going 36-30 the past 10
years. In the Braves' only visit to Qualcomm this season, the
Padres beat Denny Neagle and Greg Maddux on successive nights (Aug.
11-12). Tom Glavine averted the sweep on Aug. 13 in a 5-0 victory
over Mark Langston. Atlanta managed to outscore the Padres 33-29
and out-homer San Diego 11-6 during the season.
</P>
<P>
   -- Padres leaders: Avg. _ Tony Gwynn (.321); HR _ Greg Vaughn
(50); RBI _ Vaughn (119); SB_ Quilvio Veras (24). W _ Kevin Brown
(18); ERA _ Trevor Hoffman (1.48). Saves _ Hoffman (53). Strikeouts
_ Brown (257).
</P>
<P>
   -- Neagle update: Neagle finally gets a chance after going two
weeks since throwing his last live pitch and 23 days since his last
start. The layoff was both beneficial and troubling. The down time
has allowed him to recover almost completely from a bout of
left-shoulder bursitis, which limited him to just two September
starts. But Neagle lives with the breaking ball and change-up, both
touch pitches that require regular maintenance. ``I don't think the
time off has hurt me at all,'' he said. ``I think it's helped me.''
Neagle was 0-1 against the Padres in two starts this year. He drew
no decision in Atlanta on May 10, after being knocked out after
five innings (four runs on nine hits).
</P>
<P>
   -- Hamilton update: Born in Statesboro, schooled at Georgia
Southern and now an Atlanta resident, Hamilton has been pounded by
the Braves like no other team in his five major league seasons. He
has given up 73 hits in 62 1/3 career innings, and his eight career
losses to the Braves are more than any other opponent. That does
not detract from his 1998 season, when he set career highs in
innings pitched (217 1/3) and starts (34). Despite a 4.27 ERA, he
kept the Padres in almost all his starts, and the team went 10-2
when Hamilton was given three or more runs in support. He was 1-2
against the Braves, the victory coming on Aug. 11, when he beat
Neagle, holding the Braves to a run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who's hot: Chipper Jones has a career .370 average against
Hamilton and is 3-for-7 against him in 1998. Andres Galarraga has
two homers against Hamilton in nine at-bats this season. Chris
Gomez has a .500 career average against Neagle and was 3-for-5
against him this year. Finley is a .318 hitter against Neagle,
while catcher Carlos Hernandez hits .350.
</P>
<P>
   -- Who's not: Michael Tucker has just two hits in 13 career
at-bats (.154) against Hamilton. Keith Lockhart has a .111 career
average against him. Gwynn hasn't figured out Neagle, going
5-for-39 (.167) lifetime against him. Second baseman Quilvio Veras
is a .182 career hitter versus Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
