<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-NCSTATE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    47-24 romp over 'Pack puts Tech in title hunt
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ North Carolina State was supposed to be Georgia
Tech's first tough test of the season. The Wolfpack was supposed to
have one of the best offenses in the ACC. The ACC title path was
supposed to pass through Carter-Finley Stadium, with the Wolfpack's
win over Florida State a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Georgia Tech's 47-24 whipping of N.C. State on
Saturday, Tech had aced its latest test, put on a one-sided
offensive show and brought the ACC title chase to Bobby Dodd
Stadium, where visits from Virginia and Florida State in the next
two weeks should reshape the conference picture.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia (5-0, 3-0 ACC) and Georgia Tech (4-1, 3-0) will square
off Saturday tied for first in the ACC. Georgia Tech likely
stripped the Wolfpack of its No. 23 ranking and any warm, fuzzy
feelings it might have had left from the FSU win. The Yellow
Jackets made a case for a Top 25 ranking and should feel better
about theirchances against the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, Tech needed only a half to do it.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 30 minutes, the Yellow Jackets took out N.C. State
running back Rahshon Spikes (shoulder stinger), the Carter-Finley
crowd of 48,600, quarterback Jamie Barnette (concussion) and
embarrassed long-snapper Grant Dorn.
</P>
<P>
   The only man they couldn't touch was All-American candidate
Torry Holt, whose first three chances on offense led to 133 yards,
a field goal and a touchdown. But those 10 points, next to Tech's
33 at halftime, didn't amount to much. Tech couldn't stop Holt on
the big plays but made the rest of the big plays themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Tech got 16 first-half points from its defense and special
teams, including a pair of touchdowns from Jason Bostic, one on a
blocked punt he returned for a touchdown and the other on yet
another fumble on a sack. The other two points came compliments of
N.C. State's Dorn, who sent a long snap through the Wolfpack end
zone for a safety.
</P>
<P>
   Holt gained 48 yards on his first catch on a slant on N.C.
State's first play, which set up a Dan Deskovich field goal. His
second touchdown came on another crossing route for a 40-yard gain.
That was when Tech could have panicked. On the next play, Holt took
a hand-off on a reverse, dropped back and launched a 45-yard
touchdown pass to Chris Coleman, cutting Tech's early lead to
12-10.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yellow Jackets answered with 21 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   After surviving the first quarter with a 5-3 lead, Tech
outscored the Wolfpack 28-7 in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
