<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just another ESPN game of the week
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD N.J. _ Depending on who's talking, when the
Atlanta Falcons play the New York Giants tonight on national TV, it
will be either just another game, a big game or a bigger game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta coach Dan Reeves, who coached the Giants from 1993-'96,
has downplayed his return to Giants Stadium all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be a lot of memories,'' Reeves said. ``But
am I going to make it a big thing? No, because I don't think I can
get that across to my players.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Chuck Smith seems to be approaching this game like
the others. And he doesn't seem to care that the 8:20 p.m. game is
the team's only appearance this season on prime-time TV (ESPN,
WSB/Channel 2). It's the same to Smith if the Falcons play on
national TV or beside an RV in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is the same whether it's on prime-time or not,''
Smith said. ``It's still one game, whether you win or lose. I don't
care. You probably ought to ask somebody else about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Falcons should pretend like this isn't prime time for
their apparent up-and-coming football team. They've made one
prime-time appearance in each of the last four years and have lost
them all. Atlanta has lost eight of their last nine prime-time
appearances since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying, however, that tonight's game affords the
Falcons a chance to show a lot of people that their 3-1 record is
not a fluke and that they can beat a team with a pulse. Their three
victories have come against 0-4 Carolina (twice) and 0-5
Philadelphia. The Giants are 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prepared the same way, but everybody knows in the back of
their minds that if you have a good game on national TV when
everybody is watching it could be something that helps your career
and the team,'' running back Jamal Anderson said. ``It's in New
York on national TV in the biggest media market in the world. I
think the stars are lined up.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves isn't sure about star alignment, but he admits this game
is different for him and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you're playing a game where everybody else in
the league can watch you, the players get excited,'' he said. ``But
the most important thing is (it's a chance to show) where we are
and where we can be. It's a chance to be 4-1 when we play the
Saints (at home) next week. And any time you win a conference game,
your chances of being in the playoffs improve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
