<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0234 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-SCENE-TEX     10-10 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO SHORTAGE OF BELLS AND WHISTLES IN SAN DIEGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Jung Ho Pak, not to be confused with Chan Ho Park,
threw out the ceremonial first pitch yesterday before Game 3 of the
National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Pak received this honor simply because he's artistic director of
the San Diego Symphony, which will be located next to the new
ballpark the Padres hope will be approved in November. Some of us
were hoping for Joan Embry, the fabulous San Diego Zoo celebrity
seen on late-night talk shows, but perhaps she was tied up with an
orangutan.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kemp, a one-time San Diego Chargers quarterback who became
more famous but less successful as a politician, was around and
available yesterday. But Kemp blew the big one in his last
election, and if it's one thing the Padres don't need right now
it's a political loser giving off bad karma.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres don't miss a trick in trying to push this ballpark
through, right from the moment you pull up to Qualcomm _ not to be
confused with 3Com _ Stadium and the attendant hands you a parking
stub and artist's rendition of the new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The pregame media buffet was especially lavish, featuring
enormous amounts of shrimp, crab legs, omelets and other
delicacies, more than enough to convince reporters from the Kyodo
News Service, El Sol de Tijuana and Agence France-Presse to get
behind the new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I was convinced long before that, having been
solicited in the parking lot by two 500-pound Haystack Calhoun
look-alikes who were proclaiming themselves ``The World's Biggest
Padres Fans.'' One look at their blue-and-orange painted faces, No.
19 (Tony Gwynn's number) emblazoned in their hair and the ``Go
Padres'' etched on their massive bellies was convincing enough, as
long as they promise to wear T-shirts over that blubber.
</P>
<P>
   One look at those two is enough to swear off the Qualcomm fish
tacos forever.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the guy parading around Qualcomm in a Union blue
Civil War uniform with a sign saying, ``Burn Atlanta Burn'' and
yelling, ``Go Sherman! Thanks for the Memories!''
</P>
<P>
   How could we let his beloved Padres sneak off to Northern
Virginia? No doubt they'd find him 10 years later wandering the
streets of Tijuana in a daze, clutching his tattered Tony Gwynn
baseball card and muttering obscenities at Padres owner John
Moores.
</P>
<P>
   Why would anybody even think about leaving San Diego when the
lady on the radio announced yesterday morning, ``Today's weather,
pretty much perfect. Blue skies, temperatures in the high and low
70s''? We're told that's pretty much the conditions year round.
</P>
<P>
   The city is magnificent with harbors and bays, golf courses, a
world-famous zoo, Sea World and million-dollar homes sitting high
on the cliffs overlooking the Pacific Ocean and U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm Stadium, however, is stuck several miles inland in the
Mission _ not to be confused with Napa, Loire or Great African Rift
_ Valley, wedged between two freeways and a ridiculous-looking
19th-century trolley car operating on a 21st-century elevated
monorail line.
</P>
<P>
   There's nary a yacht, sailboat or aircraft carrier in sight, not
to mention expensive luxury boxes. The new ballpark will have that
and much more (including pittance for rent payments) down on the
city waterfront. Let's hope the trolley car stays in Mission
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is the Padres are putting 62,000 or more people
in Qualcomm Park for every playoff game, which gives ammunition to
those opposing the ballpark initiative.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, even here in plush lush San Diego there are party
poopers who don't want their tax dollars being used to build a
ballpark for a baseball owner who made billions peddling computer
software.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those opponents will also scream bloody murder if the
U.S. Navy decides to cut taxpayer spending and sends some of those
aircraft carriers sailing off into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, right now, the people of San Diego are screaming in
delight over the Padres. They can smell a World Series coming and
the stadium issue is looking good. The pregame surf-and-turf
tailgaters sported buttons, badges and bumper stickers that urged
``Yes on C.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe they ought to get Joan Embry and her orangutan down
here and let her fire one over the plate _ just to be on the safe
side.
</P>
<P>
   Agence France-Presse would be impressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
