<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCUBA-DIVING11-COX     10-10 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCUBA-DIVING11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scuba becoming outdoor pastime everyone can do
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It took a little prodding to get Linda Pazdzinski
underwater. Now it's hard for her to explain her initial
apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (husband) Frank and the boys got certified in scuba, I
told them I wanted nothing to do with it,'' the 48-year-old
Mariettan said. ``I was afraid. It was frightening to me not to
know what was underwater. But after I experienced it, there was
nothing to fear at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Her decision to try scuba two years ago in a big tank at the
inaugural Discover Diving Expo at the Cobb Galleria Centre _ where
the show will be held for the third consecutive year this weekend _
was love at first breath. And it has further unified the family.
</P>
<P>
   Now all five members are certified. Frank III, 50, and sons
Frank IV, 17, and Mike, 16, all were certified three years ago as
part of a Boys Scouts high adventure trip to the Florida Keys.
Later, Chrissy, 19, joined the family passion. All have received at
least advanced training.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a mother, it's wonderful when we're all diving,'' said
Linda, who had her checkout dive for certification at Bonaire, in
the Lesser Antilles, as part of an anniversary gift. ``It's a nice
family bonding thing to do, something we all love.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also sort of a holiday tradition. The Pazdzinskis have
spent the last two Thanksgivings diving in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we dive, we go off in teams of three and twos,'' said
Frank III, a corporate manager for Coca-Cola Enterprises. ``We're
down there holding hands. My 17-year-old will even hold my hand.
It's a bonding I just can't explain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pazdzinskis' love of scuba is not all that uncommon, as the
sport _ once reserved only for macho thrill-seekers _ becomes more
popular and family-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only sports activity we know of that everybody in
the family can participate in at the same level,'' said Ron
Gryzelka, president of Atlanta Scuba and Swim Academy in Marietta.
``Mom, Dad and Junior are all equal in scuba diving.''
</P>
<P>
   Gryzelka is part of a scuba-crazy family himself. Wife Barb, son
Brad and daughter Dawn have been certified divers for years; they
frequently spend Christmas and New Year's diving in Bonaire. Their
passion for diving got them into the scuba business, which includes
the academy as well as a travel agency called Caribbean Dive Tours.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has responded to adventurous families, who make up
a large portion of the 2.7 million people the Sporting Goods
Manufacturers Association estimated went diving at least once in
1997. Family dive packages are numerous, and some resorts even
offer day care or baby-sitting to accommodate families with young
children. There also are family live-aboard programs, in which the
divers eat in, sleep in and dive from a boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have crew members there just to take care of the
kids,'' Gryzelka said, adding that the crew will take the children
on short trips to teach them more about the ocean's environment.
``The kids have fun and they learn something, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Gryzelka learned a thing or two on a family live-aboard trip
that has spurred him to lobby for a change in the minimum age
regulation in the U.S. He had befriended the father of a family of
four, Steven Weinberg, a University of Luxembourg professor and
scuba lover, while on board a 184-foot schooner near Belize, and
their long philosophical discussions frequently centered on the
U.S. minimum of 12 years old to become certified in scuba. That age
was adopted by the Recreational Scuba Training Council (RSTC) in
the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg was used to the no-minimum in Europe; one of his
children was certified at age 6. He said, ``I don't understand you
Americans. You're so aggressive and progressive on everything you
do, except for scuba diving. ... I love (scuba diving), but if I
didn't have the opportunity of having my family involved, I
wouldn't be doing what I love to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That got Gryzelka, as well as others, thinking about changing
the age requirements, and many hope the issue will be discussed at
the RSTC conference next weekend in Scranton, Pa. Gryzelka contends
that 12 years old is an arbitrary age, and that kids much younger
are mature enough to handle diving.
</P>
<P>
   Current RSTC guidelines, which are adhered to by most
certification agencies, allow junior divers between the ages of 12
and 14 to be certified only for diving with an adult; those 15 and
over can be certified in open-water diving. Those supporting a
change want to open the door to younger children, provided they
dive under close supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Christini of Scuba Schools International in Fort Collins,
Colo., said any change would be based on safety. He expects some
changes to be made eventually. ``It's really about setting up
parameters,'' he said. ``It's not so much about lowering the age
for certification, but to find ways to expose (younger kids to
scuba).''
</P>
<P>
   Any proposed change is news to RSTC national coordinator Ken
Brock, who says the issue has not been included on the agenda for
next weekend's conference, although he admits it could come up in
open discussion. Brock says the way to develop young divers is to
expose them to extensive snorkeling, not necessarily strapping
tanks to their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always find an 8- or 9-year-old just as mature as a
12- or 13-year-old,'' Brock said, adding that when the minimum of
12 was determined, it was based on how well a child could
understand the instruction and not on physical or maturity traits.
</P>
<P>
   Christini and Gryzelka say the issue will be discussed, and
there's a chance a new guideline will be in place next year.
Opening up the opportunity for more kids to get involved with
diving also strengthens the possibility that more families will
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we probably turned down 60 kids that were 10 or
11,'' Gryzelka said. ``And at the same time, we also were turning
down their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
