<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-TENN-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road-weary Munson returning to Georgia
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Larry Munson, Georgia's legendary radio
play-by-play announcer, has decided to come home.
</P>
<P>
   Munson, who moved to Nashville last January to be near his two
sons, said Saturday that he has purchased a home in Atlanta and
will be moving back in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The travel was starting to kill me,'' said Munson, in his 33rd
year of broadcasting Georgia football. ``I was leaving Nashville
early Friday morning and driving back Monday morning after (Georgia
coach Jim) Donnan's call-in show. I was exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson, who is in his early 70s, says he does not know how much
longer he'll broadcast Georgia games, saying he's taking it ``one
year at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy lifting
</P>
<P>
   ESPN'S College Game Day Show went off without a hitch Saturday
morning with the set located on top of Georgia's Tate Student
Center. In order to ensure that the roof could hold the multi-ton
set and all the crew and equipment, additional support was brought
in and placed in the Tate Center's game room, which was just
underneath the roof. In order to do that, ESPN had to compensate
Georgia for the revenue lost by shutting down the game room for
several days. It came to around $600.
</P>
<P>
   Early truce
</P>
<P>
   While there are a number of stories this week about a personal
feud between Donnan and his counterpart at Tennessee, Phillip
Fulmer, the two men exchanged pleasantries on the field less than
an hour before the game. Donnan was reportedly upset at Fulmer for
putting Peyton Manning back in the game late in a 38-13 loss last
year in Knoxville. Fulmer supposedly was mad because Donnan hired
his best recruiter, Rodney Garner, last January.
</P>
<P>
   Tough ticket
</P>
<P>
   The largest crowd in the history of Sanford Stadium (86,117
capacity) was expected for Saturday's game. One unidentified
Georgia student wanted some tickets so bad he stole a stack of
about 60 from the ticket window at Stegeman Coliseum on Friday. The
student walked right up to the window where other students were
picking up their tickets and reached in the window and grabbed a
stack from the attendant. UGA police chief Chuck Horton said there
was an arrest in the case Saturday morning but would not release
the name of the student. The tickets had a face value of about
$1,500.
</P>
<P>
   National spotlight
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which televised the game, and ESPN, which brought College
Game Day to Athens, were just a small fraction of the national
media in attendance on Saturday. Among the national college
football writers in Georgia press box were: Mark Blaudschun (Boston
Globe), Ivan Maisel (Sports Illustrated), Dick Weiss (New York
Dailey News), Andy Bagnato (Chicago Tribune), Chris Dufresne (Los
Angeles Times), and Steve Weiberg (USA Today).
</P>
<P>
   Stanfill honored
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia All-American lineman Bill Stanfill, the Outland
Trophy winner of 1968, was honored before the game for his
induction into the College Football Hall of Fame. Stanfill will be
formerly inducted in December in New York. Stanfill, from Cairo,
Ga., went on to have an All-Pro career with the Miami Dolphins and
was a member of the undefeated Super Bowl champions of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
