<SLUG> BC-NY-SHIPYARD-EXPLOSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELDER IS KILLED IN AN EXPLOSION AT THE BROOKLYN NAVY YARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An explosion in the hull of an oil barge in the
Brooklyn Navy Yard Saturday killed a welder and injured his
assistant, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred around 4:30 p.m. while the welder was on
a ladder, fire officials said. He was blown out of the hull through
an open hatch. The force of the blast propelled his body over the
starboard side of the ship; it came to rest on the dry dock, about
40 feet from the ship, said Assistant Chief Steven DeRosa of the
Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   The welder's cracked and battered helmet was found 100 feet off
the ship's port side. The victim's name was not released Saturday
night because the authorities had not yet notified his next of kin.
</P>
<P>
   The other man, who was holding the ladder for the welder, was
burned across his body and had cuts on his arms. He was listed in
stable condition at Kings County Hospital Center Saturday night.
His name was not released.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred on the dry dock of Eastern Technical
Services, a company that repairs ships in the Navy Yard, which is
on the East River between the Manhattan and Williamsburg bridges.
Telephone calls to the company's office Saturday night were
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Workers in other parts of the ship yard said they saw a flash
and then a rumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole ship vibrated,'' said a stunned Hector Mazara, 32, a
welder at a nearby dry dock. ``Everybody, everything vibrated.
Vibrated. Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred in a compartment of the ship that is used
to transport oil, officials said. Investigators said they did not
know the exact cause of the blast, but said they are looking
closely at two possible scenarios: that the man accidentally turned
his welding flame on his own gas tank or, more likely, that he
ignited oil fumes that remained in the compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said that the compartment appeared to have been
cleaned out but that they were uncertain whether the hull had been
tested for lingering gases.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Castro, a ship welder for 18 years, suspected that the
explosion was caused by residual fumes from the oil. ``The reason
that it's so dangerous is that there are gases that remain there,
gases that are explosive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers said that another welder had died under similar
circumstances two months ago while working on a boat at an adjacent
dock.
</P>
</TEXT>
