A0252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-AL-MOORE11-COX     10-10 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-MOORE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankees not quite great
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Memo to the New York Yankees: There is this problem
with trying to rank with the greatest teams of all time. You have
to do more than just tease through September. You actually must do
it through October, and we're talking about more than just once.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the Atlanta Braves. No, ask Johnny Bench, the Hall of Fame
catcher for the Cincinnati Reds. He once rolled his eyes after we
asked him if the Braves of the 1990s resembled his Big Red Machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many world championships have they won?'' said Bench,
knowing the Braves are one shy of the Machine's two.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Morgan shook his head Saturday night at Jacobs Field after
we asked him that same question about the Braves and the Indians,
now playing against what many have called the Greatest Team in the
History of the World.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any of these teams (the Braves or the Yankees) got in front
of the Big Red Machine, they'd get run over like they were a toy
truck. It's a joke to compare them to us,'' said Morgan, another
Hall of Famer from those Reds teams before becoming a TV analyst.
</P>
<P>
   So here we have the Yankees of Williams, Jeter and Wells, not to
be confused with those of Mantle, Berra and Ford, continuing their
search for the gateway to immortality Saturday night at Jacobs
Field in the American League Championship Series against the
Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for these Yankees is that they've yet to discover
even the hemisphere to immortality. This has much to do with the
Indians, suddenly the worst thing to happen to New Yorkers since
Mayor Guiliani had the nerve to ask them to act civil. After going
meekly in Game 1, the Indians have stuck more than a few arrows
into the puffy hype of these Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way according to those who
anointed these Yankees with the elite in baseball history after
they won 114 games during the regular season. They later swept
Texas out of the Division Series by holding them to only a run.
</P>
<P>
   Then came that Yankees' blowout in the ALCS's opening game
before the Greatest Team in the History of the World quickly looked
as overrated as their Atlanta counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are reasons for why both teams are having problems
getting to the next level and staying there,'' Morgan said. ``Every
great team has The Man. You have Michael Jordan for the Bulls. The
49ers had Joe Montana. We had Tony Perez, Pete Rose, Johnny Bench
and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Yankees, Morgan shook his head again, while thinking
of a team filled with nice guys and no leaders. As for the Braves,
Morgan told the truth by saying the Braves' foolishly shipped their
version of The Man to the Indians two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't coincidental,'' Morgan said, ``that they won their
only title (in 1995) when David Justice put the pressure on his
back by getting on the Atlanta fans. Then he hit the (World
Series-winning) homer. They've depended on their pitchers for
leadership, but look back in history. It can't be a pitcher. It has
to come from an everyday player.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who run these Yankees apparently don't get it. The same
goes for the Braves' Designated Geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore can be reached at tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
