<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NL-BRADLEY11-COX     10-10 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-BRADLEY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lineup rational out in left field
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ For the biggest game of 1998, the team that
considers itself the class of the National League sent out this
lineup:
</P>
<P>
   Danny Bautista in left field;
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams in right;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Graffanino at second base;
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez catching.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's a rationale. (Isn't there always?) The Braves were
facing a left-hander, and Perez is Maddux's personal catcher. But
this isn't reason enough to bench Javy Lopez and Ryan Klesko and
Keith Lockhart, not when you're down 0-2, not when the lefty in
question is the journeyman Sterling Hitchcock. This is, alas, what
the Atlanta Braves have become: A bully of a club that can be
intimidated by a Hitchcock who's somewhat less scary than Sir
Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   Williams set an NLCS record Saturday with four strikeouts. Perez
had two singles. Graffanino walked twice and scored the Braves'
only run. Bautista was 0-for-2. If these irregulars were no more or
less culpable for the Game 3 loss than the everyday Braves _ Andres
Galarraga and Walt Weiss and the Joneses _ it was nonetheless
bewildering to see a team weaken itself by design.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Braves were weakened further, Bobby Cox pulling
Maddux for a pinch-hitter after five innings. (Said pinch-hitter,
Greg Colbrunn, struck out.) It was a panicky move, made because Cox
had seen his offense wither and die. The Braves have scored three
runs in three NLCS games. They've had no extra-base hits since
Lockhart's double in the fourth inning of Game 1. Twice Saturday
they had a runner on third with one out and couldn't deliver him
home.
</P>
<P>
   The great surprise is that this isn't all that surprising. The
Braves are utterly dependant on the home run. They scored 15 runs
in the Division Series _ 11 on homers. But pit the Braves against
pitchers who know how to keep the ball in the yard _ pitchers like
the Braves' own _ and these hitters go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Said Galarraga, 1-for-11 in the NLCS: ``I don't know how to
explain what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not so hard, really. This team is incapable of
manufacturing. Neither Lockhart or Michael Tucker, both brought on
late, could produce a tying sacrifice fly. Neither Colbrunn or
Lopez, unaccountably saved for one pinch-hit turn, could stroke a
two-out hit. With these Braves it's all or nothing; through three
games it has been nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bottom-line business,'' Williams said. ``You can
analyze it until you get tired, but the truth is that we didn't get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves looked tired as dusk fell Saturday, tired and
confused. ``I don't think we've given (the Padres) any momentum,''
said Cox, lapsing into his postseason doublespeak. ``I think we've
stopped ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They stopped themselves Saturday before the game began. They
stopped themselves by deploying a lineup more suited to the
nightcap of a doubleheader. They stopped themselves by yanking
their pitcher too soon and trotting out their better hitters too
late. They acted not at all like the mighty team they're supposed
to be. They acted like a team about to get swept.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
