<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BISHER-COLUMN11-C     10-10 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHER-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee volunteers nothing
 &HT;    By Bisher Furman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ As the clock wound down and the autumn twilight
closed in on this leafy college town, and the public address
announcer, Brooks Whitmire, switched to exciting bulletins about
Georgia women's basketball and broke the news that the men's
volleyball team would play Clemson Sunday, you gathered the white
flag was being hoisted. The Georgia football team was in arrears of
Tennessee, 22-3, and a steady flow of red and black was crowding
the exits, and the hurt had not yet begun to set in.
</P>
<P>
   What had gone awry here will be no unsolved mystery. But where
had that team gone that had so distressed Louisiana State in its
own dreaded lair?
</P>
<P>
   This one became solvable from the toss of the coin. Georgia had
chosen to start on offense, not the usual style. Most teams choose
to defer. This one backfired on the second play, when the snap was
fumbled, Deon Grant recovered, and Tennessee had the ball on
Georgia's 19-yard line. Champ Bailey got the ball back with an
interception at the 3-yard line, but the Bulldogs were in such a
bind they couldn't escape until Tennessee kicked a field goal, and
things Red and Black never got any better.
</P>
<P>
   There was no element of a contest from that time until the
finale, when Philip Fulmer and Jim Donnan engaged in a traditional
postgame handshake that set a record in its brevity. Then the
exhilarated Fulmer trotted down toward the stands, where delirious
Tennessee fans sat, and flung his sweaty cap into the mass, then
trotted away.
</P>
<P>
   These were the same fans who later gathered beneath the podium
at Tate Student Center, where ESPN's Game Day crew was perched, and
chanted, ``Overrated! Overrated!'' chiding, of course, those who
had gone against form and picked the No. 7 team to upset the No. 4
team, based on those infernal polls. Instead, it was no Georgia
upset, and in the course thereof, they not only saw visions of a
Southeastern Conference championship go a-dwindling, but saw
critical chinks develop in its armor.
</P>
<P>
   The Quincy Carter who had delivered as in fables at Baton Rouge
came across as what he is, a freshman quarterback. He showed the
rust that accumulates from two seasons away from football action.
The line in front of him leaked like a rusty bucket. Tennessee put
a rush on him like he'd never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, his counterpart, Taumaurice Nigel Martin, the
junior from Mobile, turned in a performance Peyton Manning would
have been proud of. Tucked the ball and ran for 83 yards, not
deducting sack losses, and completed 16 of 26 passes for 156 yards
and two touchdowns. You might say he has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Champ Bailey, Georgia's flaming sophomore, was lost in the midst
of the turmoil. Out of it, rarely included in Georgia's scheme.
Tony Small was Carter's designated target, and he and the senior
from Jacksonville connected seven times for 144 yards. Bailey did
catch three passes after the fact and once, when Georgia went for
it on a desperation fourth-down flea-flicker late, threw an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting development of the afternoon dealt
with an absentee. Jamal Lewis, Tennessee's bullish running back
from Atlanta, is out for the season, and custom is to mewl over
such losses. In his stead, Travis Stephens and Travis Henry,
sophomore tailbacks, accumulated 160 yards between them, and ran
with malicious intent. Lewis had been averaging 124 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   So often it happens that an understudy steps out of the wings
and steals the show. It's routine in the theater, and while this
isn't Broadway, it's a steal from the old scheme. Lewis will get
his job back, but not until next year. Until then, Tennessee's
running game will be in good hands, or maybe that should be feet.
</P>
<P>
   This time there were no recriminations, no fuming charges of
running up the score, as in Knoxville last year. Matter of fact,
there would have been no grounds for complaint, for Fulmer was
helpless to do anything about it. Georgia's defense bent and broke,
and when the end came, the Vols were running straight ahead until
the final down, when Tee Martin put his knee to the ground and a
merciless end to it all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
