</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-NCSTATE-RAIL11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech, N.C. State roundup
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ FIRST-HALF ROUNDUP
</P>
<P>
   FIRST QUARTER: Both teams squandered touchdown chances after
getting big plays and settled instead for offsetting field goals.
Phillip Rogers scooted 29 yards along the sideline to set Tech up
to N.C. State's 29, but the Wolfpack shut down the drive and Brad
Chambers booted a 41-yard field goal, his longest of the season.
Torry Holt took a short pass from Jamie Barnette on State's first
offensive play from scrimmage and turned it into a 48-yard gain,
and the Wolfpack drove to the Tech 12 before calling on Dan
Deskevich, who kicked a 29-yard field goal. Both teams would
sputter after that, with Tech bogged down by penalties and State
having trouble on special teams and with turnovers. Tech led 5-3
after 15 minutes when the N.C. State long snapper shot the ball
over the head of punter Jesse Wade and out of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   SECOND QUARTER: The Jackets took command in a wild string of
events with a 28-point quarter to claim a 33-10 halftime advantage.
Wade mishandled a snap on his own 25 and the kick was blocked by
Travares Tillman, with Tech's Jason Bostic finally recovering in
the end zone. State tried some fancy maneuvering for its first
touchdown when Holt, on a reverse, planted and threw deep to Chris
Coleman, who beat two Tech defenders and jogged into the end zone
to make the score 12-10. But the Jackets shut down State after
that. Joe Hamilton, working from the Wolfpack 31, faked a handoff,
then a reverse, and threw a touchdown strike to Dez White. Charles
Wiley capped a 48-yard TD drive for Tech to blow the game open at
26-10. Then Tech's defense scored a touchdown for the fourth
straight week when Felipe Claybrooks caused Barnette to fumble, and
Bostic picked up the loose ball and rambled 21 yards for the score.
</P>
<P>
   1ST QUARTER
</P>
