<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUMMER-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Truth hurts for Carter, fellow UGA players
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ This college football thing had been the world's
longest sustained kiss for Quincy Quarterback. It began as an
open-ended honeymoon, an endless cruise into a pink sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the inevitable Saturday when even the most fortunate
one gets hit by a quarter ton or so of reality. The truth literally
does hurt, and it apparently favors orange.
</P>
<P>
   No, Mr. Carter, you can't win them all. Nor are you allowed to
complete your first 15 passes every time against a top-10 opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, against Tennessee Saturday, Quincy Carter actually did
look like the true freshman they keep insisting he is. This day, he
fumbled the day's second snap, was chased like the only ambulance
in Lawyer Town, and threw two interceptions _ one more than he had
suffered in his first four games. Much of Georgia's 22-3 loss to
the Vols looked like blue sky to Carter, so often was he laid flat.
</P>
<P>
   Downright human he was, unlike just a week ago when he put a
microchip-perfect beating on LSU. Perfectly understandable, said
his coach, who used to quarterback a little in his day. ``(The
Vols) were coming with the house. We didn't do a very good job of
protecting our quarterback. I'd be rattled out there, too,'' said
Jim Donnan.
</P>
<P>
   We had seen Carter only in the complimentary backlighting of
victory. How might he change following the first loss of what will
be a spectacular career? Not all that much, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day is Sunday, the following day is Monday and we'll
just go on,'' said Carter, a quick student of the Zen of football.
``Things like this happen. We'll become a better football team than
we were today.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the first defeat was total. There would be no need for
a single moment of what-iffing. The Vols physically dominated
Georgia, which allowed their estimable quarterback, Tee Martin, the
illusion of bettering Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, there was public concern about the fate of
the Sanford Stadium goal posts, should Georgia win a monumental
one. The fear was quite unfounded. No Bulldog would touch the
endzone during or after the game. Carter's 23rd and last
incompletion _ he connected on 14 _ was a rolling, desperate throw
to Champ Bailey in the general direction of paydirt. That's about
as close to six points as Georgia would come all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the two-sport athlete would have reason to
miss the peace and solitude of center field. In the outfield, you
hardly ever find yourself roto-tilled into the turf, unless, of
course, your last name is Klesko. And, when you are as modest a
hitter as Carter, the game requires surprisingly little running,
sliding or human contact.
</P>
<P>
   And no one lent him a helping hand. These Bulldogs cannot run.
The defense was all out of hunker-down by the second half. The
offensive line was overpowered. While Carter was sacked only twice,
he was chased constantly and knocked down remorselessly. The Vols
invited everyone to rush. I think I saw Jamal Lewis chasing Carter
with a crutch.
</P>
<P>
   The best that can be said for this one is that Carter proved
that he is tough as he is flashy. The hard way. ``We know we've got
a quarterback who will stand in there for us,'' said senior tackle
Matt Stinchcomb, who was moved to apologize to the freshman after
this loss. ''It's pretty hard for any quarterback to play well when
he's getting his head knocked off.''
</P>
<P>
   No honeymoon ends without a little pain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
