<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LEMANS11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lease Plan car survives Petit Le Mans
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They all said the strategy for Saturday's Petit Le
Mans, 1,000 miles or 10 hours of racing, was to stay on the track
until the final three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the racing starts,'' said Dan Doyle of the
Doyle/Risi Lease Plan Ferrari 333SP.
</P>
<P>
   Ten hours later, Doyle, a big bear of a man with an easy grin,
was in the middle of a champagne shower, courtesy of his winning
drivers, Wayne Taylor and Eric van de Poele.
</P>
<P>
   The Lease Plan survived and conquered in front of an estimated
crowd of 40,000, the largest anyone can remember. They might have
witnessed the rebirth of sports car racing in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a perfect race,'' said van de Poele. ``We didn't have
any trouble all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect for the winners, but hardly anybody else. It was a race
filled with breakdowns, glitches and a spectacular crash courtesy
of the big gun, the No. 26 Porsche, winner of the 24 Hours of Le
Mans. Its day ended with a spectacular crash on Turn 8 at 4:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting another car too closely, No. 26 Porsche driver Yannick
Dalmas got into a vacuum, lost the downforce on the front of the
car and when it went over the rise at Turn 8, the front end kept on
rising and the car back-flipped, landing on its rear end, swerving
left and crashing into the retaining wall.
</P>
<P>
   Dalmas, who was leading the race at the time of the crash, was
uninjured.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 4 Panoz GT1 and the No. 7 Lease Plan Le Mans Prototype
Ferrari, two laps behind the No. 26 car, found themselves one and
two respectively in a second.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz, which hasn't had any help at all on the home track in two
outings, was in the hunt temporarily but the hex struck in the form
of an oil leak so bad it couldn't be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 5 was lost during Friday practice when it hit an oil
patch and slammed the wall in front of the press tower.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Jim Downing's team, driving a new version of his Kudzu
Mazda, finished sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy with the way it's running, it could quit now and
I'd be happy,'' Downing said two hours earlier. He was ecstatic
over the finish.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid No. 07 Q9 Panoz GT1 was the only Panoz survivor,
finishing 12th overall and third in the GT1 class.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
