<DOCNO> NYT19981010.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0488 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS &LR;      10-10 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LABOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Struggle over power, control of NBA could harm both sides
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
No Basketball Allowed. No, that's not what the acronym NBA stands
for, but it could.
</P>
<P>
   After years of explosive growth that has taken it to a global
market, the NBA is in danger of imploding because of the continuing
labor struggle. The lockout has entered its third month, and with
no progress made on a new collective-bargaining agreement between
the players' union and the owners, it could be a while before
players begin bouncing basketballs in meaningful games.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, once the model pro sports league because of its
incredible growth over the past 15 years, has become one big
sandbox as owners and players try to decide how to split up
billions of dollars in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest topic in the labor war remains the Larry Bird
exception, which allows teams to re-sign their own free agents for
any amount regardless of the salary cap. According to the union,
the Bird exception has allowed the players to reap the rewards from
what has become a multibillion-dollar industry. According to the
owners, the Bird exception has become the root of economic ruin for
a league that has an eye on the financial seismometer because half
the teams lost money last season.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the losses, the owners are willing to miss
regular-season games for the first time in NBA history in an effort
to install what they think is a viable economic system. And
players, who made roughly $1 billion in salaries and benefits last
season, say they are willing to skip the season rather than budge
on the Bird exception.
</P>
<P>
   Which means neither side has learned anything from the fiasco
baseball perpetrated on its fans during the 1994 strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I will say is that if you have a business where
it is costing you more to make the product than you're getting for
selling it, you have to suffer the consequences for putting those
two things in balance, and that is where we are,'' said NBA
commissioner David Stern. ``All we can do is beg for the indulgence
of those who follow us and are associated with us and that we are
trying along with the players to come up with a formula that can
make this a long-term success story where our current failures
might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Failures the league says it is trying to address with the newest
proposal, the centerpiece of which is the attempt to phase out the
Bird exception. But one of the biggest problems in this labor
struggle is the prevailing notion among the players that the league
is not in financial trouble, but rather the owners are trying to
test their resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to press the players and the union,'' the
Rockets' Brent Price said of the owners. ``It seems that they want
total concession by the players, to get us to give up all our
freedoms. But we're unified.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means nothing, according to Steve Woods, a player agent
and a professor of sports business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear that all the time from the players, that they are
unified,'' said Woods, who represents former Rocket Kevin Willis,
among other NBA players. ``What does that mean? The problem you
find is that the players don't know what it (the labor struggle) is
about. Very few of them have actually read the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this abstract concept like, `Oh, isn't it good that
we're unified.' But they don't understand that it's an interesting
concept, but what are you unified over? You can be unified while
somebody drives you over a cliff, but that doesn't mean that you're
right. It doesn't mean that you're fundamentally right, and that's
the big flaw I see in this whole deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods thinks that attitude could wind up killing the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This labor dispute is not so much about money, but about power
and control,'' he said. ``Players think they have the economic
leverage to take more power and control. When you look at most of
the other labor disputes (in other sports), they have been about
compensation. But this dispute is more about power. Who should
control the league? Should it be the players or the owners? The
problem is that the players are not acting like equity partners in
the league. Instead, they're acting like disgruntled employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Disgruntled employees who aren't about to return to the
workplace soon. Even when the labor problems are hammered out and
the lockout is lifted, it is going to be a while before the NBA
plays regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best guess is that we think you need at least four weeks
to do every thing that has to be done,'' said NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik. ``People have been asking me, `Can you
shave a few days here and there?' Maybe that is possible, but I
don't think much. We definitely need some period of time for teams
to put their rosters together. I mean, we have some teams that have
only four or five players under contract right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Rockets, who have Hakeem Olajuwon, Price, Rodrick
Rhodes and Roy Rogers, acquired from Toronto in the Willis trade,
under contract. A situation like that could also have a poisonous
effect on the league, Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the regular-season starts, you're going to have 12 guys
on the team and half of them won't even know each others' names,''
he said. ``So the quality of the basketball will suffer. The games
are going to be awful this season, regardless of when this is
decided. The reason this will hurt the league is because licensing,
tickets sales, international TV and international licensing all
flow from the quality of the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players will get hurt a second way because they will be
losing out on opportunities they won't even see because less money
will be coming into the league because the quality will have
suffered so much. That is why I hold the union responsible, because
the players don't understand that. They don't understand cause and
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides appear to be holding out until John Feerick rules on
the arbitration hearing on whether the owners have to pay
guaranteed contracts to 220 players during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Woods warned players not to hold their breath, one reason he is
considering filing a grievance Monday against the union on behalf
of several players who are concerned about the labor impasse and
the union's negotiating tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guaranteed-contracts (arbitration) is a joke,'' Woods
said. ``They (the owners) negotiated it in good faith, and they
negotiated it with the understanding that if payroll goes above a
certain amount (51.8 percent of the basketball-related income),
they were going to need to reopen this agreement. And the players
agreed to it. They signed it. And payroll went above that amount
(close to 57 percent paid out by the owners). That's why there's no
way the arbitrator is going to rule for the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the owners to get that clause, they had to compromise on
other issues. So the owners are not unilaterally imposing some
hardship on the players and hurting the players. So for the players
to say, `Hey, we want to play, the owners are doing something bad
to us,' that is not true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
