<DOCNO> NYT19981010.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0493 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      10-10 2328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBARTOLO CASE WILL BE PIVOTAL FOR TAGLIABUE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul Tagliabue may not realize it yet, but he is facing
the defining moment of his tenure as NFL commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Tagliabue's employers, the 31 NFL owners, look at him
and think, ``Big TV contracts, big franchise fees, big job well
down.'' On those scores they are right, even though Tagliabue also
presided over the league when it lost the second-largest TV market
in the country (Los Angeles) and put teams in the hinterlands of
Jacksonville and Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   NFL owners have made big money under Tagliabue's stewardship and
professional football has never been more popular, so no one can
complain too loudly. Yet today he faces the crisis that could
define him.
</P>
<P>
   Before long Tagliabue will have to decide the future not only of
49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo but also the future of the San
Francisco franchise and the future power of his own office.
</P>
<P>
   It should be clear now why Edward DeBartolo Sr. sent Carmen
Policy out to San Francisco 15 years ago to watch over his son's
handling of the team. Policy was the elder DeBartolo's consigliere,
the trusted lieutenant sent west from Youngstown, Ohio, to keep an
eye on the family's business interest there.
</P>
<P>
   It worked well for a while. Super Bowls followed Super Bowls.
Hall of Fame quarterbacks followed Hall of Fame quarterbacks. Great
coaches followed great coaches. But in 1994 the father died,
leaving the son in charge of his mammoth shopping mall development
company and its diversified interests as well as the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly the son began to tire of having Policy advise him on
policy. Eventually DeBartolo stopped listening, and last week he
paid the price. DeBartolo avoided prosecution on federal bribery
charges in Louisiana by pleading guilty to ``misprison of a
felony,'' which is another way of saying he knew of an alleged
scheme by former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards to extract payoffs in
exchange for a riverboat casino license because he was one of the
guys making the payoffs and didn't tell anyone about it until he
was threatened with a federal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Policy had counseled DeBartolo against going into the gambling
business in Louisiana, a state long known for politcal corruption,
but DeBartolo ignored him and is alleged to have hand-delivered a
briefcase stuffed with $400,000 in cash to Edwards. Barely 24 hours
after the money changed hands, according to federal authorities,
DeBartolo got the last riverboat gaming license the state had, and
barely 12 months after that, he pleaded guilty to a felony charge
that could have landed him in prison for three years. He agreed to
pay a $1 million fine and do something else that must have his
father twisting in his grave.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to become a rat.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards called him ``the new Linda Tripp'' after the hearing in
Baton Rouge at which DeBartolo pleaded guilty to concealing what
his lawyers now call an extortion attempt rather than a bribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd victimized him, I would have done it for a lot more
than $400,000,'' crowed Edwards, who at 71 is facing his third
federal indictment in the last two decades on racketeering charges.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo agreed to testify to get out of a deal Policy told him
stunk to the high heavens in the first place, and when it all came
to light last December, DeBartolo was forced to relinquish
day-to-day control of the 49ers to his sister when he was named as
a target in the federal probe. Now Policy has fled to Cleveland to
help run the expansion Browns organization as a minority partner
while DeBartolo faces a fight for control of the team he loves with
his sister, Denise DeBartolo York, who nominally heads it at the
moment and some say is of a mind to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Tagliabue. Because of DeBartolo's admissions, the
commissioner is empowered to ban him from day-to-day operation of
the team for as long as he wants. Some NFL insiders allege that
DeBartolo has the kind of gambling debts that undid onetime Eagles
owner Leonard Tose. Whether he does or not, all Tagliabue is saying
for the moment is that the present arrangement _ in which York is
the controlling partner and DeBartolo loyalist Larry Thrailkill
runs the day-to-day operation _ will continue through this season.
</P>
<P>
   But what then? What does Tagliabue do when one of his 31 bosses
has to testify to paying a former governor in an attempt to land a
casino license? If it was extortion, why didn't he call the FBI
before he delivered the cash? Why did he accept the casino license
and not say something even then? Why did it take the threat of a
federal indictment to suddenly see he was being extorted and why
did he reportedly take the Fifth Amendment the first time he was
called in front of the grand jury?
</P>
<P>
   While Tagliabue is mulling over his options, some voters in San
Francisco have tried to revisit the funding of a new stadium at
Candlestick Point. Originally, DeBartolo wanted to include a mall
and shopping complex with it, but his sister and Policy opposed
that because of the exorbitant costs _ at least $500 million _ and
that end of the development is now in question. Thrailkill said
recently the stadium could include cost overruns of at least $150
million, which was close to the original estimate of the
stadium-mall complex, instead of the present $325 million stadium
price tag. San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown went apoplectic, and a
press conference was called to allow Thrailkill to back off that
number, which he dutifully did.
</P>
<P>
   But what are skeptical voters to think now? Who's in charge of
the 49ers today? Who will be tomorrow? Many of the team's present
employees, including director of football operations Dwight Clark
and personnel director Vinny Cerrato, are more than a little
worried that if DeBartolo reassumes control, he will wipe them all
out as perceived Policy loyalists and possibly put Packers coach
Mike Holmgren in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Where does all this leave the commissioner's office if he does
nothing more than slap DeBartolo on the wrist? The NFL has a long
history of taking firm stands against player involvement in illegal
gambling. It has a long history of suspending players involved in
drug abuse. It has a long history of fining and suspending players
involved in on-field violence and now has a policy that addresses
off-the-field violence as well.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, how could Tagliabue allow DeBartolo to walk
away untouched.
</P>
<P>
   If he does ban DeBartolo, Tagliabue knows a lawsuit will likely
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if he does little or nothing, the next time he tries
to discipline a player for gambling or some other illegal action,
he'll find another battery of lawyers waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   So what is he to do?
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo will sell out Edwards to save his own hide and then
hope Tagliabue will sell out future commissioners by bending over
backwards to save his hide again. Tagliabue well might do that
because the NFL is a fraternity of rich men who tend to protect
their own, and DeBartolo was a popular member of that fraternity
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if it gets too hot in Louisiana when the questions
about payoffs and kickbacks and casino licenses and gambling debts
come to light, DeBartolo may suffer the greatest indignity of all.
</P>
<P>
   He may force Tagliabue to prove that the law degree he got from
NYU still stands for something.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sad story of the dissolution of a quarterback continued in
Charlotte last week when young  &UR; Kerry Collins  &LR; walked into the
office of Panthers coach  &UR; Dom Capers  &LR; Wednesday and basically told
him to take this job and shove it. Dogged by doubts and failures in
a town that apparently was a little too small and a little too
quick to question his lifestyle, his ability, his everything,
Collins simply told Capers he couldn't take it anymore, becoming
the first player in sports history to say, ``Bench me or trade
me.'' Carolina tried to do the latter on Thursday but was asking
for a No. 1 draft choice, which simply isn't going to happen. So
Collins was put on the inactive list and stayed home for Sunday's
game in Dallas. The Panthers will likely release him if he can't be
traded by next Tuesday, although they could simply sit him out for
the year. The biggest stumbling block to a trade is that Collins
becomes a free agent at the end of the season ... It seems a good
 &UR; Dick Vermeil  &LR; story surfaces every week. The latest is that after
the Rams lost their home opener to the Saints, the coach got an
angry letter from a season ticket-holder named  &UR; Jeff Roberts &LR; .
Roberts said he'd worked hard to be able to afford his tickets but
was ``disgusted with the way the team played and more or less the
way you coached.'' He enclosed the rest of his tickets. Vermeil was
so bothered by the letter that he had his wife track down Roberts
and invite him and his 6-year-old son to a team meeting the night
before the next home game. After the meeting, Vermeil talked for a
half-hour with Roberts, then reached in his pocket for the tickets
and said, ``I believe these belong to you, if you want them back.''
Roberts took them and says he'll keep coming back as long as the
Rams are in St. Louis ... The recent rise of Atlanta may not be all
it seems. Under coach  &UR; Dan Reeves &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Falcons have gone 9-3
since opening last season 1-7. But none of those victories have
come against a team with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans coach  &UR; Mike Ditka  &LR; may have been more fun to watch
in the old days, but this is what he learned about his
often-explosive and always-televised sideline demeanor: ``When
you're winning, they call it enthusiasm. When you're losing, they
call it anger.'' ... Asked if it was true that fullback  &UR; Ray
Zellers  &LR; disliked blocking, Ditka replied, ``I don't blame him. Ray
thinks he's a tailback. If he couldn't do it, I'd say fine. He has
done it. I've seen him do it in the past. He'll do it again.'' ...
Ditka also talked last week about his decision not to draft Vikings
wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss &LR; , who is tearing up the pea patch (not to
mention NFL secondaries). ``I anguished for many weeks about
picking Randy Moss,'' said Ditka. ``When it came down to it, if I
would have made the final decision to say we'll take him, we would
have taken him no matter what anybody else said here. They would
have let me do that, but I felt at this point, as good as Randy
was, he couldn't have that much effect on our football team because
we don't have the people around yet to get him the ball to do those
things. I thought we were building the foundation with the line
people. Whether I'm right or wrong, that's the way I believed and
that's the way I went. But he's good. I like him. I'm happy for
him. He's in the right place. He could be in a lot of other places
that wouldn't be the right place. They've got a great offense. They
do the right things for him, got people to get him the football.
He's in with two quality, top-notch receivers, which makes it hard
for you to double-team any one of them. I'm happy for his success.
I hope it continues.'' ... With representatives of Houston and Los
Angeles due to address league owners in Kansas City Oct. 27 on
their efforts to make a run for the next expansion team, another
owner is sitting comfortably despite his own stadium problems.  &UR; Bob
Kraft  &LR; has a troubled stadium situation but also the freedom to
pick up and move whenever he wants, because he is a tenant-at-will
at Foxboro Stadium, which he also owns. He already has been
approached by people willing to buy him out and move the Patriots
to Los Angeles, and he could do it himself without the league
intervening or legal entanglements in Massachusetts stopping him.
It would be a bonanza for him. Broncos owner  &UR; Pat Bowlen  &LR; is
believed to have the same thing in the back of his mind if he loses
a Nov. 3 stadium financing vote in Denver, but he has a lease
binding him to Mile High Stadium for 15 more years and certainly
would face lawsuits and injunctions if he tried to uproot the
Broncos ... The NFL may have a salary cap, but it's soft as a
beret. According to NFL Players Association figures, 22 of 30
teams, by virtue of fancy financing, are over the $52.38 million
``cap.'' In some circles this might be called cooking the books,
but in the NFL it's called creative management. The Patriots, for
example, are on the hook for $63.6 million in real money,
sixth-highest in the NFL. But how'd you like to be the hapless 0-4
Panthers or 0-5 Redskins? Carolina is second in the NFL, laying out
$67.7 million. And the Redskins rank just behind New England in
expenditures for a team that can't stop anyone from scoring. Of the
eight that are below the imaginary $52.38 million cap, only Atlanta
and Miami are winning teams. The Dolphins, in fact, are in the best
shape of any team. Their cap number is $47 million and they are
3-1, tied for first in the AFC East. That shows that  &UR; Jimmy Johnson
 &LR; can not only coach but count.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville coach  &UR; Tom Coughlin  &LR; said he learned a hard lesson
from his team's 42-17 playoff loss to the Broncos last year.
``Denver has taught a lot of people some lessons,'' Coughlin said.
``Our particular style and our commitment to try and develop the
run and stop the run is a result of the embarrassing loss we had to
them.'' Coughlin also said the blitzing pressure so many teams have
begun to put on the quarterback the last two seasons has become an
irreplaceable factor ... Don't be surprised if Minnesota running
back  &UR; Robert Smith  &LR; declines to celebrate after his next touchdown.
Smith lost three teeth after scoring on a 67-yard pass play against
the Bears two weeks ago when he unbuckled his chin strap just as
352-pound teammate  &UR; David Dixon  &LR; rushed over to hug him. Dixon hit
Smith so hard he knocked Smith's facemask back into his mouth and
shattered his teeth.
</P>
</TEXT>
