<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLES-PENGUINS-NY     10-10 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TV, OR REPLAYS, OR (ESPECIALLY) VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (js) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ The sky didn't fall, and neither did their
10-ton scoreboard. But the Islanders, the Chicken Little franchise
whose threat to boycott their home games due to unsavory conditions
at Nassau Coliseum landed them in state and federal court last
month, fell into immediate arrears on the 1998-99 season Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Forced by a state Supreme Court ruling to play their home games
at their 26-year-old county-owned home base, the Islanders lost
their season opener against the Pittsburgh Penguins, 4-3. The game
was not shown on Fox Sports New York, which blamed its decision on
a dearth of advertisers, but it was seen live here by 11,457 fans
whose mood ranged from hostility toward the new Islander ownership
to embarrassment for the players caught in the web of management's
machinations.
</P>
<P>
   As fans entered the arena, they were handed fringed white towels
to wave if and when their players scored. Other than that meager
touch, there were no welcome, or welcome back, mats laid out.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there wasn't even the traditional opening-night
introduction ceremony to honor the players: David Seldin, the
president of New York Sports Ventures, which owns the club,
attributed that oversight to Spectacor Management Group, the
company that runs the facility. Seldin also blamed SMG for the
virtually blank scoreboard, which showed the score but no replays.
</P>
<P>
   According to Seldin, the scoreboard, which is due to be
replaced, sprang a mysterious leak and dripped a small but steady
stream of water onto center ice throughout the opening period:
``The lack of cooperation we're receiving from the building is
profound,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And for the Islander faithful, the opening period was a doleful
one. Jaromir Jagr ignited a three-goal scoring spree with his
power-play deflection at 4:50, and in the space of four shots
between 4:50 and 6:02, the Penguins staked themselves to a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 3-0 we're scrambling for some sort of life preserver,''
said Mike Milbury, the coach and general manager, who called a
timeout after the third Penguin goal. As for the added
opening-night distraction caused by the club's off-ice
controversies, Milbury said, ``There's no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islander defense, operating somewhere between dismay and
deflation, was culpable on all three goals, with Rich Pilon
providing an inadvertent assist to Jagr on the first one, which
scuttled off his skate and behind goalie Tommy Salo. The second
Pittsburgh goal was scored by Robert Lang at 5:42, and Aleksei
Morozov completed the carnage at 6:02.
</P>
<P>
   When Jagr went to the penalty box on a hooking call, there was a
brief flurry of optimism among the fans, but things quickly turned
vituperative when the Islander power play failed to assert itself.
The crowd, sympathetic at the game's start and stunned into silence
by the Penguins' three-goal outburst, began to boo the home team.
</P>
<P>
   With five minutes left in the period, the crowd began to chant
for Zigmund Palffy, the unsigned superstar and league leader in
power-play goals (17) last season: ``We want Ziggy,'' they
demanded. And when Brad Werenka, parked just inside the blue line,
cranked out the slap shot that put Pittsburgh ahead by 4-0 at
18:04, the fans launched into a sarcastic lament for John Spano,
last year's fraudulent purchaser of the perpetually on-the-block
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Spano,'' they jeered. What they got instead, with just
over 8 seconds left on the clock, was a glimmer of hope from Kenny
Jonsson, who powered the puck behind Pittsburgh goalie Tom Barrasso
at 19:51 and trimmed the deficit to 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Trevor Linden, the team captain who
finally accepted the Islanders' take-it-or-leave-it offer of $2.5
million just four days before this opener, made up for the missing
Palffy by contributing two power-play goals of his own. Now
perceived as a hero by the Islander fans, who believe Linden
deserved the $4 million, multi-year deal he sought but exhibited
true professionalism by returning in time to lead his dejected
troops into the season, Linden put the Islanders back into
competitive position with a close range tip-in at 5:03.
</P>
<P>
   Linden made it a 4-3 game at 16:58. The towels twirled merrily,
but with no further heroics on tap for the final period, where
Linden missed a hat trick chance in a goal-side scramble with 3:54
remaining, the Islanders settled for a close loss instead of the
rapid rout.
</P>
<P>
   But the patience of the club's fans, many of whom wore Islander
jerseys emblazoned with the names of stars from the club's past, is
dwindling fast. All one had to do was look at the ice, where white
towels were tossed like garbage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
