<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TURNING UP INTENSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ After a misty Thursday morning walk-through
practice, Patriots coach Pete Carroll gathered his team around the
20-yard line at Foxboro Stadium and lit into them. Walk-throughs
are called that because they aren't very intense; the players
simply ``walk through'' some of the plays and formations in
preparation for real practice later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll detected a tone he didn't like. After waving his
arms and speaking in a very animated voice to his players, he
dismissed them and gathered his coaching staff in the same
semi-circle. Again, Carroll was animated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to make sure that we understood the importance
of this game and the commitment to the preparation that we needed
to make,'' said fullback Tony Carter, who is quietly emerging as an
offensive leader.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll acknowledged later, ``I just felt I needed to do
something to get them going.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how the week began in preparation for Sunday's game
against the Kansas City Chiefs. The practices, according to players
and coaches, were intense and precise the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Players seemed happy when practice was over Friday afternoon and
they could get on with the task of winning a game that means early
bragging rights among the elite in the American Football
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   A win would be a momentum-builder because the Jets and Dolphins,
division rivals both, are the next two opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be one of the biggest tests of the year for us,''
said Carter. ``Everybody's mood is the same: We come out and we
want to work hard each week. Sometimes there's going to be more
emphasis on certain things each week as the season builds up. We're
sticking to our game plan. We're not doing anything noticeably
different, just trying to do certain things a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Shawn Jefferson, who has faced the Chiefs more
than any other Patriot (10 times, dating back to his days with the
San Diego Chargers), said, ``We have a chance to define who we are.
We have a couple of games coming up which are going to test our
will to win. We've got some division games coming up, but I think
we need to focus on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember most about Kansas City teams is they come to
play. We have to be clicking on all cylinders. It's one of those
where you have to find a way. It's going to be one of those
drag-down, knockout games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will have to rectify one lingering problem on
defense: getting off the field. They have allowed opponents to
convert 45.3 percent of third-down chances, which is much too high.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches and players all feel they are one or two plays away
from changing all of that dramatically. Carroll even said, ``We're
on the verge of being a defense that will be very hard to deal
with.'' They won last week in New Orleans, 30-27, but they managed
to stop the Saints on only 9 of 18 third downs. Do that against the
Chiefs and the Patriots will embarrass themselves at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are holes in our zone defense that we need to plug up,''
said linebacker Ted Johnson. ``A lot of guys are asked to do things
on third down and we're not all coming through. Sometimes you play
back on your heels and get tentative in that spot. We can't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will have to contend with Donnell Bennett, a halfback in
a fullback's body, who has had some consistent if unspectacular
games since gaining 115 yards on 24 carries against Oakland Sept.
6. He had 62 yards in the rain vs. Seattle last week, and gained 87
in each of the previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Law and Chris Canty may have their hands full with wide
receivers Andre Rison and Derrick Alexander. Rison is nearly back
to 100 percent after being plagued with an early-season hamstring
injury that forced him to miss two games.
</P>
<P>
   Also returning for the Chiefs is No. 1 quarterback Elvis Grbac,
who missed four games with a separated shoulder. Former Patriot
Rich Gannon went 3-1 in relief of Grbac.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Patriots must eliminate the turnovers that
nearly ruined their stay in New Orleans last week. A 3-point
victory should have been a 21-point win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
