</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANADIENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: CANADA, N.Y.)  
 RANGERS GO NORTH, BUT THE DEFENSE GOES SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In his original travel plan, coach John Muckler
wanted his Rangers to stay after the game Saturday and spend an
extra night here in Quebec. Instead of hurrying for a charter
flight home, they could have enjoyed the bonding process that
sometimes occurs at night on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is better that a lack of available hotel rooms kept
them from crying in their beers after losing their second game in
two tries. They might have discussed the video review on a pivotal
play in the Canadiens' 7-1 victory Saturday night in the Molson
Center. Or they might have acknowledged that some of their early
difficulties stem from their inherent flaws.
</P>
<P>
   For instance: They can't score if they can't shoot and they
aren't putting many pucks on opposing goaltenders. In Friday
night's season opener, they managed 20 shots in a 1-0 loss to
Philadelphia at Madison Square Garden. Saturday, they put only 21
shots on Jocelyn Thibault. Only eight of them came in the first two
periods, when the outcome was still in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Richter played well for two periods, but seemed tired as
the Canadiens, playing their first game, scored five goals in the
final 20 minutes. Adam Graves scored for the Rangers. Saku Koivu,
Vincent Damphousse, Craig Rivet, Benoit Brunet, Scott Thornton,
Igor Ulanov and Brett Clark scored for Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens took the lead, 2-1, at 13:32 of the second period,
on the power play, but the goal didn't count until it was confirmed
by video replay. Vincent Damphousse scored it by beating Richter
from low to the left of the net, but the puck bounced out quickly
and play continued for more than a minute. After a whistle, referee
Lance Roberts consulted with the video judges as the scoreboard
screen showed a replay of the puck seemingly going in the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were shorthanded because Aleksei Kovalev, at the end
of a very long shift, was called for obstruction holding. After the
goal, 1 minute 8 seconds was was restored on the clock. The Rangers
were doubly jinxed because play was stopped when Esa Tikkanen was
penalized for holding. Had the Rangers scored during the phantom
time between the Damphousse shot and the next whistle, the goal
would have been negated. However, a penalty in that time period
would not have been washed out. The Rangers argued long and loudly
that the penalty should have been canceled. The Rangers had an
excellent scoring chance in that time period, but Canadiens
goaltender Jocelyn Thibault stopped rookie Manny Malhotra on a
breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the game, the Rangers were suffering from injuries.
Defenseman Alexsander Karpovtsev and right wing Todd Harvey, both
hurt in Friday night's 1-0 loss to Philadelphia in the season
opener at Madison Square Garden, were sidelined. Both were listed
with the status of day to day, Karpovtsev with a bruised knee,
Harvey with a hip flexor. Scott Fraser, another right wing, missed
his second consecutive game with the effects of a concussion
suffered in the exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   Malhotra was making his first National Hockey League appearance
in a regular-season game. The 18-year-old center was chosen by the
Rangers in the first round of the entry draft last June. Malhotra,
who sat out Friday's game, centered a checking line with Adam
Graves on the left and Mike Knuble on the right. On an early shift,
Malhotra knocked Vladimir Malhokov, Montreal's big defenseman, into
the end boards. Malhotra also got the Rangers' first shot of the
game, after almost 8 minutes of play, but Thibault stopped him from
close range. Malhotra also showed precocious poise on
penalty-killing assignments.
</P>
<P>
   The teams each scored goals in the first period, Saku Koivu at
even strength for Montreal, Adam Graves on the power play for New
York. Koivu created the play by rushing up ice and twirling after
crossing the blue line before making a long shot that beat Richter
at 9:50. Graves tied the score with a power-play goal at 11:13,
knocking Knuble's rebound from the side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rangers' first power-play goal of the season after an
0-for-6 debut on Friday night. The goal might have been aided by
the new dimensions of the goal crease. Last season's wide
semi-circle has been shaved by 2 feet on each side. Graves was
parked in an area that might have been part of the crease last
year. Also assisting was Gretzky, who had many scoring
opportunities in the first 20 minutes. He seemed to show less
energy in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
