<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-TEX     10-10 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES STUMP BRAVES AGAIN, 4-1, TAKE 3-0 LEAD IN NLCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The Atlanta Braves have caught the same disease that
afflicted the Rangers, and it might cost them another trip to the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' offense has been silenced by the San Diego Padres
just as the Rangers' was by the New York Yankees in the American
League Division Series, and the best starting pitching in baseball
can't make up for it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Braves were pushed to the brink of elimination with
a 4-1 loss to the Padres in Game 3 of the National League
Championship Series yesterday. A crowd of 62,779 rocked and shook
Qualcomm Stadium with thunderous delight as the Padres took a 3-0
lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be our time,'' Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn said.
``We're getting good starting pitching, guys are delivering with
the bat and making defensive plays. But from our standpoint, we
have to think they have a chance they can come back and keep on
doing what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   History says the Braves are finished. No team in major-league
history has ever come back from a 3-0 deficit and won a postseason
series. In fact, 18 of the 21 teams who took a 3-0 lead went on to
sweep the series. The other three finished it off in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could for ask for a better situation,''
Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. ``But we still have to be
levelheaded about it and remind ourselves it's a best-of-seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Hitchcock, who has beaten Randy Johnson and Greg Maddux
in the playoffs, held the Braves to three hits in five innings,
then let relievers Donne Wall, Dan Miceli, Randy Myers and Trevor
Hoffman finish it.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who have scored three runs in three games, had eight
hits and drew seven walks but failed to score in two bases-loaded,
one-out situations in the sixth and eighth innings. A third-inning
rally also died when Walt Weiss was thrown out at home by left
fielder John Vander Waal while trying to score from second on
Chipper Jones' single.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at our offense and see we scored three runs in three
games and it's hard to believe,'' Braves outfielder Ryan Klesko
said. ``You see it happen to other teams against our pitching, but
it usually doesn't happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves pitchers aren't doing too badly, but they're getting
pounded when San Diego pitchers grab a bat. Kevin Brown had two
hits Thursday, and Hitchcock yesterday started a two-run rally in
the fifth against Maddux by grounding a one-out single through the
left side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody with a bat in their hand is dangerous,'' Maddux said.
``It doesn't matter if it's the pitcher or Tony Gwynn. Give him
credit. He put the bat on the ball and found a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves led 1-0 at the time, but Hitchcock moved to second on
Quilvio Veras' high chopper back to the mound and scored on Steve
Finley's double to left-center. After Gwynn was intentionally
walked, Ken Caminiti put the Padres ahead for good with a single to
right.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, now 3-6 in LCS play, was finished after five. Manager
Bobby Cox went to the bench in the sixth when the Braves loaded the
bases with one out against Hitchcock and Wall. But Wall came back
to strike out pinch hitters Michael Tucker and Greg Colbrunn to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The same scenario unfolded again in the eighth when the Braves
loaded the bases with one out. This time, Myers got Keith Lockhart
on a short pop to left and Hoffman came in to strike out Javier
Lopez. The Padres then scored two in the eighth to put it away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't leave the bases loaded without doing some damage,''
Cox said. ``For some reason, we had won 10 in a row (before this
series); we were hot as a dickens, getting line drives everywhere.
Now they've shut it down completely.''
</P>
<P>
   History says the Braves don't have time to get it going again.
The Rangers never did either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
