<SLUG> BC-FBC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES LIGHTEN LOAD WITH BIG VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ On afternoons such as yesterday, the
scene at Kyle Field is unmatched in college football, or, for that
matter, unmatched in any sports' venue coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   First, this was a rare big-game atmosphere that had come
floating down the Brazos. When combined with the traditional
hocus-pocus that makes football at Aggieland uniquely one of a
kind, well ...
</P>
<P>
   Call it a magical moment, and then hold on tight as massive
concrete upper decks sway like cottonwood trees, moving to the
frenzied rhythm of a maroon army gone bonkers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you heard, a large upset occurred here yesterday,
witnessed by an overflow crowd that was limited to just more than
60,000 because of stadium construction.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Aggies outplayed No. 2-ranked Nebraska for more than
three quarters, built a three-touchdown lead, and then had to
survive potential disaster in an eventual 28-21 victory.
</P>
<P>
   They've been playing football at A&AMP;M for more than 100 years.
Maybe it was the biggest win ever. Certainly it was the biggest win
in the R.C. Slocum era. For years, Slocum critics have always had a
good point _ couldn't win the big one. Like hadn't beaten a Top 10
team since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If Slocum had really been prepared, he would have walked into
the postgame media conference with an elephant on a leash. ``I just
removed this thing from my back,'' he could have announced.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a jubilant Slocum did a verbal ramble, before finally
admitting this was a victory that ``takes away some of the things
we keep getting hammered with.'' Later, Slocum added, ``I guess now
it can be said we won a lot of games, and also won one big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lighten up, R.C. Your load just did.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to A&AMP;M senior tight end Dan Campbell to correctly give
the score, and he wasn't necessarily talking about 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the kind of win dearly needed around here,'' Campbell
said. ``All we've ever heard is A&AMP;M can't win the big game and
coach Slocum can't coach the big game. That constant negative
reminder was always there. Now it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, for one blue-skies-up-above afternoon in Maroonland, there
was no more reminder. It had been flushed by the performance of the
18th-ranked Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing part was how A&AMP;M dominated most of the 60 minutes.
They hit Nebraska, coming in with a 19-game winning streak, where
the Cornhuskers had no answer _ a strong defense that stopped the
option, and a running game that blistered the heart of the famed
``Blackshirts'' defense.
</P>
<P>
   There is no rest stop against a Nebraska, however. Out of
options, so to speak, the Huskers went upstairs with quarterback
Bobby Newcombe, and caused late panic among the Kyle Field
faithful. It took a midfield interception by nickel-back Sedrick
Curry with 59 seconds left to assure the Aggies of victory.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M had come into the game labeled an offensive wasteland, and
rightfully so, based on the season's first five games. For those
suffering such an offensive disease, the Nebraska defense is not
the unit that normally provides a cure-all.
</P>
<P>
   But here came the Aggies, stunning the Huskers with two big-play
strikes in the first half. Quarterback Randy McCown evaded a rush,
tiptoed to the line of scrimmage and then fired a strike to
receiver Chris Taylor, whose pattern had taken him east-west. Once,
however, Taylor made the grab at the A&AMP;M 42, he headed due north
for the end zone. The 81-yard TD play, longest by air of the season
for the Aggies, made it 7-0 on A&AMP;M's second possession.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a 7-7 tie in the second quarter, freshman fullback
Ja'Mar Toombs suddenly bolted 71 yards up the middle, carrying to
the Nebraska 1. That set up a TD, and set up Toombs as the Aggies'
most pleasant surprise of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In need of removing this big load of criticism about big-game
failures, the Aggies turned to a big load. Toombs checks in at 260
pounds. He made good use of bulk, rolling up 110 yards on 10
carries, to bookend the 124 yards on 32 carries by workhorse
tailback Dante Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Toombs, who had carried only nine times all season, also blasted
in from the 3-yard line on third-and-goal on the first play of the
fourth quarter. A&AMP;M not having to settle for a field goal, instead
taking a 28-7 lead, would be critical later, as Nebraska tried to
rally.
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, A&AMP;M won without tricks or smoke and mirrors. The
Aggies played their game and then took the Huskers out of their
game.
</P>
<P>
   And to the victors ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, according to Slocum, there has been this one particular
critic bombarding him lately with nasty mail. ``I hope,'' said
R.C., ``that he has to eat himself a bucket-load of crow on Monday
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   But the guy will certainly have plenty of company among the
multitude who thought A&AMP;M had no prayer yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
