<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NEBRASK     10-10 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-NEBRASKA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M ROCKS NO. 2 NEBRASKA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jimmy Burch 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Surrounded by a sea of maroon-clad
towel wavers, Texas A&AMP;M tight end Dan Campbell wept openly as he
watched coach R.C. Slocum ride triumphantly toward the dressing
room on the shoulders of two offensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell hugged Donna Watson as he soaked in the significance of
yesterday's 28-21 upset of No. 2 Nebraska, marking the
highest-ranked team A&AMP;M has defeated in the 104-year history of the
school's football program.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, mother of a former A&AMP;M assistant coach who died in a
Sept. 26 car accident, said she wished her late son, Jim, could
have seen yesterday's defining moment of the Slocum era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her he did see this one, only from a better place. And
I knew he was smiling,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Smiles were the order of the day in Kyle Field, where the
18th-ranked Aggies (5-1, 2-0) rocked Nebraska (5-1, 1-1) with a
flurry of big plays and ended the Cornhuskers' 19-game winning
streak, the nation's longest. It marked A&AMP;M's first victory over a
Top 10 opponent in 11 meetings, dating to a 17-13 upset of No. 8
Houston in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, you get tired of hearing how we can't get over
the hump and win a big game,'' said tailback Dante Hall, who rushed
for a game-high 113 yards and a touchdown. ``I'm so glad to finally
get a positive after so many negatives. The monkey is finally off
our back, but we've got to keep it off. We can't let it climb back
on.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M sent the monkey packing with five game-turning plays, all of
them integral to building a 28-7 lead and then holding off a
spirited Nebraska comeback in the final 14:57. The first came when
quarterback Randy McCown connected with reserve receiver Chris
Taylor on an 81-yard touchdown strike. The reception, Taylor's
first of the season, converted a third-and-25 and gave the Aggies a
7-0 lead they would never relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   Pivotal Play No. 2 in the Aggies' five-step program came in the
second quarter when freshman fullback Ja'Mar Toombs (10 carries,
110 yards, one TD) broke a blast off left guard for 71 yards to the
Huskers' 1-yard line. Hall scored on the next snap, sending the
Aggies to the locker room with a 14-7 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense flows so hard, they flow themselves right into
plays and right out of plays,'' Hall said, explaining how the
Aggies managed their longest pass (81 yards), longest run (71
yards) and longest quarterback scramble (33 yards) of the season
against the Nebraska defense. ``When they overpursue, you've got to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCown caught the Cornhuskers flowing the wrong way in the third
quarter, ducking the pass rush and scrambling 33 yards to the
Cornhuskers' 7-yard line. Three plays later, Toombs burrowed in
from 3 yards out to give the Aggies a 28-7 advantage and cap an
86-yard march.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of a third-quarter defensive touchdown, when
A&AMP;M's Warrick Holdman recovered a fumble in the Nebraska end zone
after a sack by teammate Ron Edwards, the Aggies seemed destined to
deliver a lopsided knockout punch. But the Cornhuskers rallied
behind quarterback Bobby Newcombe, who threw for 145 of his
career-high 204 passing yards in the final quarter, setting up two
touchdowns in a four-minute stretch.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Nebraska took possession for the final time, with
2:00 remaining, A&AMP;M's lead had withered to 28-21 and the Aggies
were in dire need of a defensive stop. They got it with 51 seconds
remaining when cornerback Sedrick Curry hugged a Newcombe pass to
his chest before sliding to the turf at the Nebraska 48.
</P>
<P>
   The game-clinching interception marked the fifth and final big
play that swung the game in the Aggies' direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't so much dominant as we were opportunistic,'' said
A&AMP;M offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe, whose team picked up
185 of its 352 yards on three pivotal snaps. ``We made some big
plays and got the crowd into it. That really helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska players concurred after struggling to hear signals in
front of a standing-room only crowd of 60,798 that A&AMP;M safety Rich
Coady described as ``so loud, we had trouble hearing ourselves
think.''
</P>
<P>
   As he headed off the field following his postgame hug with
Watson, Campbell was stopped by Nebraska defensive end Chad Kelsay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Y'all are for real at home,''' said Campbell, a
Glen Rose native. ``That was very uplifting. It's the first time
I've felt like we've got some respect from a team like this. We
didn't get lucky. We beat those guys and they acknowledged it. That
meant a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It meant enough to bring tears of joy to lots of maroon-clad
folks in Kyle Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
