<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA LOSES KING OF ITS BALD EAGLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was known simply as JD _ and he was the king of bald eagles
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, he was the longest-lived male bird of his kind in the
state. He fathered more eaglets than any other Arizona eagle. And
he amazed scientists with his calm regard as they banded his brood
for research.
</P>
<P>
   Now wildlife officials are mourning his death. This unique eagle
died recently, either because of natural causes or from wounds
inflicted by another bird, possibly an eagle.
</P>
<P>
   JD lived nearly twice the average lifespan of desert-nesting
bald eagles in the wild. His twin sister, known simply as the Alamo
Lake female, now reigns as Arizona's longest-lived bald eagle in
the wild.
</P>
<P>
   JD, who lived most of the past two decades near Saguaro Lake,
raised 30 eaglets to fledgling age, helping boost the population of
the national symbol in Arizona from 20 in 1979 to 72 today.
</P>
<P>
   This more than tripling of the population helped enable
biologists in 1995 to upgrade the bald eagles' chances of survival.
</P>
<P>
   But JD also experienced the encroachment of people into the
eagles' most successful feeding territories, along the Salt, Verde
and Agua Fria rivers closest to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest threat eagles have in Arizona is the increasing
human population right in their back yard,'' said Greg Beatty, bald
eagle management coordinator for the Arizona Game and Fish
Department.
</P>
<P>
   JD, for example, moved his nest several years ago from near the
Salt River to a more distant location, probably because of the
increasing number of tubers, boaters and other recreation
enthusiasts, Beatty said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, bald eagle nest sites are threatened by proposed
resort developments along the north end of Lake Pleasant and along
the Verde River near the community of Rio Verde, Beatty said.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of eagle numbers in Arizona is attributed, in part, to
round-the-clock guards posted near many of the state's bald eagle
nests. These ``nest watchers,'' mostly college students, camp for
up to six months in remote areas to prevent eagles from being shot
or harassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, it's amazing that the young ever hatched,'' said
Bob Witzeman of the Maricopa Audubon Society, which helped fund
some of the first nest-watch positions. The program now is funded
by the Arizona Lottery, federal agencies, tribes and donations from
firms such as the Salt River Project.
</P>
<P>
   JD was found flopping around near a Saguaro Lake cove by a hiker
on Sept. 12. By the time Mark Weise, Game and Fish wildlife
manager, arrived, JD was dead.
</P>
<P>
   It was along the Verde River, north of the Beeline Highway, that
JD hatched in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one could have expected how many biologists' lives he would
touch or how many boaters and other recreationists would crane
their necks upwards to see him fly overhead,'' Beatty said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other bald eagles born in Arizona, JD probably migrated
during his first few years to the northern Rockies. Young Arizona
eagles have been traced as far as Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But, usually after four to six years, they come home to breed.
</P>
<P>
   JD was a good daddy from the start, taking over the incubation
duties at the nest of another eagle that died near Saguaro Lake.
After that, he paired with several female eagles, raising 30
eaglets to the point where they could fly and survive on their own.
Five of them now have nests of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, bald eagles were reclassified under the federal
Endangered Species Act from ``endangered,'' meaning on the verge of
extinction, to ``threatened,'' meaning their numbers are still low,
but not critically so.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty said researchers learned more from JD than from any other
bald eagle in Arizona, tracing his habits year-round.
</P>
<P>
   When researchers annually invaded JD's nest to band and identify
his young, JD would simply move to a nearby perch, while other
eagles screeched with anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a cool cucumber. He was wise. He was hip,'' Beatty
said.
</P>
<P>
   The next-oldest male, which nests along Tonto Creek, north of
Roosevelt Lake, is 15. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
