<HEADLINE>
KINGS DEFENSEMAN WILL PLAY IN FINLAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ Unsigned defenseman Aki Berg played Saturday
in Finland, meaning he is officially out of the Los Angeles Kings'
picture for this season.
</P>
<P>
   League rules stipulate that because he played in the game after
the start of the NHL's regular season, the 21-year-old Berg would
have to clear waivers to rejoin the Kings if the two sides were
agree to contract terms. It is nearly certain Berg, chosen third in
the 1995 draft, would be claimed by another NHL team if the Kings
waived him, which they would not risk doing.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are believed to have offered Berg a one-year contract
worth $625,000 and a three-year deal worth an average of $700,000 a
season. Berg's agent, Larry Kelly, said his client would not sign
for less than the $825,000 he earned last season in base salary and
a portion of the $1 million bonus he received when he first signed
with the Kings in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's there for the year,'' Kelly said. ``Probably two years,
at least. I don't understand the (Kings') approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Berg's decision to play in his native country, Kelly said,
``Rather than be typecast as a stay-at-home defenseman (with the
Kings), he's going to play for his club team (TPS, in the Finnish
league) and his national team and develop into the player he feels
he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fiset's sorrow: Kings goalie Stephane Fiset had more on his
mind this week than hockey. He was hit hard by the news of Stephane
Morin's death during a game Tuesday in Germany. Morin, 29, who
apparently died of a heart attack, was a former NHL and Ice Dogs
player and Fiset's roommate when the two were in the Quebec
Nordiques' organization in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   When he learned of Morin's death, the 28-year-old Fiset said,
``I was depressed. You don't know what to do. When that happens,
you don't know what to say. He was playing hockey all his life. You
don't expect that. You have to live your life every day. When I
heard about that, I grabbed my daughter (Karolane, 5) and kissed
her. You never know what's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset said he and his French-Canadian teammates, all of whom
knew Morin, are planning to assist in the formation of a foundation
for Morin's 2-year-old son, Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Kings general manager Dave Taylor said he is
waiting to finalize a contract extension for coach Larry Robinson,
whose current deal expires after the season.... Former Colorado
coach Marc Crawford worked the Kings game for Hockey Night in
Canada. Ex-Kings goalie Kelly Hrudey, who retired after playing in
San Jose, was scheduled to work the game but instead was in Calgary
with his 6-year-old daughter, who is ill.... Even though the Kings
finished seven points ahead of Edmonton in last year's standings,
the Oilers dominated the season series 4-1, outscoring the Kings
14-8, and shutting them out in the last two meetings.... Before
Saturday, the Kings were 12-11-8 in season openers, the Oilers
10-7-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-10-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
