<HEADLINE>
2 MILLION MILES TO PARADISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a gravely ill father from Casa Grande was
able to take his children to Disneyland, for free, because of Jim
Adameak.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, an ailing woman from Phoenix took the trip
to San Francisco she'd always dreamed about, for free, because of
Jim Adameak.
</P>
<P>
   A Mesa family, the mother very sick, traveled to a family
gathering in Michigan, for free, because of Jim Adameak.
</P>
<P>
   A Tucson grandmother got to see her grandson; a Phoenix woman
visited relatives in Washington, D.C.; a Scottsdale mother watched
her son play baseball in California.
</P>
<P>
   All for free.
</P>
<P>
   All because of Jim Adameak, a 39-year-old working guy whose
actual vocation, it turned out, was working miracles.
</P>
<P>
   A representative from the Dream Foundation in Santa Barbara,
Calif., put me in touch with Adameak last February. Jim and his
family had only been in Phoenix for about a year. They'd moved from
Michigan after Jim got a job driving a truck. Within a few months,
he was diagnosed with a rare form of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a better chance of winning the lottery than of getting
this,'' he told me. ``The doctors tell me it was bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, then added, ``Maybe, but a guy like me, with a family
like mine, I figure I've had a lot more good luck than bad.'' &QL; 
DREAM OF 1 LAST TRIP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Foundation helps terminally ill adults with vacations
they can no longer afford. Years earlier, the Adameaks had been to
Hawaii. Their youngest child had been conceived there.
</P>
<P>
   Jim thought of the islands as paradise. He wanted to go back one
last time with his wife, Kathy, his daughter, Sammi Jo, and his
son, Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Foundation (805-564-2131) makes such trips possible by
collecting donated frequent-flier miles for United Airlines. A
family of four needs an average of about 100,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   After Jim's story appeared in ``The Arizona Republic,'' people
touched by his story quickly donated the miles he needed. And kept
donating, and donating.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, more than 2 million frequent-flier miles had been
contributed. And, because the donated miles don't expire, other
families still are being helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' the foundation's Steven Sharpe told me
Friday. ``Because of Jim, we've been able to help about 20 families
fulfill their dreams. Imagine that.''
</P>
<P>
   People offered hotel accommodations, condos, meals, tours,
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were overwhelmed by the generosity of the people out
there,'' Sharpe said.
</P>
<P>
   A terminally ill Mesa woman was able to take her family to the
beach near Carmel, for free, because of Jim Adameak.
</P>
<P>
   A woman from Apache Junction was reunited with her son and
daughter, for free, because of Jim Adameak.
</P>
<P>
   A Chandler mother and her family went to San Diego's Sea World,
for free, because of Jim Adameak. &QL; 
`I FEEL VERY LUCKY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, the Adameaks went to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful time,'' Kathy Adameak told me Friday. ``It
was difficult, but we loved it. And it's even better knowing other
people were helped. Jim would love to know that. He does know it, I
suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, Jim died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very lucky to have been around such a great guy for as
long as we had together,'' Kathy said. ``We got to say everything
we needed to say. To take care of the important things. It wasn't
enough, of course, but I still feel lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim asked that his body be cremated and his remains be scattered
in Hawaii. Not because it's paradise, though. He knows the real
thing by now.
</P>
<P>
   He knew all along.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I spoke with Adameak, I asked about his illness
and his attitude, about Hawaii, about paradise. There was a TV
blaring in the background, a dog barking and a little boy saying,
``Dad. Dad. Dad'' while we tried to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Adameak laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradise,'' he said, ``is everyday life.'' &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
