<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ CALMLY PULLS THE YANKEES OUT OF A HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.Y.)  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Yankees spent recent years carefully piecing
together the juggernaut that won 114 games this summer, but the
player responsible for winning their most important game to date
washed up on a sliver of island aboard a leaky boat last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez, the defector from Cuba, shut out the
Cleveland Indians into the eighth inning Saturday night as the
Yankees won, 4-0, and fought back to even the four-of-seven-game
American League Championship Series with Cleveland at two games
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill hammered a first-inning home run off the Indians'
starter, Dwight Gooden, and set up the other rally for the Yankees,
whose collective slump continued. They scored their four runs on
just four hits, lowering their batting average for the series to
.194. But they nonetheless brightened the mood of their principal
owner, George Steinbrenner, who gave understated pep talks to
several players in the clubhouse before Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are back in control of this series: David Wells,
their ace, will pitch in Game 5 on Sunday afternoon, against the
Indians' Chad Ogea, and then both teams will return to New York for
at least one more game, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando and Livan Hernandez are half brothers, with the same
father and different mothers, but they both got the big-game gene.
Livan, a pitcher with the Florida Marlins, was the World Series'
most valuable player last year, winning two games against the
Indians. Orlando took the ball Saturday night in the most important
game of the Yankees' season: one loss would leave them on the brink
of playoff defeat and probable off-season chaos, as the front
office tried to figure out why a team that played almost perfectly
in the regular season had been beaten by Cleveland once again.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez carried himself this weekend as if there was no
possibility he would lose. Relaxed and smiling perpetually when
speaking with reporters on Friday (he begins all his responses with
the word bueno _ good) Hernandez repeatedly referred to his escape
from Cuba as he put his Game 4 start in perspective: after what he
had survived, a journey on a leaking boat with little food or water
in a sea known to be a favored shark hangout, why would a baseball
game bother him? No big deal. Bueno, no problema.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez marched to the mound for the first inning, then stood
at the rubber and paced off five small steps to locate his landing
area for his front leg. He was ready to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had one great moment of anxiousness, in the first
inning, when the heart of every Yankees' player and fan raced. Omar
Vizquel singled and stole second, and with two out, Manny Ramirez
coaxed a walk from Hernandez, who initially was having trouble
controlling his sidearm slider. Jim Thome was next, 24 hours
removed from his two-homer performance in Game 3, in a situation
that Yankees manager Joe Torre feared. If Hernandez was going to
run into trouble, Torre thought, it would be in the first few
innings, when he was trying to find his command after not pitching
for 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez fell behind Thome, three balls and one strike. The
slugger then swung viciously through a fastball without making
contact, for a full count. Hernandez threw a change-up, but the
pitch drifted into Thome's danger zone. Thome smacked it with an
uppercut, launching the ball toward the right field seats on a
parabolic trajectory, like so many home runs. The 44,981 patrons
stood to follow the flight, roaring.
</P>
<P>
   But Thome had made contact near the end of his bat, and O'Neill
moved back to the warning track and caught the ball just in front
of the wall, the Yankees' slim 1-0 margin intact.
</P>
<P>
   With their offense sputtering, the Yankees had needed a quick
lift from somebody, some early inning propulsion to take pressure
off everybody. Thirteen pitches into the game, O'Neill waited on a
low curveball from Gooden and golfed it into the right field
stands.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' offense did not exactly break out after O'Neill's
home run; they would collect just four hits all night, and have
just 26 in the first four games of the series. But O'Neill's homer
did seem to apply pressure to Gooden, who pitched tentatively
thereafter and set up the Yankees' fourth-inning rally himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gooden walked O'Neill on six pitches to lead off, then walked
Bernie Williams as Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove changed his
posture uncomfortably in the dugout. Chili Davis then leaned on a
curveball and punched it into the left field corner for what turned
out to be a ground-rule double; O'Neill scored the Yankees' second
run.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez then lifted a high fly to center, of medium depth,
and Williams retreated to third to tag up. But Kenny Lofton,
Cleveland's center fielder, fumbled the ball as he removed it from
his glove, and the second base umpire, Jim McKean, ruled no catch.
Williams trotted home, uncontested, the Yankees' lead increasing to
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   As Torre had predicted, Hernandez's command improved as the
night went along. In a loss to Cleveland in July, Hernandez had
stubbornly refused to pitch inside to left-handed hitters, but
Saturday evening he jammed them repeatedly, knocking them back off
the plate before finishing them by flopping change-ups low and
away.
</P>
<P>
   A single and a hit batsmen in the sixth gave Cleveland two on
and one out, with Manny Ramirez and Thome due to bat. But Hernandez
blew a fastball past Ramirez for strike three when Ramirez clearly
was anticipating a breaking ball. Then, with a full count on Thome,
Hernandez flipped a changeup and Thome swung over the top, ending
the inning. Hernandez left the game in the eighth, having allowed
just three hits and two walks, striking out six.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's performance gives Torre some options to ponder if
this series extends to seven games. Andy Pettitte, who gave up four
home runs in four and two-thirds innings in Game 3, is scheduled to
pitch in Game 7, but Torre has said in the past that he is
comfortable using Hernandez on three days of rest because he is in
such great condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
