<SLUG> BC-COPTERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS COPTERS CROWD SKY, ZOOM IN ON TRAGEDY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   News helicopters are standard scenery in Phoenix skies, battling
for airspace over tragedies, their high-tech eyes offering
close-ups of carnage to television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the choppers have flown in Arizona for decades, they've
never done so in such numbers or with such fervor. There are now
five choppers in Phoenix, up from three as little as three years
ago, and they are in the air more now than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of news helicopters, the crews looked for
beautiful views of canyons, wildlife and sunsets to offset the
day's edgier coverage. Now the helicopters speed through the skies
to capture excitement for the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly the playthings of a few big-city stations, the copters
have whup-whupped into TV markets across the country. Tucson, the
No. 78 market, just got its first helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   And Phoenix, the nation's No. 17 market, is rivaling No. 2 Los
Angeles, which has seven media choppers.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures helicopters capture are ratings gold. The pilots
become local celebrities and folk heroes, rescuing motorists from
flooded washes and plucking people off mountaintops.
</P>
<P>
   But all that hardware in the sky is a bit unsettling for police
and fire crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can imagine, it looked like ``Apocalypse Now'' when you
had these five helicopters coming in on you,'' said Bob Kahn,
battalion chief for the Phoenix Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   One news pilot has already died in this decade. And police
departments worry that the squadron of helicopters over a touchy
scene will one day get an officer killed.
</P>
<P>
   There are other questions about copter coverage, too. While
debate rages on television content, news choppers allow stations to
air live close-up dramas whose unscripted endings can be brutally
violent.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters also tempt stations to cover marginal news stories,
often with threadbare information.
</P>
<P>
   And it tempts them to turn an all-too-common tragedy, such as a
child drowning or fatal car wreck, into the top story on the
evening news.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the questions about news by copter, TV managers _
and TV viewers _ seem to love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fascination with live news events,'' said Doug
Barnard, the news director at Channel 10 (KSAZ), Phoenix's Fox
network affiliate. ``There is no better way to capture a lot of
those things than by helicopter.'' &QL; 
6 MINUTES TILL AIR TIME
</P>
<P>
   It's 4:54 p.m. on a warm monsoon day and a baby girl has fallen
into a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 3's Bruce Haffner is flying 300 feet in the air when he
hears about the drowning from his station's assignment desk.
</P>
<P>
   It's six minutes before the start of ``Good Evening Arizona,''
the city's most popular 5 p.m. newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner's headset, as familiar to viewers as his array of
baseball caps, is crackling with chatter. He monitors police
scanners, airport tower traffic, the voices of his directors at the
station, and other TV and radio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   As Haffner heads to the drowning, a familiar voice cuts through
the chatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out here,'' says Rick Crabbs, the pilot of SkyFox 10, who
has made it to the north Phoenix house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it good?'' Haffner asks, meaning, is it a real drowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Crabbs says flatly.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner gets to the scene and finds room to hover west of the
house.
</P>
<P>
   Cameraman Hilton Metzner cranks open the helicopter door,
letting in a blast of hot air. He hoists a large camera and gets
tight shots of the glistening pool in the back yard and the
rescuers in front.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopters from Channel 3 and 10 are soon joined by those
from Channel 5, Channel 12 and Channel 15. Channel 12's helicopter
circles around the other four. It's an older helicopter and doesn't
have enough power to hover.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers don't bother to look up. Five helicopters flying in a
3-square-mile area is a sight to which they're accustomed.
</P>
<P>
   Around 5:07 p.m., Channel 3 anchor Patti Kirkpatrick tells
viewers about the drowning, using the phrase, ``This just in . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   Cut to Haffner, who uses the casual Chuck Yeager tones of a
pilot to say what he knows by looking out his window and
deciphering the scanner traffic: A 19-month-old girl has fallen
into a backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can see, paramedics are about to transport her,''
Haffner says.
</P>
<P>
   Off the air, Haffner considers the implications of what he's
doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I look at us and think we're a bunch of sharks,''
Haffner says, ``but think of that one family watching that and it
makes them get a pool fence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your shot is live,'' someone says in Haffner's headphones as
the girl is wheeled out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   The medical helicopter takes off, flying below the five news
choppers. One follows it to the hospital. &QL; 
FIGHTING TO BE 1ST
</P>
<P>
   The five stations in Phoenix are vying for viewers. And they'll
try anything and everything.
</P>
<P>
   One station is warm and fuzzy. Another offers ``Extreme Video.''
One station cut its 10 p.m. newscast to five minutes so it could
run ``Seinfeld.'' Another dumped its 6 p.m. show for ``Judge
Judy.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition extends skyward. Each of the five helicopters
fights to be first and to maneuver into the best vantage point at
police and fire scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, to a layperson it would look like an accident waiting
to happen,'' said Colin Williams, public information officer with
the Rural/Metro Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   One pilot has already lost his life covering the news, though it
wasn't due to the number of helicopters in the sky. On July 5,
1991, Mike Nuetzman, a helicopter pilot for radio station KTAR-AM,
was apparently spooked by a bottle rocket that flashed by him as he
flew low. He lost control and crashed just before he was to deliver
a traffic report.
</P>
<P>
   KTAR has since ditched its helicopter and uses a fixed-wing
airplane, flying at high altitude, for its traffic reports.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, newspapers also take to the skies, but mostly
for extraordinary events or aerial shots.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots don't forget the danger they face clipping through the
skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very respectful of Mother Nature,'' Haffner said.
</P>
<P>
   That respect has caused the pilots to sacrifice some of their
competitive instincts so they don't crash into each other.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots share a radio frequency and information, letting each
other know where they're going and which way they're approaching a
scene. They also tell the same to the officers and paramedics in
the air and on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive atmosphere until we get to the
scene,'' said Jerry Clifton, pilot for NewsHawk 5 (KPHO). ``Then,
everybody's life depends on everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   An incident in Tucson shows the potential for disaster when
communication between TV stations and authorities breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson station's KOLD-TV had had a helicopter just weeks when it
was sent to a June school bus accident and landed on a dirt road,
blocking the path of an ambulance carrying injured students. The
ambulance was delayed for about two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot received only indirect messages from authorities on
the ground and thought he had permission to land on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no malice on anyone's behalf,'' said Capt. George
Heaney of the Tucson Fire Department.``It was strictly a
miscommunication.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson station is working with the Fire Department to create
a way to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   But even when pilots and officials on the ground are talking to
each other, situations can get sticky. If authorities feel the
need, they'll close airspace over a scene.
</P>
<P>
   Fire departments will do so around some hazardous fires, fear
ing the pilot will inhale noxious fumes or be blinded. But that's
rare.
</P>
<P>
   Potential problems pop up more often at police scenes.
</P>
<P>
   It's dramatic television when police in SWAT gear surround a
building, weapons drawn. Problem is, the person inside the building
might also be riveted to the live television drama.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a Portland, Ore., officer was killed as he and two
other officers forced their way into a home and faced an immediate
barrage of bullets from the man inside. Police said the man was
monitoring officers' movements on the television news and therefore
knew exactly when to pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   The same scenario has almost happened in Phoenix, said Sgt. Mike
Torres, the Police Department's public information officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had officers compromised,'' Torres said, ``but luckily,
the guy wasn't watching.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV pilots say they would not want to be responsible for
getting an officer hurt or killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to show on TV, where everybody live can see,
where SWAT team members are hiding,'' said Fritz Holly, pilot for
Chopper 15 (KNXV). ``I think it's something that all of us take
into consideration now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Haffner said he wouldn't let a police request keep him from
getting a shot for his station.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to hinder (my job), I'm going to split the
difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has helped. High-tech cameras mean the choppers don't
have to be as intrusive as they once were.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cameras in this town that can stay out of (any)
legal limits and still show the pimple on the end of your nose,''
said Phil Monahan, the cameraman who flies in Sky 12 (KPNX).
</P>
<P>
   When Torres and Detective Mike McCullough, another department
spokesman, ask for the media to back off, which happens at least
several times a year, they usually get compliance, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not been so competitive that they're not listening to
reason,'' Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   But the police spokesmen worry that pilots' reasoning might be
clouded by the drive for ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to use (helicopters) as an enforcement tool and they
try to use it for its marketing value,'' McCullough said.
</P>
<P>
   The news pilots generally get along better with fire and rescue
agencies than with police. And they can offer more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm at a scene and I see a helicopter from a news agency,
I'll ask them if they can assist us,'' said Williams, of
Rural/Metro.
</P>
<P>
   Media helicopter pilots are often glad to help.
</P>
<P>
   They often give firefighters aerial views of brush fires,
letting commanders plan strategies to fight the blazes.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton took a Rural/Metro commander up in Channel 5's helicop
ter during the 1996 Rio fire and credits himself with keeping that
blaze from charring hundreds more acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he (the commander) been driving out there, it would have
been another hour until he realized the magnitude of that thing,''
Clifton said.
</P>
<P>
   Media helicopters can also aid search and rescue missions, fire
agencies say.
</P>
<P>
   Some pilots like helping out with those missions. Others don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a feather in my cap if I find the person,'' said Crabbs,
who recently located the body of a Florida hiker in the
Superstition Mountains east of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner said he would do a rescue only in a life-and-death
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do rescues. We show people doing rescues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, someday he would like to be responsible for
saving someone's life. &QL; 
THE BIG STORY?
</P>
<P>
   A drunk, delirious man is pulled from a canal on a hot August
day and tells paramedics he was trying to rescue a 4-year-old girl
who sank beneath the water.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers have no choice but to believe him and start combing the
canal looking for the 4-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   The phone rings at the Scottsdale Airpark where Mike McDonald,
pilot for Sky 12, waits every weekday for news to call him to his
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end is Colin Williams of Rural/Metro, who tells
McDonald rescuers could use ``an extra pair of eyes in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   It's 4:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald and photographer Phil Monahan dash to the helicopter
and are in the air in less than three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 minutes later, McDonald is over the scene and live on
Channel 12, giving the story to thousands of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know for sure if the person he was trying to rescue
was in the water or out of the water,'' McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, the rest of the helicopters converge, drawn by
the words uttered by the drunk, delirious man.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Crabbs goes live on Channel 10 at 5 p.m. He's covering that
night's Big Story. He tells viewers there is confusion about
whether the drowned person is a child or adult.
</P>
<P>
   Crabbs ends his report saying he typically sees kids swimming in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   By 5:10 p.m., the story gets more detailed. Haffner tells
Channel 3 viewers, ``There's a 4-year-old wearing a rainbow-colored
swimsuit.'' He says officials are bringing in equipment to drag the
canal.
</P>
<P>
   Crabbs wraps up his second live report with some quick banter
with anchor John Hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder what a 4-year-old is doing near a canal,'' Hook
says disapprovingly.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of rescuers' radio chatter starts changing.
</P>
<P>
   They start to doubt the story about the 4-year-old in the canal.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:30 p.m., all the pilots go live telling viewers it appears
the call is bogus.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, most rescue units are sent off the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear it was an erroneous call?'' Haffner says, over the
pilots' common radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing,'' McDonald says. ``But it's a shame we
wasted all this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, someone puts a note on the bulletin board of
Channel 12 giving kudos to McDonald for being the first to beam the
bogus story to Phoenix television viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you spend big bucks for the helicopter. You want to
be first,'' McDonald says that day. &QL; 
CARTOONS TO SUICIDE
</P>
<P>
   In several instances in other markets, helicopters have shown up
in the middle of a drama and started beaming back a live show that
ended with a violent death.
</P>
<P>
   It happened that way in California this summer when a man drove
along a Los Angeles freeway, threw firebombs at passing cars, set
his car and himself on fire, displayed a banner protesting HMOs,
and then killed himself with a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Some LA stations interrupted cartoons to broadcast the suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Petty was flying for KNBC, Channel 4 in LA, that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He said he yelled at his cameraman to zoom out when he realized
the man was going to shoot himself. But he was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way we could tell he was progressing into killing
himself,'' Petty said. ``As soon as that man did kill himself, we
never went back to the body, never went anywhere near it.''
</P>
<P>
   The story then became focused on the traffic backup, with the
man's death mentioned in passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll be more sensitive in the future,'' Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident caused debate in television newsrooms. Some
wondered whether news shows should be broadcast with a seven-second
delay. Others said viewers can decide for themselves whether to
watch news with violent potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy on the freeway was very sobering for us,'' said
Jeanine L'Ecuyer, news director for Channel 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could very easily happen to us. A coverable situation
that can get out of hand very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis O'Neill, news director for Channel 3, said he wouldn't
have turned his cameras from the suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are beginning to sense that (tragedy) is going to
happen, folks have already got the choice of turning off the
television or switching it to another channel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most people won't change the channel, however.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, a 10-year-old autistic child climbed a
120-foot electrical tower in Mesa. Five channels beamed his
precarious predicament for nearly 90 full minutes. From his narrow
perch, he waved at the helicopters that captured his peril from
every angle.
</P>
<P>
   He was fingertips away from 230,000 volts of electricity, one
grip from a fatal plummet towards earth.
</P>
<P>
   And he was being watched by about 416,000 viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Stations said they had their hands on the switches, ready to
toggle back to the news anchors or go to an alternate camera shot
if the boy had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   But balancing sensitivity and ratings success means this kind of
situation is a close call.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner said that with four competitors, all armed with
high-tech gadgets, it's in the stations' interest to provide the
best, most compelling video possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you're walking through the living room,'' Haffner said,
``it's the shot that stops you cold in your tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Haffner goes to great lengths to get what he hopes will be the
perfect shot. Sometimes he barks orders to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'mon lightning. Lightning now,'' Haffner said as he got a
shot of an approaching storm.
</P>
<P>
   It was the shot Channel 3 used for the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chopper, thanks for taking us home,'' said a voice in
Haffner's headset. Haffner was done for the day.
</P>
<P>
   It's 6:30, and Haffner was the last pilot to leave the sky,
until the next morning, when the five helicopters would be back in
the air and on the air again.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
