<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE GIRL FALLS FROM STANDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A 4-year-old girl was knocked unconscious when she
fell 18 feet from the North Campus Stadium bleachers Saturday
during the third quarter of Cal State Northridge's 21-7 win against
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN spokesman Ryan Finney said the girl, a Northridge resident
whose name was not available, was transported to Northridge
Hospital Medical Center but is not in critical condition. No other
details were available.
</P>
<P>
   First-aid personnel were quick on the scene and said the girl
lost consciousness for approximately two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear to be anything critical,'' Finney said.
``She came to quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl was in the visitors section of bleachers when she fell
off the north side and landed on the ground. She apparently slipped
between the few feet of space between the floor of the bleachers
and the first bar of the railing.
</P>
<P>
   Three ambulances were called to the scene before she was taken
away.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ah (Yat), my achin' back: The screenwriters for ``Conspiracy
Theory'' should have talked to Montana regarding a plot.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Brian Ah Yat, second in Division I-AA in total
offense, didn't dress for the game despite being labeled as
probable throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, backup Seth Davis got the start.
</P>
<P>
   Ah Yat injured his back a week ago against Portland State and
was termed probable to face CSUN by the media-relations staff
throughout the week. Earlier in the week Montana spokespersons said
Ah Yat had returned to practice, which, in their interpretation,
meant he was on the practice field throwing balls on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things when you watch him throw the ball he
can do it, but we would never play someone who can't protect
himself,'' Montana coach Mick Dennehy said. ``He's at the point
where he can't protect himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A one-time Walter Payton Award candidate, Ah Yat's status, as
you can guess, is unknown for next week's game against Northern
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   __ Special duty: Montana junior Di-Onte Smith, a Grant High
graduate, can play either cornerback or safety, but he's more
valuable to the Grizzlies in another role. Smith is their best
special-teams player.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a year ago he was voted Montana's special-teams player
of the year. And against CSUN, that's where he got his action.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, from Van Nuys, didn't figure in any tackles against the
Matadors but does have five this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Short yardage: Punter Ethan Beck fell five yards shy of the
school record for longest punt but only because the Matadors were
on their own 28. His 72-yard punt in the first quarter one-hopped
into the end zone. Later in the game he booted a 66-yarder....
Montana's Kris Heppner's 60-yard field goal attempt to end the
first half fell short, glancing off the crossbar.... CSUN's men's
basketball team will be at the Northridge Fashion Center Sears
signing autographs today from noon to 3 p.m. Posters and free
Polaroid photos are available, as well as the chance to win $5,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
