<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLS-AZR &LR;      10-10 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY SUPPORT LOOKS SOLID IN ARIZONA POLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't bet on the Arizona Lottery disappearing anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   A new ``Arizona Republic'' poll shows a solid majority of voters
_ 60 percent _ aren't ready to bury Windfall Willy, the Lottery's
plucky prospector, or any other state-sponsored game of chance.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also shows 55 percent of Arizona voters believe
Lottery dollars are a financial boon to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will decide Nov. 3 whether to extend of the life of the
Arizona Lottery to July 1, 2003. If Proposition 304 fails, the
Lottery will expire after June 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 percent of the respondents in ``The Republic'' survey
said they're ready to let the Lottery die.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lottery is doing good,'' Pam Blanche of Glendale said.
``It's free choice, and nobody has to buy the tickets, so I would
vote to keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bill Reid of Sun City West: ``It's an advantage to the
state. As a result of the state benefiting financially, I think the
people benefit financially from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The statewide poll of 811 registered voters, taken Oct. 3-6 for
``The Republic'' by Precision Research Inc., has an error margin of
plus or minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Other major findings:
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three percent of Arizona voters support Proposition 200,
dubbed the Clean Elections Act by supporters. Designed to reduce
the role of special interests in Arizona politics, the measure
provides public funding to candidates who agree to strict
contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Public frustration with lobbyists' influence at the Legislature
apparently is fueling support for the measure. Sixty-eight percent
of Arizona voters polled said lobbyists have too much influence
with state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-one percent support Proposition 300, which requires
authorization of the Food and Drug Administration or Congress
before doctors could prescribe drugs like marijuana and heroin to
seriously or terminally ill patients in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's findings suggest that House Speaker Jeff Groscost,
the state's leading Lottery critic, faces an uphill struggle in
persuading voters to kill the games.
</P>
<P>
   It found support for the Lottery crosses party lines, with 55
percent of Republicans and 66 percent of Democrats saying they will
vote to extend the Lottery's life.
</P>
<P>
   And support for the Lottery comes from those who rarely, if
ever, buy tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one percent of the respondents said they never play the
Arizona Lottery but would vote to extend it, and 56 percent of
those who rarely play the game would also vote to support it. Fully
81 percent of those who play at least once a week said they will
vote to extend it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lotto and the Fantasy Five and Pick 3 are like playing
bingo at the Catholic Church,'' said poll respondent Dorothy Skeen
of Peoria. ``I don't have a problem with those. I think the
Powerball is a waste of our money.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost said Friday he's prepared for a major fight for public
opinion. `We've always known that this is a David and Goliath
struggle,'' he said. ``If we do win, it's with underdog status.''
</P>
<P>
   Groscost is relying heavily on churches, whose leaders view the
Lottery as state-sponsored gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mormon leaders reminded the state's 275,000 members
of the church's opposition to all forms of gambling, including the
Lottery, and urged them to voice their views at the polls on
Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is strictly a grass-roots campaign. There's no organized
campaign buying radio or television time,'' Groscost said. ``The
other side has a lot of money. If they perceive there's a threat,
they'll dump that money in.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those opposed to the Lottery is Helen Gephart of Peoria,
who participated in the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play the Lottery every week, but I think there's a lot of
people who can't afford it who are playing and should not, so maybe
it's better that they do away with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But critics are in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   Only 13 percent in the Arizona Poll said the Lottery has a
negative financial impact on the state, 14 percent said it had no
impact and 18 percent had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mundell, chairman of ``Yes on 304,'' said the results show
voters know Lottery proceeds provide a windfall for state programs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Lottery raised $79 million, including nearly $25
million that went to the state's general fund. Other programs
funded by the Lottery include the Heritage Fund, which received $20
million for historic preservation, state parks and wildlife
projects.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether they thought casino gambling should be banned
in Arizona, 55 percent said no, compared to 37 percent yes. The
remainder were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Most respondents, 60 percent, said they do not think casino
gambling should be extended statewide, beyond Indian reservations.
Thirty-three percent said it should, and 7 percent had no opinion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
