<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-OKLAHOMA-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH TAKES NEW FOOTPATH TO REMAIN UNDEFEATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ It was an increasingly familiar story in front
of 47,589 at Jones Stadium last night _ another opponent ground
underfoot by Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, the evening's key moment featured a fleet red-shirted
hero dashing downfield to ice a 24-17 victory over Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams, the nation's No. 2 rusher? No, it was Red
Raiders linebacker Dorian Pitts.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, who had set up an earlier touchdown with a blocked punt,
raced 53 yards with a Tony Lindsay fumble with 2:53 remaining to
give Tech (6-0, 3-0 Big 12) a 14-point lead that proved
insurmountable _ barely.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (2-3, 1-2) weren't finished. Just 33 seconds later,
they had traveled 58 yards and scored on a pass from Lindsay to
Terrance Richardson to make it a seven-point game again.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they held a command meeting and came up with an odd plan.
Disdaining an onside kick, they kicked deep and turned to their
defense.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Cowboys got the ball back _ at their 35 _ they
had 25 seconds, no timeouts, and no hope.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on a night when their fifth-ranked rushing game managed
131 yards _ exactly half their usual total, the Raiders were saved
by Pitts and a variety of OSU mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among those were 11 penalties for 132 yards.
Additionally, Tech's three touchdowns came off the blocked punt and
two fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   The last of these came with the Cowboys trailing, 17-10, and
facing fourth-and-11 at the Tech 41. As Lindsay scrambled,
desperately looking for a receiver, he was hit by Montae Reagor and
fumbled. Pitts scooped it off the ground and scored easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montae made the play and the ball popped right _ I just had no
choice but to take it in,'' Pitts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of those deals where it gets late, and you check
your hole card,'' said Tech coach Spike Dykes, whose team played
without several injured starters. ``Fortunately, we had one we
could use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great win from stem to stern, but it wasn't always
pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   This was especially true during Tech's fourth-quarter field-goal
drive, which was kept alive by two flagrant OSU penalties _ a punch
thrown by Raymond Cato at Tech tight end Kyle Allamon, and a
face-mask tackle of quarterback Rob Peters by linebacker Troy West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' said Tech receiver Donnie Hart, who caught
two touchdown passes. ``I've never been 6-0 before in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Williams was held to 97 yards on 25 carries, he now has
1,026 yards this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders led, 14-10, at the half despite averaging less than
2 yards per snap and trailing in total yards, 144-53.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys broke from the gate quickly, converting their first
two possessions into 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   A short Tech punt into the wind left OSU needing to march just
51 yards, which it did in 12 plays, with fullback Brian Aikins
scoring from the 1. Another punt gave the Cowboys the ball at the
Tech 48, but the drive was stalled by a penalty and OSU settled for
a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   For the Raiders, matters improved midway through the second
period. Tim Duffie's fumble recovery at the OSU 37 set up a 14-yard
scoring pass from Peters to Hart, and Pitts' blocked kick set up
another collaboration between the pair for 18 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Tech is now 6-0 for the first time since 1976, and the third
time in the school's history. It was Dykes' 75th victory at Tech,
second in school history to Pete Cawthon (1930-1940), who had 76.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
