<SLUG> BC-RACES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNDECIDEDS' MAY BE PIVOTAL IN STATEWIDE RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 and CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Jane Hull has a 25-point lead over Democrat Paul
Johnson in a new ``Arizona Republic'' poll.
</P>
<P>
   But the point spread in other statewide races is not as big, and
their outcomes rest with a sizable number of undecided voters, the
survey found.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a month to go before the Nov. 3 election, Hull
leads Johnson, 52 percent to 27 percent, in the governor's race,
according to the statewide poll of 811 registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Libertarian Kat Gallant registered 2 percent, and Reform Party
candidate Scott Malcomson garnered 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who put an additional $100,000 of his own money into
the campaign Friday, remains confident he can win. The poll was
taken as Johnson attacked Hull at a Sunday night debate for
reputedly trading Arizona water rights for Las Vegas campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   The charge backfired when key elements were proved false. But
Johnson says voters are uncomfortable with the broader implications
of the fact that Hull accepted $31,000 from Las Vegas gaming and
development interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I figured out anything this week, it's that this campaign
began in earnest last Sunday,'' Johnson said. ``This week, good and
bad, is a thousand times different than the last (campaign). The
reality is, it is engaged now. There are a lot of dynamics that
will happen between now and election day.''
</P>
<P>
   With the focus on the governor's race, Johnson said, he will be
able to raise additional issues and force Hull to respond.
</P>
<P>
   And ``my guess is that's not in Mrs. Hull's advantage,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Poll, taken Saturday through Tuesday by Precision
Research Inc. for ``The Republic,'' has an error margin of plus or
minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   It found that Sen. John McCain has a virtually insurmountable
lead over Democratic challenger Ed Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-two percent of those surveyed said they would vote for
McCain, compared to 11 percent for Ranger, a political newcomer.
Reform Party candidate Bob Park and Libertarian John Zajac
registered 3 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   And while Hull has a commanding lead over Johnson, the poll's
findings suggest the outcome of other statewide races rests on a
large contingent of undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for attorney general, Republican Tom McGovern leads
Democrat Janet Napolitano, 36 percent to 28 percent. Libertarian
Thomas Eblen brought up the rear with 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But a third of the voters surveyed said they have not made up
their minds.
</P>
<P>
   That large voting bloc will be the obvious target of both
candidates in the coming weeks, as voters begin to focus on the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is going to be a close race,'' McGovern predicted.
``It will get tighter before it gets wider.''
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano supporters were encouraged by the survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the amount of personal money McGovern has put into his
campaign, his high exposure in the primary and his support from
political insiders, Napolitano is in great shape,'' said Mario
Diaz, her campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he noted, Napolitano still had about half of her
$500,000 campaign war chest to spend on media when the latest
campaign finance reports were filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern's $485,000 campaign included $156,000 of his own money
and was running about $30,000 in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano launched a major TV blitz last week. McGovern
apparently is awaiting results of a GOP fund-raiser on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A sizable number of undecided voters could sway the outcome of
other races, the Arizona Poll found:
</P>
<P>
   In the race for Secretary of State, Republican Betsey Bayless
leads Democrat Art Hamilton, 40 percent to 26 percent. But about a
third of the vote, 34 percent, is undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the Corporation Commission race, 44 percent of the poll
respondents were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Among those with an opinion, Republican Tony West led Democrat
Paul Newman, 33 percent to 22 percent. &QL; 
 &UR; Republic reporter Mike McCloy contributed to this article. &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
